{"title_page": "Janowska concentration camp", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox concentration camp\n| name            = Janowska concentration camp\n| image           = Jewish prisoners forced to work for a Sonderkommando 1005 unit pose next to a bone crushing machine in the Janowska concentration camp.jpg\n| image size      = \n| type            = [[Concentration camp]]\n| caption         = Survivors of the camp's [[Sonderkommando 1005]] unit stand next to a bone crushing machine <small>(taken following the liberation of the camp in 1944)</small> \n| alt             = \n| location map    = Ukraine\n| map alt         = Ukraine\n| coordinates     = {{coord|49|51|15|N|23|59|24|E|region:UA_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| map caption     = Location of Janowska camp in modern Ukraine\n{{location mark|float=center|image=WW2-Holocaust-Poland.PNG |width=226 |x%=69.5 |y%=74.4 |label='''Janowska''' |position=right}}\nLocation of KL Janowska in World War&nbsp;II,<br />south of the [[Belzec]] [[death camp]]\n| location        = Lemberg, [[District of Galicia]], [[General Government]] (formerly Lw\u00f3w, [[Second Polish Republic]]; today [[Lviv]], Ukraine)\n| operated by     = [[SS]]\n| original use    = \n| construction    = \n| in operation    = September 1941 \u2013 November 1943\n| prisoner type   = Jews\n| inmates         = 100,000\n| killed          = 35,000\u201340,000\n| liberated by    = The Red Army\n| notable inmates = \n| notable books   = \n| website         = {{URL|https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/janowska}}\n}}\n'''Janowska concentration camp''' ({{lang-pl|Janowska}}, {{lang-ru|\u042f\u043d\u043e\u0432 or \"Yanov\"}}, {{lang-uk|\u042f\u043d\u0456\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0442\u0430\u0431\u0456\u0440}}) was a [[Nazi concentration camp]] combining elements of labor, transit and [[extermination camp]]s. It was established in September 1941 on the outskirts of Lw\u00f3w in [[Eastern Poland]] / [[Western Ukraine]] (today: [[Lviv]], Ukraine). The camp was named after the nearby street ''Janowska'' in Lw\u00f3w of the interwar [[Second Polish Republic]]. The camp was liquidated in November 1943, with the evidence of mass murder being largely destroyed in the Nazi program of ''[[Sonderaktion 1005]]''. Estimates put the total number of prisoners who passed through the Janowska camp at between 100,000 and 120,000, mostly Polish and Soviet Jews.<ref name=Kerenji>{{cite book |title=Jewish Responses to Persecution: 1942\u20131943 |author=Emil Kerenji |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gXDYBAAAQBAJ&q=Janowska+100%2C000+DAW |year=2014 |isbn=978-1442236271 |pages=69\u201370, 539}}</ref> The number of victims murdered at the camp is estimated at 35,000\u201340,000.\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|Lviv pogroms (1941)}}\nLw\u00f3w ([[Lviv]]) was a multicultural city just before World War&nbsp;II, with a population of 312,231. The city's 157,490 ethnic Poles constituted just over 50 per cent, with Jews at 32 per cent (99,595) and Ukrainians at 16 per cent (49,747).{{sfn|Himka|2011|p=210}} On 28 September 1939, after the [[Invasion of Poland|joint Soviet-German invasion]], the [[USSR]] and [[Nazi Germany]] signed the [[German\u2013Soviet Frontier Treaty]], which assigned about 200,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (77,000&nbsp;sq&nbsp;mi) of Polish territory inhabited by 13.5&nbsp;million people of all nationalities to the Soviet Union. Lviv was then [[Territories of Poland annexed by the Soviet Union|annexed to the Soviet Union]] as part of the [[Ukrainian SSR]].{{sfn|Gross|2002 |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=XKtOr4EXOWwC&pg=PA17 17, 28\u201330]}}\n\nAt the time of the German attack on the Soviet Union in June 1941, about 160,000 Jews lived in the city;{{sfn|Beorn|2018|p=136}} the number had swelled by tens of thousands due to the arrival of Jewish refugees from German-occupied Poland in late 1939.{{sfn|Kulke|2012|p=802}} Lviv was occupied by the [[Wehrmacht]] on 30 June 1941. Jews were press-ganged by the Germans to remove bodies of the victims of the [[NKVD prisoner massacre]]s for which [[Nazi propaganda]] and Ukrainian nationalists blamed the Jews.{{sfn|Himka|2011|p=211}} In the ensuing [[Lviv pogroms (1941)|July pogroms]] and the concurrent [[Einsatzgruppen]] killings, thousands of Jews were murdered.{{sfn|Kulke|2012|p=802}}\n\n==Lw\u00f3w Ghetto==\n{{main|Lw\u00f3w Ghetto}}\nIn early November 1941, the Nazis closed-off northern portions of the city thus forming the [[Lw\u00f3w Ghetto]].<ref name=\"Koonz\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.uvm.edu/~uvmchs/documents/KoonzHilbergLecture_002.pdf |title=SS Man Katzmann's \"Solution of the Jewish Question in the District of Galicia\" |publisher=University of Vermont |journal=The Raul Hilberg Lecture |date=November 2, 2005 |accessdate=January 30, 2015 |author=Claudia Koonz |pages=2, 11, 16\u201318 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205021305/http://www.uvm.edu/~uvmchs/documents/KoonzHilbergLecture_002.pdf |archive-date=February 5, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> During the forced relocation of the Jewish families to the newly created ghetto, German police shot and killed thousands of elderly and sick Jews as they crossed under the rail bridge on Pe\u0142tewna Street (which came to be known as the ''bridge of death'' for the Jews). Several months later, in March 1942, the Nazi police under [[Fritz Katzmann]] began to deport Jews from the ghetto to the [[Belzec extermination camp]]. By August 1942, more than 65,000 Jews from Lw\u00f3w had been sent away aboard [[Holocaust trains]] and killed. In early June 1943, the Germans destroyed and liquidated the ghetto.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Filip Friedman, ''Zag\u0142ada \u017byd\u00f3w lwowskich'' (Extermination of the Jews of Lw\u00f3w) {{OCLC|38706656}}.</ref>\n\n==Labour and transit camp==\nIn addition to the Lw\u00f3w ghetto, in September 1941 the occupation authorities set up a German Armament Works D.A.W. factory (''[[Deutsche Ausr\u00fcstungswerke]]'') in prewar Steinhaus Milling Machines Merchants (''Maszyny m\u0142y\u0144skie - Sprzeda\u017c'') on 134 Janowska Street (Grodecka 10a address),<ref>Jewishgen.org (May 2005), [https://kehilalinks.jewishgen.org/lviv/FramesetSt.html Businesses, Partnerships and Addresses: Steinhaus Milling Machines-Merchants]</ref> in northwestern suburbs of Lw\u00f3w. This factory became a part of a network of factories owned and operated by the SS. The commandant of the camp was ''{{nobreak|SS-Haupsturmf\u00fchrer}}'' Fritz Gebauer. Jews who worked at this factory were used as forced laborers, mainly working in [[carpentry]] and [[metalwork]].\n\nIn October 1941, the Nazis established a concentration camp next to the factory, which housed the forced laborers along with other prisoners. Thousands of Jews from the Lw\u00f3w ghetto were forced to work as [[Slavery|slave]] laborers in this complex. When the Lw\u00f3w ghetto was liquidated by the Nazis, the ghetto's inhabitants who were fit for work were sent to the Janowska camp; the rest were deported to [[Belzec]] for extermination. The concentration camp was guarded by a ''[[Sonderdienst]]'' battalion of the {{nobreak|''SS''-trained}} ''[[Hiwi (volunteer)|Hiwi]]'' guards known as \"[[Trawniki men]]\".<ref name=USHMM1>{{cite web |url=http://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10007397 |title=Trawniki |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |author=Holocaust Encyclopedia |accessdate=July 21, 2011 |id=permission granted to be reused, in whole or in part, on Wikipedia; [[OTRS]] ticket no. 2007071910012533 |quote=Text from USHMM has been released under the [[GFDL]].}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to being a forced-labor camp for Jews, Janowska was a transit camp (''Durchgangslager Janowska'') during the [[Final Solution|mass deportations of Polish Jews to the killing centers]] from across German-occupied southeastern Poland (now western Ukraine) in 1942. Jews underwent a selection process in Janowska camp similar to that used at [[Auschwitz-Birkenau|Auschwitz\u2013Birkenau]] and [[Majdanek]] [[extermination camps]]. Those classified as fit to work remained at Janowska for forced labor. The majority, rejected as unfit for work, were deported to Belzec and killed, or else were shot at the Piaski ravine, located just north of the camp. In the summer and fall of 1942, thousands of Jews (mainly from the Lw\u00f3w ghetto) were deported to Janowska and killed in the Piaski ravine.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe Nazis occasionally allowed small groups of Jews to go to town for daylong leaves of absence.  They would use this temporary freedom to dig up [[Torah]]s that had been hidden in Lw\u00f3w's Jewish cemetery.  The Torahs were then cut into pieces which were hidden under their clothes and smuggled back into the camp.  After the war the various pieces were assembled into a single scroll, the [[Yanov torah]], which is currently in California.<ref>Erwin and Agnes Herman ''The Yanov Torah'' [[Kar-Ben Publishing]] {{ISBN|978-0930494452}} (1985)</ref>\n\n==Liquidation==\n[[File:Site of Janowska Nazi Camp - Lviv, 1944.jpg|thumbnail|right|Soviet [[Extraordinary State Commission]] at the site of mass graves adjoining the camp, 1944.]]\nAhead of the Soviet advance, in November 1943 the new camp commandant ''SS-Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer'' Friedrich Warzok was put in charge of the evacuation of the Janowska inmates to [[Przemy\u015bl]].<ref name=\"Levy\">{{cite book | last = Levy | first = Alan | authorlink = Alan Levy | title = Nazi Hunter: The Wiesenthal File | edition = Revised 2002 | year = 2006 | origyear = 1993 | publisher = Constable & Robinson | location = London | isbn = 978-1-84119-607-7 | ref = harv }}</ref> The Germans attempted to destroy the traces of mass murder during ''[[Sonderaktion 1005]]''. Prisoners were forced to open the mass graves in Lesienicki forest and burn the bodies. On November 19, 1943, the ''Sonderkommando'' inmates staged a revolt against the Nazis and attempted a mass escape. A few succeeded, but most were recaptured and killed. The SS and their local auxiliaries murdered at least 6,000 Jews who had survived the uprising killings at Janowska, as well as Jews in other forced labor camps in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]], at the time of the camps' liquidation.<ref>{{cite web|author=USHMM |url=https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/janowska |title=Janowska| encyclopedia=[[Holocaust Encyclopedia]] |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |accessdate=2018-11-18 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Soviet [[Extraordinary State Commission]] determined that over 200,000 people were killed in Janowska in the course of the camp operation. The ashes mixed with crushed bones were buried to a depth of six feet in various places.<ref name=\"HEART\" /> {{Interlanguage link multi|Leon Weliczker Wells|de}} told the Commission that between June 6 and November 20, 1943 his \"team burned more than 310,000 bodies\" including 170,000 in the immediate vicinity of the camp and another 140,000 or more in the Lysynychi area of eastern Lw\u00f3w.<ref>[[Avner Falk]] ''Anti-semitism: A History and Psychoanalysis of Contemporary Hatred'' [[ABC-CLIO]] {{ISBN|9780313353840}} (2008) p. 191</ref>  Weliczker repeated the claim of \"a few hundred thousand\" at [[Adolf Eichmann]]'s trial in 1961.<ref>[http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/people/e/eichmann-adolf/transcripts/Sessions/Session-023-03.html \"The Trial of Adolf Eichmann\"] Session #23 2 May 1961</ref> Weliczker also described his work as part of the Sonderaktion 1005 in his book ''Death Brigade''.\n\nJanowska served as a Soviet prison camp after its liberation.<ref name=\"HEART\">{{cite web | url=http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/othercamps/janowska.html | title=The Soviet Special Commission | publisher=Holocaust Education & Archive Research Team | work=Janowska \u2013 Lvov | year=2007 | accessdate=January 28, 2018 | author=Carmelo Lisciotto, H.E.A.R.T}}</ref><br />\n\n==Tango of Death==\n[[File:Janowska Nazi camp orchestra.jpg|thumb|Tango of Death]]\nIn the Janowska concentration camp, the Nazis conducted torture and executions to music. The Orchestra members, who were prisoners, played one and the same tune, Tango of Death. Lviv National Philharmonic Orchestra professor Shtriks, opera conductor Mund and other famous Jewish musicians were among the members. \n\nDuring hanging the Nazis ordered the orchestra to play [[tango]], and during tortures the musicians had to play [[foxtrot]]. Some evenings the orchestra musicians were made to play under the camp commander\u2019s windows for hours on end.\n\nOn the eve of Lviv\u2019s liberation German Nazis ordered 40 orchestra musicians to form a circle. The security ringed the musicians tightly and ordered them to play. First the orchestra conductor, Mund, was executed. Then the commandant ordered the musicians to come to the center of the circle one by one, put their instrument onto the ground and strip naked, after which they were killed by a headshot.\n\nA photo of the orchestra players was one of the incriminating documents at the [[Nuremberg trials]].\n\nJacob Mund\u2019s story is described in the book called [https://www.amazon.com/Tango-Death-Story-Holocaust-Survivors/dp/B085HHMGMT/ Tango of Death].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awesomegang.com/tango-of-death-a-true-story-of-a-holocaust-survivor/|title=Tango of Death: A True Story of a Holocaust Survivor|last=O'Hare|first=Vinny|website=awesomegang.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Notable inmates==<!-- Please respect alphabetical order -->\n* [[Maurycy Allerhand]], lawyer\n* [[Adolf Beck (physiologist)|Adolf Beck]], physiologist\n* [[Enrico Ciantelli]] Italian Military Internee, lawyer\n* [[Janina Altman|Janina Hescheles]] (then Altman), Polish-Israeli chemist and writer \n* Rabbi [[Yisroel Spira]], Grand Rabbi of Bluzev ([[B\u0142a\u017cowa]])\n* [[Emanuel Szlechter]], screenwriter and lyricist\n* [[William Ungar]], founder of the [[National Envelope Corporation]]\n* [[Debora Vogel]], philosopher and poet\n* [[Simon Wiesenthal]], [[Nazi hunter]]\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=21em}}\n* [[Kaiser Wilhelm Institute of Anthropology, Human Heredity, and Eugenics]]\n* [[List of Nazi concentration camps]]\n* [[Nazi concentration camps]]\n{{div col end}}\n{{Portal bar|Genocide|Germany|Poland|World War II}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}} \n*[https://www.amazon.com/Tango-Death-Story-Holocaust-Survivors/dp/B085HHMGMT/ Tango of Death]. A True Story of Holocaust Survivors \u2014 Mr. Mintz Publishing, Mikhail Baranovskiy, 2020. - ISBN 979-8620147014\n*{{cite book |last1=Beorn |first1=Waitman Wade |author-link = Waitman Wade Beorn|title=The Holocaust in Eastern Europe: At the Epicenter of the Final Solution |date=2018 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=978-1474232227 |ref = harv}}\n* Filip Friedman, ''Zag\u0142ada \u017byd\u00f3w Lwowskich'' (Extermination of the Jews of Lw\u00f3w) \u2013 [https://web.archive.org/web/20101106061357/http://www.mankurty.com/fridpl.html online in Polish, Ukrainian and Russian]\n*{{cite book |authorlink=Jan T. Gross |last=Gross |first=Jan Tomasz |year=2002 |title=Revolution from Abroad: The Soviet Conquest of Poland's Western Ukraine and Western Belorussia |location=Princeton, [[New Jersey|NJ]] |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=0691096031 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Himka |first=John-Paul |author-link =John-Paul Himka | year=2011 |title=The Lviv Pogrom of 1941: The Germans, Ukrainian Nationalists, and the Carnival Crowd |journal=[[Canadian Slavonic Papers]] |volume=53 |issue=2\u20134 |pages=209\u2013243 |issn=0008-5006 |id=Taylor & Francis |doi=10.1080/00085006.2011.11092673|ref=harv |url=https://www.academia.edu/3181252}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia| first=Christine  |last=Kulke |editor1=[[Geoffrey P. Megargee]] |title=Lw\u00f3w |encyclopedia=[[Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos, 1933\u20131945]]. Ghettos in German-Occupied Eastern Europe |publisher=The United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |year=2012 |volume=II, part A |isbn=978-0-253-00202-0 |ref=harv}}\n* Aharon Weiss, [[Encyclopaedia of the Holocaust]] (Hebrew edition), vol. 3, pp.&nbsp;572\u2013575. Map, illustration\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Janowska Nazi camp}}\n* [http://www.ushmm.org/ US Holocaust Memorial Museum Website (Search: \"Janowska\")]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120214102219/http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/people/e/eichmann-adolf/transcripts/Sessions/Session-022-02.html Eichmann Trial transcript: Testimony of Dr. Leon Weliczker-Wells (part 1 of 5)] \u2013 navigate consecutive web pages within website\n* [http://www.history.ucsb.edu/projects/holocaust/ Story of Nina Morecki], who was imprisoned in Janowska in 1942; photo page has images of boulder memorial at site of mass executions\n* [http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/othercamps/janowska.html The HolocaustResesearchProject]\n\n{{Holocaust Poland}} \n{{Prison riots and uprisings}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1941 establishments in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:1942 in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:1943 disestablishments]]\n[[Category:1943 in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:1943 riots]]\n[[Category:Nazi concentration camps in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Prison uprisings]]\n[[Category:General Government]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox concentration camp\n| name            = Janowska concentration camp\n| image           = Jewish prisoners forced to work for a Sonderkommando 1005 unit pose next to a bone crushing machine in the Janowska concentration camp.jpg\n| image size      = \n| type            = [[Concentration camp]]\n| caption         = Survivors of the camp's [[Sonderkommando 1005]] unit stand next to a bone crushing machine <small>(taken following the liberation of the camp in 1944)</small> \n| alt             = \n| location map    = Ukraine\n| map alt         = Ukraine\n| coordinates     = {{coord|49|51|15|N|23|59|24|E|region:UA_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| map caption     = Location of Janowska camp in modern Ukraine\n{{location mark|float=center|image=WW2-Holocaust-Poland.PNG |width=226 |x%=69.5 |y%=74.4 |label='''Janowska''' |position=right}}\nLocation of KL Janowska in World War&nbsp;II,<br />south of the [[Belzec]] [[death camp]]\n| location        = Lemberg, [[District of Galicia]], [[General Government]] (formerly Lw\u00f3w, [[Second Polish Republic]]; today [[Lviv]], Ukraine)\n| operated by     = [[SS]]\n| original use    = \n| construction    = \n| in operation    = September 1941 \u2013 November 1943\n| prisoner type   = Jews\n| inmates         = 100,000\n| killed          = 35,000\u201340,000\n| liberated by    = The Red Army\n| notable inmates = \n| notable books   = \n| website         = {{URL|https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/janowska}}\n}}\n'''Janowska concentration camp''' ({{lang-pl|Janowska}}, {{lang-ru|\u042f\u043d\u043e\u0432 or \"Yanov\"}}, {{lang-uk|\u042f\u043d\u0456\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0442\u0430\u0431\u0456\u0440}}) was a [[Nazi concentration camp]] combining elements of labor, transit and [[extermination camp]]s. It was established in September 1941 on the outskirts of Lw\u00f3w in [[Eastern Poland]] / [[Western Ukraine]] (today: [[Lviv]], Ukraine). The camp was named after the nearby street ''Janowska'' in Lw\u00f3w of the interwar [[Second Polish Republic]]. The camp was liquidated in November 1943, with the evidence of mass murder being largely destroyed in the Nazi program of ''[[Sonderaktion 1005]]''. Estimates put the total number of prisoners who passed through the Janowska camp at between 100,000 and 120,000, mostly Polish and Soviet Jews.<ref name=Kerenji>{{cite book |title=Jewish Responses to Persecution: 1942\u20131943 |author=Emil Kerenji |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gXDYBAAAQBAJ&q=Janowska+100%2C000+DAW |year=2014 |isbn=978-1442236271 |pages=69\u201370, 539}}</ref> The number of victims murdered at the camp is estimated at 35,000\u201340,000.\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|Lviv pogroms (1941)}}\nLw\u00f3w ([[Lviv]]) was a multicultural city just before World War&nbsp;II, with a population of 312,231. The city's 157,490 ethnic Poles constituted just over 50 per cent, with Jews at 32 per cent (99,595) and Ukrainians at 16 per cent (49,747).{{sfn|Himka|2011|p=210}} On 28 September 1939, after the [[Invasion of Poland|joint Soviet-German invasion]], the [[USSR]] and [[Nazi Germany]] signed the [[German\u2013Soviet Frontier Treaty]], which assigned about 200,000&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> (77,000&nbsp;sq&nbsp;mi) of Polish territory inhabited by 13.5&nbsp;million people of all nationalities to the Soviet Union. Lviv was then [[Territories of Poland annexed by the Soviet Union|annexed to the Soviet Union]] as part of the [[Ukrainian SSR]].{{sfn|Gross|2002 |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=XKtOr4EXOWwC&pg=PA17 17, 28\u201330]}}\n\nAt the time of the German attack on the Soviet Union in June 1941, about 160,000 Jews lived in the city;{{sfn|Beorn|2018|p=136}} the number had swelled by tens of thousands due to the arrival of Jewish refugees from German-occupied Poland in late 1939.{{sfn|Kulke|2012|p=802}} Lviv was occupied by the [[Wehrmacht]] on 30 June 1941. Jews were press-ganged by the Germans to remove bodies of the victims of the [[NKVD prisoner massacre]]s for which [[Nazi propaganda]] and Ukrainian nationalists blamed the Jews.{{sfn|Himka|2011|p=211}} In the ensuing [[Lviv pogroms (1941)|July pogroms]] and the concurrent [[Einsatzgruppen]] killings, thousands of Jews were murdered.{{sfn|Kulke|2012|p=802}}\n\n==Lw\u00f3w Ghetto==\n{{main|Lw\u00f3w Ghetto}}\nIn early November 1941, the Nazis closed-off northern portions of the city thus forming the [[Lw\u00f3w Ghetto]].<ref name=\"Koonz\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.uvm.edu/~uvmchs/documents/KoonzHilbergLecture_002.pdf |title=SS Man Katzmann's \"Solution of the Jewish Question in the District of Galicia\" |publisher=University of Vermont |journal=The Raul Hilberg Lecture |date=November 2, 2005 |accessdate=January 30, 2015 |author=Claudia Koonz |pages=2, 11, 16\u201318 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205021305/http://www.uvm.edu/~uvmchs/documents/KoonzHilbergLecture_002.pdf |archive-date=February 5, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> During the forced relocation of the Jewish families to the newly created ghetto, German police shot and killed thousands of elderly and sick Jews as they crossed under the rail bridge on Pe\u0142tewna Street (which came to be known as the ''bridge of death'' for the Jews). Several months later, in March 1942, the Nazi police under [[Fritz Katzmann]] began to deport Jews from the ghetto to the [[Belzec extermination camp]]. By August 1942, more than 65,000 Jews from Lw\u00f3w had been sent away aboard [[Holocaust trains]] and killed. In early June 1943, the Germans destroyed and liquidated the ghetto.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Filip Friedman, ''Zag\u0142ada \u017byd\u00f3w lwowskich'' (Extermination of the Jews of Lw\u00f3w) {{OCLC|38706656}}.</ref>\n\n==Labour and transit camp==\nIn addition to the Lw\u00f3w ghetto, in September 1941 the occupation authorities set up a German Armament Works D.A.W. factory (''[[Deutsche Ausr\u00fcstungswerke]]'') in prewar Steinhaus Milling Machines Merchants (''Maszyny m\u0142y\u0144skie - Sprzeda\u017c'') on 134 Janowska Street (Grodecka 10a address),<ref>Jewishgen.org (May 2005), [https://kehilalinks.jewishgen.org/lviv/FramesetSt.html Businesses, Partnerships and Addresses: Steinhaus Milling Machines-Merchants]</ref> in northwestern suburbs of Lw\u00f3w. This factory became a part of a network of factories owned and operated by the SS. The commandant of the camp was ''{{nobreak|SS-Haupsturmf\u00fchrer}}'' Fritz Gebauer. Jews who worked at this factory were used as forced laborers, mainly working in [[carpentry]] and [[metalwork]].\n\nIn October 1941, the Nazis established a concentration camp next to the factory, which housed the forced laborers along with other prisoners. Thousands of Jews from the Lw\u00f3w ghetto were forced to work as [[Slavery|slave]] laborers in this complex. When the Lw\u00f3w ghetto was liquidated by the Nazis, the ghetto's inhabitants who were fit for work were sent to the Janowska camp; the rest were deported to [[Belzec]] for extermination. The concentration camp was guarded by a ''[[Sonderdienst]]'' battalion of the {{nobreak|''SS''-trained}} ''[[Hiwi (volunteer)|Hiwi]]'' guards known as \"[[Trawniki men]]\".<ref name=USHMM1>{{cite web |url=http://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10007397 |title=Trawniki |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |author=Holocaust Encyclopedia |accessdate=July 21, 2011 |id=permission granted to be reused, in whole or in part, on Wikipedia; [[OTRS]] ticket no. 2007071910012533 |quote=Text from USHMM has been released under the [[GFDL]].}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to being a forced-labor camp for Jews, Janowska was a transit camp (''Durchgangslager Janowska'') during the [[Final Solution|mass deportations of Polish Jews to the killing centers]] from across German-occupied southeastern Poland (now western Ukraine) in 1942. Jews underwent a selection process in Janowska camp similar to that used at [[Auschwitz-Birkenau|Auschwitz\u2013Birkenau]] and [[Majdanek]] [[extermination camps]]. Those classified as fit to work remained at Janowska for forced labor. The majority, rejected as unfit for work, were deported to Belzec and killed, or else were shot at the Piaski ravine, located just north of the camp. In the summer and fall of 1942, thousands of Jews (mainly from the Lw\u00f3w ghetto) were deported to Janowska and killed in the Piaski ravine.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe Nazis occasionally allowed small groups of Jews to go to town for daylong leaves of absence.  They would use this temporary freedom to dig up [[Torah]]s that had been hidden in Lw\u00f3w's Jewish cemetery.  The Torahs were then cut into pieces which were hidden under their clothes and smuggled back into the camp.  After the war the various pieces were assembled into a single scroll, the [[Yanov torah]], which is currently in California.<ref>Erwin and Agnes Herman ''The Yanov Torah'' [[Kar-Ben Publishing]] {{ISBN|978-0930494452}} (1985)</ref>\n\n==Liquidation==\n[[File:Site of Janowska Nazi Camp - Lviv, 1944.jpg|thumbnail|right|Soviet [[Extraordinary State Commission]] at the site of mass graves adjoining the camp, 1944.]]\nAhead of the Soviet advance, in November 1943 the new camp commandant ''SS-Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer'' Friedrich Warzok was put in charge of the evacuation of the Janowska inmates to [[Przemy\u015bl]].<ref name=\"Levy\">{{cite book | last = Levy | first = Alan | authorlink = Alan Levy | title = Nazi Hunter: The Wiesenthal File | edition = Revised 2002 | year = 2006 | origyear = 1993 | publisher = Constable & Robinson | location = London | isbn = 978-1-84119-607-7 | ref = harv }}</ref> The Germans attempted to destroy the traces of mass murder during ''[[Sonderaktion 1005]]''. Prisoners were forced to open the mass graves in Lesienicki forest and burn the bodies. On November 19, 1943, the ''Sonderkommando'' inmates staged a revolt against the Nazis and attempted a mass escape. A few succeeded, but most were recaptured and killed. The SS and their local auxiliaries murdered at least 6,000 Jews who had survived the uprising killings at Janowska, as well as Jews in other forced labor camps in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]], at the time of the camps' liquidation.<ref>{{cite web|author=USHMM |url=https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/janowska |title=Janowska| encyclopedia=[[Holocaust Encyclopedia]] |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |accessdate=2018-11-18 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Soviet [[Extraordinary State Commission]] determined that over 200,000 people were killed in Janowska in the course of the camp operation. The ashes mixed with crushed bones were buried to a depth of six feet in various places.<ref name=\"HEART\" /> {{Interlanguage link multi|Leon Weliczker Wells|de}} told the Commission that between June 6 and November 20, 1943 his \"team burned more than 310,000 bodies\" including 170,000 in the immediate vicinity of the camp and another 140,000 or more in the Lysynychi area of eastern Lw\u00f3w.<ref>[[Avner Falk]] ''Anti-semitism: A History and Psychoanalysis of Contemporary Hatred'' [[ABC-CLIO]] {{ISBN|9780313353840}} (2008) p. 191</ref>  Weliczker repeated the claim of \"a few hundred thousand\" at [[Adolf Eichmann]]'s trial in 1961.<ref>[http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/people/e/eichmann-adolf/transcripts/Sessions/Session-023-03.html \"The Trial of Adolf Eichmann\"] Session #23 2 May 1961</ref> Weliczker also described his work as part of the Sonderaktion 1005 in his book ''Death Brigade''.\n\nJanowska served as a Soviet prison camp after its liberation.<ref name=\"HEART\">{{cite web | url=http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/othercamps/janowska.html | title=The Soviet Special Commission | publisher=Holocaust Education & Archive Research Team | work=Janowska \u2013 Lvov | year=2007 | accessdate=January 28, 2018 | author=Carmelo Lisciotto, H.E.A.R.T}}</ref><br />\n\n==Tango of Death==\n[[File:Janowska Nazi camp orchestra.jpg|thumb|Tango of Death]]\nIn the Janowska concentration camp, the Nazis conducted torture and executions to music. The Orchestra members, who were prisoners, played one and the same tune, Tango of Death. Lviv National Philharmonic Orchestra professor Shtriks, opera conductor Mund and other famous Jewish musicians were among the members. \n\nDuring hanging the Nazis ordered the orchestra to play tango, and during tortures the musicians had to play foxtrot. Some evenings the orchestra musicians were made to play under the camp commander\u2019s windows for hours on end.\n\nOn the eve of Lviv\u2019s liberation German Nazis ordered 40 orchestra musicians to form a circle. The security ringed the musicians tightly and ordered them to play. First the orchestra conductor, Mund, was executed. Then the commandant ordered the musicians to come to the center of the circle one by one, put their instrument onto the ground and strip naked, after which they were killed by a headshot.\n\nA photo of the orchestra players was one of the incriminating documents at the [[Nuremberg trials]].\n\nJacob Mund\u2019s story is described in the book called [https://www.amazon.com/Tango-Death-Story-Holocaust-Survivors/dp/B085HHMGMT/ Tango of Death].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://awesomegang.com/tango-of-death-a-true-story-of-a-holocaust-survivor/|title=Tango of Death: A True Story of a Holocaust Survivor|last=O'Hare|first=Vinny|website=awesomegang.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Notable inmates==<!-- Please respect alphabetical order -->\n* [[Maurycy Allerhand]], lawyer\n* [[Adolf Beck (physiologist)|Adolf Beck]], physiologist\n* [[Enrico Ciantelli]] Italian Military Internee, lawyer\n* [[Janina Altman|Janina Hescheles]] (then Altman), Polish-Israeli chemist and writer \n* Rabbi [[Yisroel Spira]], Grand Rabbi of Bluzev ([[B\u0142a\u017cowa]])\n* [[Emanuel Szlechter]], screenwriter and lyricist\n* [[William Ungar]], founder of the [[National Envelope Corporation]]\n* [[Debora Vogel]], philosopher and poet\n* [[Simon Wiesenthal]], [[Nazi hunter]]\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=21em}}\n* [[Kaiser Wilhelm Institute of Anthropology, Human Heredity, and Eugenics]]\n* [[List of Nazi concentration camps]]\n* [[Nazi concentration camps]]\n{{div col end}}\n{{Portal bar|Genocide|Germany|Poland|World War II}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}} \n*[https://www.amazon.com/Tango-Death-Story-Holocaust-Survivors/dp/B085HHMGMT/ Tango of Death]. A True Story of Holocaust Survivors \u2014 Mr. Mintz Publishing, Mikhail Baranovskiy, 2020. - ISBN 979-8620147014\n*{{cite book |last1=Beorn |first1=Waitman Wade |author-link = Waitman Wade Beorn|title=The Holocaust in Eastern Europe: At the Epicenter of the Final Solution |date=2018 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=978-1474232227 |ref = harv}}\n* Filip Friedman, ''Zag\u0142ada \u017byd\u00f3w Lwowskich'' (Extermination of the Jews of Lw\u00f3w) \u2013 [https://web.archive.org/web/20101106061357/http://www.mankurty.com/fridpl.html online in Polish, Ukrainian and Russian]\n*{{cite book |authorlink=Jan T. Gross |last=Gross |first=Jan Tomasz |year=2002 |title=Revolution from Abroad: The Soviet Conquest of Poland's Western Ukraine and Western Belorussia |location=Princeton, [[New Jersey|NJ]] |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=0691096031 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Himka |first=John-Paul |author-link =John-Paul Himka | year=2011 |title=The Lviv Pogrom of 1941: The Germans, Ukrainian Nationalists, and the Carnival Crowd |journal=[[Canadian Slavonic Papers]] |volume=53 |issue=2\u20134 |pages=209\u2013243 |issn=0008-5006 |id=Taylor & Francis |doi=10.1080/00085006.2011.11092673|ref=harv |url=https://www.academia.edu/3181252}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia| first=Christine  |last=Kulke |editor1=[[Geoffrey P. Megargee]] |title=Lw\u00f3w |encyclopedia=[[Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos, 1933\u20131945]]. Ghettos in German-Occupied Eastern Europe |publisher=The United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |year=2012 |volume=II, part A |isbn=978-0-253-00202-0 |ref=harv}}\n* Aharon Weiss, [[Encyclopaedia of the Holocaust]] (Hebrew edition), vol. 3, pp.&nbsp;572\u2013575. Map, illustration\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Janowska Nazi camp}}\n* [http://www.ushmm.org/ US Holocaust Memorial Museum Website (Search: \"Janowska\")]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120214102219/http://www.nizkor.org/hweb/people/e/eichmann-adolf/transcripts/Sessions/Session-022-02.html Eichmann Trial transcript: Testimony of Dr. Leon Weliczker-Wells (part 1 of 5)] \u2013 navigate consecutive web pages within website\n* [http://www.history.ucsb.edu/projects/holocaust/ Story of Nina Morecki], who was imprisoned in Janowska in 1942; photo page has images of boulder memorial at site of mass executions\n* [http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/othercamps/janowska.html The HolocaustResesearchProject]\n\n{{Holocaust Poland}} \n{{Prison riots and uprisings}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1941 establishments in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:1942 in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:1943 disestablishments]]\n[[Category:1943 in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:1943 riots]]\n[[Category:Nazi concentration camps in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Prison uprisings]]\n[[Category:General Government]]\n", "name_user": "Deepcom", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Janowska_concentration_camp"}
{"title_page": "Hepatitis C", "text_new": "{{short description|Human viral infection}}\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{Good Article}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Hepatitis C\n| image           = HCV EM picture 2.png\n| caption         = [[Electron micrograph]] of [[hepatitis C virus]] from cell culture (scale = 50&nbsp;[[nanometers]])\n| field           = [[Gastroenterology]], [[Infectious disease (medical specialty)|infectious disease]]\n| symptoms        = Typically none<ref name=CDC2016 />\n| complications   = [[Liver failure]], [[hepatocellular carcinoma|liver cancer]], [[esophageal varices|esophageal]] and [[gastric varices]]<ref name=Sherris2004 />\n| onset           = \n| duration        = Long term (80%)<ref name=CDC2016 />\n| causes          = [[Hepatitis C virus]] usually spread by blood-to-blood contact<ref name=CDC2016 /><ref name=Mah2010/>\n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = Blood testing for [[antibodies]] or viral [[RNA]]<ref name=CDC2016 />\n| differential    = \n| prevention      = Clean needles, testing donated blood<ref name=WHO2015 />\n| treatment       = Medications, [[liver transplant]]<ref name=NEJM2011 />\n| medication      = [[Sofosbuvir]], [[simeprevir]]<ref name=CDC2016 /><ref name=WHO2015 />\n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = 143 million / 2% (2015)<ref name=GBD2015Pre/>\n| deaths          = 496,000 (2015)<ref name=GBD2015De/>\n}}\n<!-- Definition and symptoms -->\n'''Hepatitis C''' is an [[infectious disease]] caused by the [[hepatitis C virus]] (HCV) that primarily affects the [[liver]].<ref name=Sherris2004>{{cite book | title = Sherris Medical Microbiology | edition = 4th | publisher = McGraw Hill | year = 2004 | pages=551\u201352 | isbn = 978-0-8385-8529-0 |veditors=Ryan KJ, Ray CG }}</ref> During the initial infection people often have mild or no symptoms.<ref name=CDC2016 /> Occasionally a fever, dark urine, abdominal pain, and [[jaundice|yellow tinged skin]] occurs.<ref name=CDC2016 /> The virus persists in the liver in about 75% to 85% of those initially infected.<ref name=CDC2016 /> Early on chronic infection typically has no symptoms.<ref name=CDC2016 /> Over many years however, it often leads to [[liver disease]] and occasionally [[cirrhosis]].<ref name=CDC2016 /> In some cases, those with cirrhosis will develop serious complications such as [[liver failure]], [[hepatocellular carcinoma|liver cancer]], or [[esophageal varices|dilated blood vessels in the esophagus]] and [[gastric varices|stomach]].<ref name=Sherris2004 />\n\n<!-- Cause and diagnosis -->\nHCV is spread primarily by blood-to-blood contact associated with [[intravenous drug use]], poorly sterilized medical equipment, [[needlestick injuries]] in healthcare, and [[blood transfusions|transfusions]].<ref name=CDC2016 /><ref name=Mah2010>{{cite journal|last=Maheshwari|first=A|author2=Thuluvath, PJ|title=Management of acute hepatitis C|journal=Clinics in Liver Disease|date=February 2010|volume=14|issue=1|pages=169\u201376, x|pmid=20123448|doi=10.1016/j.cld.2009.11.007}}</ref> Using blood screening, the risk from a transfusion is less than one per two million.<ref name=CDC2016 /> It may also be spread from an infected mother to her baby during birth.<ref name=CDC2016 /> It is not spread by superficial contact.<ref name=WHO2015 /> It is one of five known hepatitis viruses: [[hepatitis A|A]], [[hepatitis B|B]], C, [[hepatitis D|D]], and [[hepatitis E|E]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Viral Hepatitis: A through E and Beyond|url=http://www.niddk.nih.gov/health-information/health-topics/liver-disease/viral-hepatitis-a-through-e/Pages/facts.aspx|website=National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases|accessdate=4 February 2016|date=April 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202083731/http://www.niddk.nih.gov/health-information/health-topics/liver-disease/viral-hepatitis-a-through-e/Pages/facts.aspx|archivedate=2 February 2016}}</ref> Diagnosis is by blood testing to look for either [[antibodies]] to the virus or its [[RNA]].<ref name=CDC2016 /> Testing is recommended in all people who are at risk.<ref name=CDC2016>{{cite web|title=Hepatitis C FAQs for Health Professionals|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/hcv/hcvfaq.htm|website=CDC|accessdate=4 February 2016|date=January 8, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160121073721/http://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/hcv/hcvfaq.htm|archivedate=21 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Prevention and treatment -->\nThere is no [[vaccine]] against hepatitis C.<ref name=CDC2016 /><ref name=Web2015>{{cite journal|last1=Webster|first1=Daniel P|last2=Klenerman|first2=Paul|last3=Dusheiko|first3=Geoffrey M|title=Hepatitis C|journal=The Lancet|volume=385|issue=9973|year=2015|pages=1124\u201335|pmid=25687730|pmc=4878852|issn=0140-6736|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(14)62401-6}}</ref> Prevention includes [[harm reduction]] efforts among people who use intravenous drugs and testing donated blood.<ref name=WHO2015 /> Chronic infection can be cured about 95% of the time with antiviral medications such as [[sofosbuvir]] or [[simeprevir]].<ref name=CDC2016 /><ref name=WHO2015 /> [[Peginterferon]] and [[ribavirin]] were earlier generation treatments that had a cure rate of less than 50% and greater side effects.<ref name=WHO2015/><ref name=Kim2016/> Getting access to the newer treatments however can be expensive.<ref name=WHO2015 /> Those who develop cirrhosis or liver cancer may require a [[liver transplant]].<ref name=NEJM2011 /> Hepatitis C is the leading reason for liver transplantation, though the virus usually recurs after transplantation.<ref name=NEJM2011>{{cite journal|last=Rosen|first=HR|title=Clinical practice. Chronic hepatitis C infection|journal=The New England Journal of Medicine|date=2011-06-23|volume=364|issue=25|pages=2429\u201338|pmid=21696309|doi=10.1056/NEJMcp1006613|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/ee00276a6c2b5e9af4841bce7922b00b92ff20a4}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Epidemiology and history -->\nAn estimated 143 million people (2%) worldwide are infected with hepatitis C {{as of| 2015|lc=yes}}.<ref name=GBD2015Pre>{{cite journal|last1=GBD 2015 Disease and Injury Incidence and Prevalence|first1=Collaborators.|title=Global, regional, and national incidence, prevalence, and years lived with disability for 310 diseases and injuries, 1990\u20132015: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2015.|journal=Lancet|date=8 October 2016|volume=388|issue=10053|pages=1545\u20131602|pmid=27733282|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(16)31678-6|pmc=5055577}}</ref> In 2013, about eleven million new cases occurred.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Global Burden of Disease Study 2013|first1=Collaborators|title=Global, regional, and national incidence, prevalence, and years lived with disability for 301 acute and chronic diseases and injuries in 188 countries, 1990\u20132013: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2013.|journal=Lancet|date=22 August 2015|volume=386|issue=9995|pages=743\u2013800|pmid=26063472|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(15)60692-4|pmc=4561509}}</ref> It occurs most commonly in Africa and Central and East Asia.<ref name=WHO2015>{{cite web|title=Hepatitis C Fact sheet N\u00b0164|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs164/en/|website=WHO|accessdate=4 February 2016|date=July 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131041006/http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs164/en/|archivedate=31 January 2016}}</ref> About 167,000 deaths due to liver cancer and 326,000 deaths due to cirrhosis occurred in 2015 due to hepatitis C.<ref name=GBD2015De>{{cite journal|last1=GBD 2015 Mortality and Causes of Death|first1=Collaborators.|title=Global, regional, and national life expectancy, all-cause mortality, and cause-specific mortality for 249 causes of death, 1980\u20132015: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2015.|journal=Lancet|date=8 October 2016|volume=388|issue=10053|pages=1459\u20131544|pmid=27733281|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(16)31012-1|pmc=5388903}}</ref> The existence of hepatitis C \u2013 originally identifiable only as a type of non-[[Hepatitis A|A]] non-[[Hepatitis B|B]] [[hepatitis]] \u2013 was suggested in the 1970s and proven in 1989.<ref name=\"pmid19781804\">{{cite journal |author=Houghton M |title=The long and winding road leading to the identification of the hepatitis C virus |journal=Journal of Hepatology |volume=51 |issue=5 |pages=939\u201348 |date=November 2009 |pmid=19781804 |doi=10.1016/j.jhep.2009.08.004 |url=http://www.journal-of-hepatology.eu/article/S0168-8278%2809%2900535-2/fulltext|doi-access=free }}</ref> Hepatitis C infects only humans and [[Common chimpanzee|chimpanzees]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Shors|first=Teri|title=Understanding viruses|publisher=Jones & Bartlett Learning|location=Burlington, MA|isbn=978-0-7637-8553-6|pages=535|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Uk8xP5LRHr4C&pg=PA535|edition=2nd|year=2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515225439/https://books.google.com/books?id=Uk8xP5LRHr4C&pg=PA535|archivedate=2016-05-15}}</ref>\n[[File:Wikipedia-VideoWiki-Hepatitis C.webm|thumb|thumbtime=0:28|upright=1.3|Video summary ([[Wikipedia:VideoWiki/Hepatitis C|script]])]]\n\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n== Signs and symptoms ==\n\n=== Acute infection ===\n[[Acute (medicine)|Acute]] symptoms develop in some 20\u201330% of those infected.<ref name=CDC2016/> When this occurs, it is generally 4\u201312 weeks following infection (but it may take from 2 weeks to 6 months for acute symptoms to appear).<ref name=CDC2016/><ref name=\"WHO2015\" />\n\nSymptoms are generally mild and vague, and may include fatigue, [[nausea]] and vomiting, fever, [[myalgia|muscle]] or [[Arthralgia|joint pains]], abdominal pain, [[Anorexia (symptom)|decreased appetite]] and weight loss, jaundice (occurs in ~25% of those infected), dark urine, and clay-coloured stools.<ref name=CDC2016/><ref name=\"Book2011p4\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6G7mff5DnBQC&pg=PA4|title=Chronic Hepatitis C Virus Advances in Treatment, Promise for the Future|publisher=Springer Verlag|year=2011|isbn=978-1-4614-1191-8|page=14|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617181023/https://books.google.com/books?id=6G7mff5DnBQC&pg=PA4|archivedate=2016-06-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"AFP2010\">{{cite journal|last=Wilkins|first=T|author2=Malcolm JK|author3=Raina D|author4=Schade RR|title=Hepatitis C: diagnosis and treatment|journal=American Family Physician|date=2010-06-01|volume=81|issue=11|pages=1351\u201357|pmid=20521755|url=http://www.aafp.org/afp/2010/0601/p1351.pdf|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521071850/http://www.aafp.org/afp/2010/0601/p1351.pdf|archivedate=2013-05-21}}</ref> There is no evidence that acute hepatitis C can alone cause [[acute liver failure]], though liver injury and elevated liver enzymes may occur.<ref name=Book2011p4/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Manka|first=Paul|last2=Verheyen|first2=Jens|last3=Gerken|first3=Guido|last4=Canbay|first4=Ali|date=April 2016|title=Liver Failure due to Acute Viral Hepatitis (A\u2013E)|journal=Visceral Medicine|volume=32|issue=2|pages=80\u201385|doi=10.1159/000444915|issn=2297-4725|pmc=4926881|pmid=27413724}}</ref> Symptoms and laboratory findings suggestive of liver disease should prompt further tests and can thus help establish a diagnosis of hepatitis C infection early on.<ref name=AFP2010/>\n\nFollowing the acute phase, the infection may resolve spontaneously in 10\u201350% of affected people; this occurs more frequently in young people, and females.<ref name=\"Book2011p4\" />\n\n=== Chronic infection ===\nAbout 80% of those exposed to the virus develop a chronic infection.<ref name=Lancet2011 /> This is defined as the presence of detectable viral replication for at least six months. Most experience minimal or no symptoms during the initial few decades of the infection.<ref name=Book2011 /> Chronic {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} can be associated with fatigue<ref name=ID2010 /> and mild cognitive problems.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Forton|first=DM|author2=Allsop, JM |author3=Cox, IJ |author4=Hamilton, G |author5=Wesnes, K |author6=Thomas, HC |author7= Taylor-Robinson, SD |title=A review of cognitive impairment and cerebral metabolite abnormalities in patients with hepatitis C infection|journal=AIDS|date=October 2005|volume=19 |issue=Suppl 3|pages=S53\u201363|pmid=16251829|doi=10.1097/01.aids.0000192071.72948.77}}</ref> Chronic infection after several years may cause [[cirrhosis]] or [[liver cancer]].<ref name=NEJM2011 /> The liver enzymes are normal in 7\u201353%.<ref name=Nicot2011 /> Late relapses after apparent cure have been reported, but these can be difficult to distinguish from reinfection.<ref name=Nicot2011 />\n\n[[Steatohepatitis|Fatty changes to the liver]] occur in about half of those infected and are usually present before cirrhosis develops.<ref name=\"El-Zayadi2008\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Paradis|first=V|author2=Bedossa, P|title=Definition and natural history of metabolic steatosis: histology and cellular aspects|journal=Diabetes & Metabolism|date=December 2008|volume=34|issue=6 Pt 2|pages=638\u201342|pmid=19195624|doi=10.1016/S1262-3636(08)74598-1}}</ref> Usually (80% of the time) this change affects less than a third of the liver.<ref name=\"El-Zayadi2008\">{{cite journal|last=El-Zayadi|first=AR|title=Hepatic steatosis: a benign disease or a silent killer.|journal=World Journal of Gastroenterology|date=2008-07-14|volume=14|issue=26|pages=4120\u201326|pmid=18636654|doi=10.3748/wjg.14.4120|pmc=2725370}}</ref> Worldwide hepatitis C is the cause of 27% of cirrhosis cases and 25% of hepatocellular carcinoma.<ref name=World2007>{{cite journal|last=Alter |first=MJ |title=Epidemiology of hepatitis C virus infection |journal=World Journal of Gastroenterology |date=2007-05-07 |volume=13 |issue=17 |pages=2436\u201341 |pmid=17552026 |pmc=4146761 |doi=10.3748/wjg.v13.i17.2436 }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> About 10\u201330% of those infected develop cirrhosis over 30&nbsp;years.<ref name=NEJM2011 /><ref name=AFP2010 /> Cirrhosis is more common in those also infected with [[hepatitis B]], [[schistosoma]], or HIV, in [[alcoholic]]s and in those of male gender.<ref name=AFP2010 /> In those with hepatitis C, excess alcohol increases the risk of developing cirrhosis 100-fold.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mueller|first=S|author2=Millonig G|author3=Seitz HK|title=Alcoholic liver disease and hepatitis C: a frequently underestimated combination|journal=World Journal of Gastroenterology|date=2009-07-28|volume=15|issue=28|pages=3462\u201371|pmid=19630099|doi=10.3748/wjg.15.3462|pmc=2715970|url=http://www.wjgnet.com/downpdf.asp?url=/1007-9327/15/3462|format=PDF}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=Level C |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Those who develop cirrhosis have a 20-fold greater risk of [[hepatocellular carcinoma]]. This transformation occurs at a rate of 1\u20133% per year.<ref name=NEJM2011 /><ref name=AFP2010 /> Being infected with hepatitis B in addition to hepatitis C increases this risk further.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fattovich|first=G|author2=Stroffolini, T |author3=Zagni, I |author4= Donato, F |title=Hepatocellular carcinoma in cirrhosis: incidence and risk factors.|journal=Gastroenterology|date=November 2004|volume=127|issue=5 Suppl 1|pages=S35\u201350|pmid=15508101|doi=10.1053/j.gastro.2004.09.014}}</ref>\n\nLiver cirrhosis may lead to [[portal hypertension]], [[ascites]] (accumulation of fluid in the abdomen), [[coagulopathy|easy bruising or bleeding]], varices (enlarged veins, especially in the stomach and esophagus), [[jaundice]], and a syndrome of cognitive impairment known as [[hepatic encephalopathy]].<ref name=Tah2009 /> Ascites occurs at some stage in more than half of those who have a chronic infection.<ref name=Zaltron2012>{{cite journal|last=Zaltron|first=S|author2=Spinetti, A |author3=Biasi, L |author4=Baiguera, C |author5= Castelli, F |title=Chronic HCV infection: epidemiological and clinical relevance.|journal=BMC Infectious Diseases|year=2012|volume=12 Suppl 2|pages=S2|pmid=23173556|doi=10.1186/1471-2334-12-S2-S2 |pmc=3495628}}</ref>\n\n=== Extrahepatic complications ===\nThe most common problem due to {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} but not involving the liver is mixed [[cryoglobulinemia]] (usually the type II form) \u2013 an [[vasculitis|inflammation of small and medium-sized blood vessels]].<ref name=Cryo2013>{{cite journal| title =Review Article: Therapy for Hepatitis C Virus\u2013Related Cryoglobulinemic Vasculitis| journal =N Engl J Med| date =September 12, 2013| vauthors =Dammacco F, Sansonno D| volume =369| issue =11| pages =1035\u201345| doi =10.1056/NEJMra1208642| pmid =24024840| url =https://semanticscholar.org/paper/0ef3d558b0baf48b389b413380a82c9a6458e1b0}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Iannuzzella | first1 = F | last2 = Vaglio | first2 = A | last3 = Garini | first3 = G |title=Management of hepatitis C virus-related mixed cryoglobulinemia |journal=Am. J. Med. |volume=123 |issue=5 |pages=400\u201308 |date=May 2010 |pmid=20399313 |doi=10.1016/j.amjmed.2009.09.038 |url=}}</ref> {{nowrap|Hepatitis C}} is also associated with autoimmune disorders such as [[Sj\u00f6gren's syndrome]], [[lichen planus]], [[thrombocytopenia|a low platelet count]], [[porphyria cutanea tarda]], [[necrolytic acral erythema]], [[insulin resistance]], [[diabetes mellitus]], [[diabetic nephropathy]], autoimmune [[thyroiditis]], and B-cell [[lymphoproliferative disorder]]s.<ref name=Extrahepatic>{{cite journal | last1 = Zignego | first1 = AL | last2 = Ferri | first2 = C | last3 = Pileri | first3 = SA | last4 = Caini | first4 = P | last5 = Bianchi | first5 = FB |title=Extrahepatic manifestations of Hepatitis C Virus infection: a general overview and guidelines for a clinical approach |journal=Digestive and Liver Disease |volume=39 |issue=1 |pages=2\u201317 |date=January 2007 |pmid=16884964 |doi=10.1016/j.dld.2006.06.008 | display-authors=3 }}</ref><ref name=Ko2012>{{cite journal|last=Ko|first=HM|author2=Hernandez-Prera, JC |author3=Zhu, H |author4=Dikman, SH |author5=Sidhu, HK |author6=Ward, SC |author7= Thung, SN |title=Morphologic features of extrahepatic manifestations of hepatitis C virus infection.|journal=Clinical & Developmental Immunology|year=2012|volume=2012|pages=1\u20139|pmid=22919404|doi=10.1155/2012/740138 |pmc=3420144}}</ref> 20\u201330% of people infected have [[rheumatoid factor]] \u2013 a type of antibody.<ref name=Dammacco2000>{{cite journal|last=Dammacco|first=F|author2=Sansonno, D |author3=Piccoli, C |author4=Racanelli, V |author5=D'Amore, FP |author6= Lauletta, G |title=The lymphoid system in hepatitis C virus infection: autoimmunity, mixed cryoglobulinemia, and Overt B-cell malignancy.|journal=Seminars in Liver Disease|year=2000|volume=20|issue=2|pages=143\u201357|pmid=10946420|doi=10.1055/s-2000-9613}}</ref> Possible associations include [[prurigo nodularis|Hyde's prurigo nodularis]]<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lee|first=MR|author2=Shumack, S|title=Prurigo nodularis: a review|journal=The Australasian Journal of Dermatology|date=November 2005|volume=46|issue=4|pages=211\u201318; quiz 219\u201320|pmid=16197418|doi=10.1111/j.1440-0960.2005.00187.x}}</ref> and [[membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis]].<ref name=ID2010 />  [[Cardiomyopathy]] with associated [[Heart arrhythmia|abnormal heart rhythms]] has also been reported.<ref name=Matsumori2006>{{cite book|last=Matsumori|first=A|title=Role of hepatitis C virus in cardiomyopathies.|journal=Ernst Schering Research Foundation Workshop|volume=55|year=2006|issue=55|pages=99\u2013120|pmid=16329660|doi=10.1007/3-540-30822-9_7|isbn=978-3-540-23971-0}}</ref> A variety of [[central nervous system]] disorders has been reported.<ref name=Monaco2012>{{cite journal|last=Monaco|first=S|author2=Ferrari, S |author3=Gajofatto, A |author4=Zanusso, G |author5= Mariotto, S |title=HCV-related nervous system disorders.|journal=Clinical & Developmental Immunology|year=2012|volume=2012|pages=1\u20139|pmid=22899946|doi=10.1155/2012/236148 |pmc=3414089}}</ref> Chronic infection seems to be associated with an increased risk of [[pancreatic cancer]].<ref name=Web2015 /><ref name=Xu2013>{{cite journal|last=Xu|first=JH|author2=Fu, JJ |author3=Wang, XL |author4=Zhu, JY |author5=Ye, XH |author6= Chen, SD |title=Hepatitis B or C viral infection and risk of pancreatic cancer: A meta-analysis of observational studies.|journal=World Journal of Gastroenterology|date=2013-07-14|volume=19|issue=26|pages=4234\u201341|pmid=23864789|doi=10.3748/wjg.v19.i26.4234 |pmc=3710428}}</ref> People may experience other issues in the mouth such as [[xerostomia|dryness]], [[sialadenitis|salivary duct stones]], and crusted lesions around the mouth.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1998-07-01|title=Hepatitis C virus infection: Review and implications for the dentist|journal=Oral Surgery, Oral Medicine, Oral Pathology, Oral Radiology, and Endodontology|volume=86|issue=1|pages=8\u201322|doi=10.1016/S1079-2104(98)90143-3|pmid=9690239|issn=1079-2104|last1=Lodi|first1=G.|last2=Porter|first2=S.R|last3=Scully|first3=C.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Carrozzo|first=M.|last2=Gandolfo|first2=S.|date=2003-03-01|title=Oral Diseases Possibly Associated with Hepatitis C Virus|journal=Critical Reviews in Oral Biology & Medicine|volume=14|issue=2|pages=115\u201327|doi=10.1177/154411130301400205|pmid=12764074|issn=1045-4411|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Dental Management of the Medically Compromised Patient|year=2013|isbn=978-0323080286|location=|page=151|last1=Little|first1=James W.|last2=Falace|first2=Donald A. |first3=Craig |last3=Miller |first4=Nelson L. |last4=Rhodus}}</ref>\n\n=== Occult infection ===\nPersons who have been infected with hepatitis C may appear to clear the virus but remain infected.<ref name=Sugden2012>{{cite journal|last=Sugden|first=PB|author2=Cameron, B |author3=Bull, R |author4=White, PA |author5= Lloyd, AR |title=Occult infection with hepatitis C virus: friend or foe?|journal=Immunology and Cell Biology|date=September 2012|volume=90|issue=8|pages=763\u201373|pmid=22546735|doi=10.1038/icb.2012.20}}</ref> The virus is not detectable with conventional testing but can be found with ultra-sensitive tests.<ref name=\"Carre\u00f1o2006\">{{cite journal|last=Carre\u00f1o|first=V|title=Occult hepatitis C virus infection: a new form of hepatitis C.|journal=World Journal of Gastroenterology|date=2006-11-21|volume=12|issue=43|pages=6922\u201325|pmid=17109511|pmc=4087333|doi=10.3748/wjg.12.6922}}</ref> The original method of detection was by demonstrating the viral [[genome]] within liver biopsies, but newer methods include an antibody test for the virus' core protein and the detection of the viral genome after first concentrating the viral particles by [[ultracentrifugation]].<ref name=\"Carre\u00f1oGarc\u00eda2011\">{{cite journal|last=Carre\u00f1o Garc\u00eda|first=V|author2=Nebreda, JB |author3=Aguilar, IC |author4= Quiroga Est\u00e9vez, JA |title=[Occult hepatitis C virus infection].|journal=Enfermedades Infecciosas y Microbiologia Clinica|date=March 2011|volume=29 Suppl 3|pages=14\u201319|pmid=21458706|doi=10.1016/S0213-005X(11)70022-2}}</ref> A form of infection with persistently moderately elevated serum liver enzymes but without antibodies to hepatitis C has also been reported.<ref name=Pham2010>{{cite journal|last=Pham|first=TN|author2=Coffin, CS |author3=Michalak, TI |title=Occult hepatitis C virus infection: what does it mean?|journal=Liver International|date=April 2010|volume=30|issue=4|pages=502\u201311|pmid=20070513|doi=10.1111/j.1478-3231.2009.02193.x}}</ref> This form is known as cryptogenic occult infection.\n\nSeveral clinical pictures have been associated with this type of infection.<ref name=\"Carre\u00f1o2012\">{{cite journal|last=Carre\u00f1o|first=V|author2=Bartolom\u00e9, J |author3=Castillo, I |author4= Quiroga, JA |title=New perspectives in occult hepatitis C virus infection.|journal=World Journal of Gastroenterology|date=2012-06-21|volume=18|issue=23|pages=2887\u201394|pmid=22736911|doi=10.3748/wjg.v18.i23.2887 |pmc=3380315}}</ref> It may be found in people with anti-hepatitis-C antibodies but with normal serum levels of liver enzymes; in antibody-negative people with ongoing elevated liver enzymes of unknown cause; in healthy populations without evidence of liver disease; and in groups at risk for HCV infection including those on hemodialysis or family members of people with occult HCV. The clinical relevance of this form of infection is under investigation.<ref name=\"Carre\u00f1o2008\">{{cite journal|last=Carre\u00f1o|first=V|author2=Bartolom\u00e9, J |author3=Castillo, I |author4= Quiroga, JA |title=Occult hepatitis B virus and hepatitis C virus infections.|journal=Reviews in Medical Virology|date=May\u2013June 2008|volume=18|issue=3|pages=139\u201357|pmid=18265423|doi=10.1002/rmv.569}}</ref> The consequences of occult infection appear to be less severe than with chronic infection but can vary from minimal to hepatocellular carcinoma.<ref name=\"Carre\u00f1oGarc\u00eda2011\" />\n\nThe rate of occult infection in those apparently cured is controversial but appears to be low.<ref name=Nicot2011>{{cite book|last=Nicot|first=F|title=Occult hepatitis C virus infection: Where are we now?|year=2004|isbn=978-953-307-883-0|chapter=Chapter 19. Liver biopsy in modern medicine.}}</ref> 40% of those with hepatitis but with both negative hepatitis C serology and the absence of detectable viral genome in the serum have hepatitis C virus in the liver on biopsy.<ref name=Scott2007>{{cite journal|last=Scott|first=JD|author2=Gretch, DR|title=Molecular diagnostics of hepatitis C virus infection: a systematic review.|journal=JAMA: The Journal of the American Medical Association|date=2007-02-21|volume=297|issue=7|pages=724\u201332|pmid=17312292|doi=10.1001/jama.297.7.724|doi-access=free}}</ref> How commonly this occurs in children is unknown.<ref name=Robinson2008>{{cite journal|last=Robinson|first=JL|title=Vertical transmission of the hepatitis C virus: Current knowledge and issues|journal=Paediatr Child Health|date=July 4, 2008|volume=13|issue=6|pages=529\u201334|pmc=2532905|pmid=19436425|doi=10.1093/pch/13.6.529}}</ref>\n\n== Virology ==\n{{Main|Hepatitis C virus}}\n\nThe [[hepatitis C virus]] (HCV) is a small, enveloped, single-stranded, positive-sense [[RNA virus]].<ref name=NEJM2011 /> It is a member of the genus ''[[Hepacivirus]]'' in the family ''[[Flaviviridae]]''.<ref name=ID2010>{{cite book | last1 = Ray | first1 = Stuart C. | last2 = Thomas | first2 = David L. |editor1-first = Gerald L. | editor1-last = Mandell | editor2-first = John E. | editor2-last = Bennett | editor3-last = Dolin | editor3-first = Raphael |title=Mandell, Douglas, and Bennett's principles and practice of infectious diseases|year=2009|publisher=Churchill Livingstone |location=Philadelphia, PA|isbn=978-0-443-06839-3|chapter=Chapter 154: Hepatitis C |edition=7th}}</ref> There are seven major genotypes of HCV, which are known as genotypes one to seven.<ref name=Nakano2011>{{cite journal | last1 = Nakano | first1 = T | last2 = Lau | first2 = GM | last3 = Lau | first3 = GM | last4 = Sugiyama | first4 = M | last5 = Mizokami | first5 = M |title=An updated analysis of hepatitis C virus genotypes and subtypes based on the complete coding region |journal=Liver Int. |date=December 2011 |pmid=22142261 |doi=10.1111/j.1478-3231.2011.02684.x |volume=32 |issue=2 |pages=339\u201345 | display-authors=3 }}</ref> The genotypes are divided into several subtypes with the number of subtypes depending on the genotype. In the United States, about 70% of cases are caused by genotype 1, 20% by genotype 2 and about 1% by each of the other genotypes.<ref name=AFP2010 /> Genotype 1 is also the most common in South America and Europe.<ref name=NEJM2011 />\n\nThe half life of the virus particles in the serum is around 3 hours and may be as short as 45 minutes.<ref name=Lerat2004 /><ref>{{cite book|last=Pockros|first=Paul|title=Novel and Combination Therapies for Hepatitis C Virus, An Issue of Clinics in Liver Disease|year=2011|isbn=978-1-4557-7198-1|page=47|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gm6aXv8A8cUC&pg=PT47|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160521235637/https://books.google.com/books?id=Gm6aXv8A8cUC&pg=PT47|archivedate=2016-05-21}}</ref> In an infected person, about 10<sup>12</sup> virus particles are produced each day.<ref name=Lerat2004>{{cite journal|last=Lerat|first=H|author2=Hollinger, FB|title=Hepatitis C virus (HCV) occult infection or occult HCV RNA detection?|journal=The Journal of Infectious Diseases|date=2004-01-01|volume=189|issue=1|pages=3\u20136|pmid=14702146|doi=10.1086/380203|doi-access=free}}</ref> In addition to replicating in the liver the virus can multiply in lymphocytes.<ref name=Zignego2012>{{cite journal|last=Zignego|first=AL|author2=Giannini, C |author3=Gragnani, L |author4=Piluso, A |author5= Fognani, E |title=Hepatitis C virus infection in the immunocompromised host: a complex scenario with variable clinical impact.|journal=Journal of Translational Medicine|date=2012-08-03|volume=10|pages=158|pmid=22863056|doi=10.1186/1479-5876-10-158 |issue=1 |pmc=3441205}}</ref>\n\n== Transmission ==\n[[File:Hepatitis C infection by source (CDC) - en.svg|thumb|upright=1.4|Hepatitis C infection in the United States by source]]\n\nThe primary route of transmission in the [[developed world]] is [[intravenous drug use]] (IDU), while in the [[developing world]] the main methods are [[blood transfusions]] and unsafe medical procedures.<ref name=Mah2010 /> The cause of transmission remains unknown in 20% of cases;<ref name=Pon2011>{{cite journal|last=Pond\u00e9|first=RA |title=Hidden hazards of HCV transmission|journal=Medical Microbiology and Immunology|date=February 2011|volume=200|issue=1|pages=7\u201311|pmid=20461405|doi=10.1007/s00430-010-0159-9 }}</ref> however, many of these are believed to be accounted for by IDU.<ref name=Book2011p4 />\n\n=== Drug use ===\nIntravenous drug use (IDU) is a major risk factor for {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} in many parts of the world.<ref name=China2008>{{cite journal|last=Xia|first=X|author2=Luo J |author3=Bai J |author4=Yu R  |title=Epidemiology of HCV infection among injection drug users in China: systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=Public Health|date=October 2008|volume=122|issue=10|pages=990\u20131003|pmid=18486955|doi=10.1016/j.puhe.2008.01.014}}</ref> Of 77 countries reviewed, 25 (including the United States) were found to have prevalences of {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} in the intravenous drug user population of between 60% and 80%.<ref name=Lancet2011>{{cite journal|last=Nelson|first=PK|author2=Mathers BM |author3=Cowie B |author4=Hagan H |author5=Des Jarlais D |author6=Horyniak D |author7=Degenhardt L  |title=Global epidemiology of hepatitis B and hepatitis C in people who inject drugs: results of systematic reviews|journal=Lancet|date=2011-08-13|volume=378|issue=9791|pages=571\u201383|pmid=21802134|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(11)61097-0|pmc=3285467}}</ref><ref name=China2008 />  Twelve countries had rates greater than 80%.<ref name=Lancet2011 /> It is believed that ten million intravenous drug users are infected with {{nowrap|hepatitis C}}; China (1.6&nbsp;million), the United States (1.5&nbsp;million), and Russia (1.3&nbsp;million) have the highest absolute totals.<ref name=Lancet2011 /> [[Infectious diseases within American prisons#Hepatitis C|Occurrence of {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} among prison inmates in the United States]] is 10 to 20 times that of the occurrence observed in the general population; this has been attributed to high-risk behavior in prisons such as IDU and tattooing with nonsterile equipment.<ref name=Jail2010>{{cite journal|last=Imperial|first=JC|title=Chronic hepatitis C in the state prison system: insights into the problems and possible solutions|journal=[[Expert Review of Gastroenterology & Hepatology]]|date=June 2010|volume=4|issue=3|pages=355\u201364|pmid=20528122|doi=10.1586/egh.10.26}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Vescio|first=MF|author2=Longo B |author3=Babudieri S |author4=Starnini G |author5=Carbonara S |author6=Rezza G |author7=Monarca R  |title=Correlates of hepatitis C virus seropositivity in prison inmates: a meta-analysis|journal=Journal of Epidemiology and Community Health|date=April 2008|volume=62|issue=4|pages=305\u201313|pmid=18339822|doi=10.1136/jech.2006.051599}}</ref> Shared intranasal drug use may also be a risk factor.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Moyer|first1=VA|last2=U.S. Preventive Services Task|first2=Force|title=Screening for hepatitis C virus infection in adults: U.S. Preventive Services Task Force recommendation statement.|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=3 September 2013|volume=159|issue=5|pages=349\u201357|pmid=23798026|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-159-5-201309030-00672|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/cc502bd0e6ef93d2c52e48d32c1923eb1f32d8de}}</ref>\n\n=== Healthcare exposure ===\n[[Blood transfusion]], transfusion of blood products, or [[organ transplants]] without HCV screening carry significant risks of infection.<ref name=AFP2010 /> The United States instituted universal screening in 1992<ref name=Rosen2011 /> and Canada instituted universal screening in 1990.<ref>{{cite book|vauthors=Day RA, Paul P, Williams B|title=Brunner & Suddarth's textbook of Canadian medical-surgical nursing|date=2009|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|location=Philadelphia, PA|isbn=978-0-7817-9989-8|page=1237|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SB_-CRXvZPYC&pg=PA1237|edition=Canadian 2nd|display-authors=etal|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425134413/https://books.google.com/books?id=SB_-CRXvZPYC&pg=PA1237|archivedate=2016-04-25}}</ref> This decreased the risk from one in 200 units<ref name=Rosen2011>{{cite book|title=Rosen's emergency medicine: concepts and clinical practice 7th edition |last=Marx |first=John |year=2010|publisher=Mosby/Elsevier |location=Philadelphia, PA |isbn=978-0-323-05472-0 |page=1154 |url=}}</ref> to between one in 10,000 to one in 10,000,000 per unit of blood.<ref name=Book2011p4 /><ref name=Pon2011 /> This low risk remains as there is a period of about 11\u201370&nbsp;days between the potential [[blood donor]]'s acquiring {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} and the blood's testing positive depending on the method.<ref name=Pon2011 /> Some countries do not screen for {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} due to the cost.<ref name=World2007 />\n\nThose who have experienced a [[needle stick injury]] from someone who was HCV positive have about a 1.8% chance of subsequently contracting the disease themselves.<ref name=AFP2010 /> The risk is greater if the needle in question is hollow and the puncture wound is deep.<ref name=World2007 /> There is a risk from mucosal exposures to blood, but this risk is low, and there is no risk if blood exposure occurs on intact skin.<ref name=World2007 />\n\nHospital equipment has also been documented as a method of transmission of {{nowrap|hepatitis C}}, including reuse of needles and syringes; multiple-use medication vials; infusion bags; and improperly sterilized surgical equipment, among others.<ref name=World2007 /> Limitations in the implementation and enforcement of stringent standard precautions in public and private medical and dental facilities are known to be the primary cause of the spread of HCV in [[Egypt]], the country with highest rate of infection in the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.albawaba.com/en/news/highest-rates-hepatitis-c-virus-transmission-found-egypt |title=Highest Rates of Hepatitis C Virus Transmission Found in Egypt |publisher=Al Bawaaba |date=2010-08-09 |accessdate=2010-08-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120515221938/http://www.albawaba.com/news/highest-rates-hepatitis-c-virus-transmission-found-egypt |archive-date=2012-05-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Sexual intercourse ===\nSexual transmission of hepatitis C is uncommon.<ref name=Kim2016/> Studies examining the risk of HCV transmission between [[heterosexual]] partners, when one is infected and the other is not, have found very low risks.<ref name=Kim2016/> Sexual practices that involve higher levels of trauma to the [[anogenital area|anogenital]] mucosa, such as [[anal penetration|anal penetrative sex]], or that occur when there is a concurrent [[sexually transmitted infection]], including [[HIV]] or [[genital ulcer]]ation, present greater risks.<ref name=Kim2016/><ref name=Sex2010>{{cite journal|vauthors=Tohme RA, Holmberg SD |title=Is sexual contact a major mode of hepatitis C virus transmission? |journal=Hepatology |volume= 52|issue= 4|pages= 1497\u2013505|date=June 2010|pmid=20635398 |doi=10.1002/hep.23808 }}</ref> The [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]] recommends [[condom]] use to prevent {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} transmission in those with multiple partners, but not those in relationships that involve only a single partner.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hepatitis C Group Education Class|url=http://www.hepatitis.va.gov/products/HCV-education-class-script.asp|publisher=United States Department of Veteran Affairs|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111109105344/http://www.hepatitis.va.gov/products/HCV-education-class-script.asp|archivedate=2011-11-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Body modification ===\n[[Tattooing]] is associated with two to threefold increased risk of {{nowrap|hepatitis C}}.<ref name=Tato2010>{{cite journal|last=Jafari|first=S|author2=Copes R|author3=Baharlou S|author4=Etminan M|author5=Buxton J|title=Tattooing and the risk of transmission of hepatitis C: a systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=International Journal of Infectious Diseases|date=November 2010|volume=14|issue=11|pages=e928\u201340|pmid=20678951|url=http://natap.org/2010/HCV/tatoohcv.pdf|doi=10.1016/j.ijid.2010.03.019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426085445/http://natap.org/2010/HCV/tatoohcv.pdf|archivedate=2012-04-26}}</ref> This can be due to either improperly sterilized equipment or contamination of the dyes being used.<ref name=Tato2010 /> [[Tattoos]] or [[Body piercing|piercings]] performed either before the mid-1980s, \"underground,\" or nonprofessionally are of particular concern, since sterile techniques in such settings may be lacking. The risk also appears to be greater for larger tattoos.<ref name=Tato2010 /> It is estimated that nearly half of prison inmates share unsterilized tattooing equipment.<ref name=Tato2010 /> It is rare for tattoos in a licensed facility to be directly associated with HCV infection.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hepatitis C|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/HCV/PDFs/HepCGeneralFactSheet.pdf|publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)|accessdate=2 January 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105131937/http://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/HCV/PDFs/HepCGeneralFactSheet.pdf|archivedate=5 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Shared personal items ===\nPersonal-care items such as razors, toothbrushes, and manicuring or pedicuring equipment can be contaminated with blood. Sharing such items can potentially lead to exposure to HCV.<ref name=\"pmid16907842\">{{cite journal |author=Lock G |title=Hepatitis C \u2013 contamination of toothbrushes: myth or reality? |journal=J. Viral Hepat. |volume=13 |issue=9 |pages=571\u201373 |date=September 2006 |pmid=16907842 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2893.2006.00735.x |url= |name-list-format=vanc|author2=Dirscherl M |author3=Obermeier F |display-authors=3 |last4=Gelbmann |first4=CM |last5=Hellerbrand |first5=C |last6=Knoll |first6=A |last7=Scholmerich |first7=J |last8=Jilg |first8=W }}</ref><ref name=CDC12 /> Appropriate caution should be taken regarding any medical condition that results in [[bleeding]], such as cuts and sores.<ref name=CDC12 /> HCV is not spread through casual contact, such as hugging, kissing, or sharing eating or cooking utensils.<ref name=CDC12>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/HCV/HCVfaq.htm |title= Hepatitis C FAQs for Health Professionals |publisher= Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) |accessdate= 2 January 2012 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120104063744/http://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/hcv/hcvfaq.htm |archivedate= 4 January 2012 }}</ref> Neither is it transmitted through food or water.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Wong T, Lee SS |title=Hepatitis C: a review for primary care physicians |journal=CMAJ |volume=174 |issue=5 |pages=649\u201359 |date=February 2006 |pmid=16505462 |pmc=1389829 |doi=10.1503/cmaj.1030034 |url=}}</ref>\n\n=== Mother-to-child transmission ===\n[[Mother-to-child transmission]] of {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} occurs in fewer than 10% of pregnancies.<ref name=Preg10>{{cite journal|last=Lam|first=NC|author2=Gotsch, PB|author3=Langan, RC|title=Caring for pregnant women and newborns with hepatitis B or C|journal=American Family Physician|date=2010-11-15|volume=82|issue=10|pages=1225\u201329|pmid=21121533|url=http://www.aafp.org/afp/2010/1115/p1225.pdf|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521080102/http://www.aafp.org/afp/2010/1115/p1225.pdf|archivedate=2013-05-21}}</ref> There are no measures that alter this risk.<ref name=Preg10 /> It is not clear when transmission occurs during pregnancy, but it may occur both during gestation and at delivery.<ref name=Pon2011 /> A long labor is associated with a greater risk of transmission.<ref name=World2007 /> There is no evidence that [[breastfeeding]] spreads HCV; however, to be cautious, an infected mother is advised to avoid breastfeeding if her nipples are cracked and bleeding,<ref>{{cite book |author=Mast EE |title=Mother-to-infant hepatitis C virus transmission and breastfeeding |journal=Advances in Experimental Medicine and Biology|volume=554 |pages=211\u201316|year=2004 |pmid=15384578 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-4242-8_18|isbn=978-1-4419-3461-1 }}</ref> or if her viral loads are high.<ref name=Pon2011 />\n\n== Diagnosis ==\n[[File:Hepatitis C serology.png|thumb|upright=1.4|Serologic profile of Hepatitis C infection]]\n\nThere are a number of diagnostic tests for {{nowrap|hepatitis C}}, including HCV [[antibody]] [[ELISA|enzyme immunoassay]] or ELISA, [[Western blot|recombinant immunoblot assay]], and quantitative HCV [[RNA]] [[polymerase chain reaction]] (PCR).<ref name=AFP2010 /> HCV [[RNA]] can be detected by PCR typically one to two weeks after infection, while antibodies can take substantially longer to form and thus be detected.<ref name=Tah2009 />\n\nChronic {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} is defined as infection with the {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} virus persisting for more than six months based on the presence of its RNA.<ref name=Book2011>{{cite book|title=Chronic Hepatitis C Virus Advances in Treatment, Promise for the Future|year=2011|publisher=Springer Verlag|isbn=978-1-4614-1191-8|pages=103\u201304|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6G7mff5DnBQC&pg=PA104|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529054409/https://books.google.com/books?id=6G7mff5DnBQC&pg=PA104|archivedate=2016-05-29}}</ref> Chronic infections are typically asymptomatic during the first few decades,<ref name=Book2011 /> and thus are most commonly discovered following the investigation of [[Liver function tests|elevated liver enzyme levels]] or during a routine screening of high-risk individuals. Testing is not able to distinguish between acute and chronic infections.<ref name=World2007 /> Diagnosis in the infant is difficult as maternal antibodies may persist for up to 18 months.<ref name=Robinson2008 />\n\n=== Serology ===\n{{nowrap|Hepatitis C}} testing typically begins with [[serology|blood testing]] to detect the presence of antibodies to the HCV, using an enzyme immunoassay.<ref name=AFP2010 /> If this test is positive, a confirmatory test is then performed to verify the immunoassay and to determine the [[viral load]].<ref name=AFP2010 /> A recombinant immunoblot assay is used to verify the immunoassay and the viral load is determined by an HCV RNA polymerase chain reaction.<ref name=AFP2010 /> If there is no RNA and the immunoblot is positive, it means that the person tested had a previous infection but cleared it either with treatment or spontaneously; if the immunoblot is negative, it means that the immunoassay was wrong.<ref name=AFP2010 /> It takes about 6\u20138 weeks following infection before the immunoassay will test positive.<ref name=ID2010 /> A number of tests are available as [[point of care testing]] which means that results are available within 30&nbsp;minutes.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Shivkumar|first=S|author2=Peeling, R |author3=Jafari, Y |author4=Joseph, L |author5= Pant Pai, N |title=Accuracy of Rapid and Point-of-Care Screening Tests for Hepatitis C: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis.|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=2012-10-16|volume=157|issue=8|pages=558\u201366|pmid=23070489|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-157-8-201210160-00006|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/562197b7c0b56dd4f55f8a2f743261005ac1c079}}</ref>\n\nLiver enzymes are variable during the initial part of the infection<ref name=Book2011 /> and on average begin to rise at seven weeks after infection.<ref name=ID2010 /> The elevation of liver enzymes does not closely follow disease severity.<ref name=ID2010 />\n\nThere are reports of negative plasma PCR for the viral genome with positive PCR for the viral genome within peripheral blood monocytes of liver cells.<ref name=Austria2018/> This condition has been termed occult HCV infection and it was first recognized in 2004.<ref name=Austria2018>{{cite journal |last1=Austria |first1=A |last2=Wu |first2=GY |title=Occult Hepatitis C Virus Infection: A Review. |journal=Journal of Clinical and Translational Hepatology |date=28 June 2018 |volume=6 |issue=2 |pages=155\u201360 |doi=10.14218/JCTH.2017.00053 |pmid=29951360|pmc=6018308 }}</ref>\n\n=== Biopsy ===\n[[Liver biopsy|Liver biopsies]] are used to determine the degree of liver damage present; however, there are risks from the procedure.<ref name=NEJM2011 /> The typical changes seen are [[lymphocyte]]s within the parenchyma, [[lymphoid follicles]] in [[portal triad]], and changes to the bile ducts.<ref name=NEJM2011 /> There are a number of blood tests available that try to determine the degree of [[hepatic fibrosis]] and alleviate the need for biopsy.<ref name=NEJM2011 />\n\n=== Screening ===\nIt is believed that only 5\u201350% of those infected in the United States and Canada are aware of their status.<ref name=Tato2010 /> Routine screening for those between the ages of 18 and 79 was recommended by the [[United States Preventive Services Task Force]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owens |first1=Douglas K. |last2=Davidson |first2=Karina W. |last3=Krist |first3=Alex H. |last4=Barry |first4=Michael J. |last5=Cabana |first5=Michael |last6=Caughey |first6=Aaron B. |last7=Donahue |first7=Katrina |last8=Doubeni |first8=Chyke A. |last9=Epling |first9=John W. |last10=Kubik |first10=Martha |last11=Ogedegbe |first11=Gbenga |last12=Pbert |first12=Lori |last13=Silverstein |first13=Michael |last14=Simon |first14=Melissa A. |last15=Tseng |first15=Chien-Wen |last16=Wong |first16=John B. |title=Screening for Hepatitis C Virus Infection in Adolescents and Adults |journal=JAMA |volume=323 |issue=10 |pages=970 |date=2 March 2020 |doi=10.1001/jama.2020.1123|pmid=32119076 |doi-access=free }}</ref> Previously testing was recommended for those at high risk, which includes injection drug users, those who have received blood transfusions before 1992,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Moyer|first=VA (on behalf of the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force)|title=Screening for Hepatitis C Virus Infection in Adults: U.S. Preventive Services Task Force Recommendation Statement.|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=2013-06-25|pmid=23798026|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-159-5-201309030-00672|volume=159|issue=5|pages=349\u201357|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/cc502bd0e6ef93d2c52e48d32c1923eb1f32d8de}}</ref> those who have been in jail, those on long term [[hemodialysis]],<ref name=Moyer2013>{{cite journal|last=Moyer|first=VA (U.S. Preventive Services Task Force)|title=Screening for hepatitis C virus infection in adults: U.S. Preventive Services Task Force recommendation statement.|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=2013-09-03|volume=159|issue=5|pages=349\u201357|pmid=23798026|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-159-5-201309030-00672|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/cc502bd0e6ef93d2c52e48d32c1923eb1f32d8de}}</ref> and those with tattoos.<ref name=Tato2010 /> Screening is also recommended in those with elevated liver enzymes, as this is frequently the only sign of chronic hepatitis.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Senadhi|first=V|title=A paradigm shift in the outpatient approach to liver function tests|journal=Southern Medical Journal|date=July 2011|volume=104|issue=7|pages=521\u201325|pmid=21886053|doi=10.1097/SMJ.0b013e31821e8ff5}}</ref> {{As of|2012}}, the U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) recommends a single screening test for those born between 1945 and 1965.<ref>{{cite journal  |vauthors=Smith BD, Morgan RL, Beckett GA, etal |title=Recommendations for the identification of chronic hepatitis C virus infection among persons born during 1945\u20131965 |journal=MMWR Recomm Rep |volume=61 |issue=RR-4 |pages=1\u201332 |date=August 2012 |pmid=22895429 |doi= |url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/pdf/rr/rr6104.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Testing Recommendations for Hepatitis C Virus Infection \u2013 HCV \u2013  Division of Viral Hepatitis | website=U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) | date=12 June 2019 | url=https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/hcv/guidelinesc.htm | access-date=11 January 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=People Born 1945\u20131965 (Baby Boomers) \u2013 Populations and Settings \u2013 Division of Viral Hepatitis | website=U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) | date=26 July 2019 | url=https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/populations/1945-1965.htm | access-date=11 January 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022221926/https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/populations/1945-1965.htm | archive-date=22 October 2019 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Final Update Summary: Hepatitis C: Screening | website=US Preventive Services Task Force | url=https://www.uspreventiveservicestaskforce.org/Page/Document/UpdateSummaryFinal/hepatitis-c-screening | access-date=11 January 2020}}</ref> In Canada one time screening is recommended for those born between 1945 and 1975.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shah |first1=Hemant |last2=Bilodeau |first2=Marc |last3=Burak |first3=Kelly W. |last4=Cooper |first4=Curtis |last5=Klein |first5=Marina |last6=Ramji |first6=Alnoor |last7=Smyth |first7=Dan |last8=Feld |first8=Jordan J. |title=The management of chronic hepatitis C: 2018 guideline update from the Canadian Association for the Study of the Liver |journal=CMAJ |date=4 June 2018 |volume=190 |issue=22 |pages=E677\u201387 |doi=10.1503/cmaj.170453 |pmid=29866893 |pmc=5988519 |issn=0820-3946}}</ref>\n\n== Prevention ==\n{{See also|Hepatitis C vaccine}}\n{{As of|2016}}, no approved [[vaccine]] protects against contracting {{nowrap|hepatitis C}}.<ref name=Vac2016 /> A combination of [[harm reduction]] strategies, such as the [[needle exchange programs|provision of new needles and syringes]] and treatment of [[substance abuse|substance use]], decreases the risk of {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} in intravenous drug users by about 75%.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Hagan|first=H|author2=Pouget, ER|author3=Des Jarlais, DC|title=A systematic review and meta-analysis of interventions to prevent hepatitis C virus infection in people who inject drugs|journal=The Journal of Infectious Diseases|date=2011-07-01|volume=204|issue=1|pages=74\u201383|pmid=21628661|doi=10.1093/infdis/jir196|pmc=3105033}}</ref> The screening of blood donors is important at a national level, as is adhering to [[universal precautions]] within healthcare facilities.<ref name=ID2010 /> In countries where there is an insufficient supply of sterile [[syringes]], medications should be given orally rather than via injection (when possible).<ref name=World2007 />\n\n== Treatment ==\nThose with chronic {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} are advised to avoid [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]] and medications [[Hepatotoxicity|toxic to the liver]].<ref name=AFP2010 /> They should also be [[vaccinated]] against [[hepatitis A]] and [[hepatitis B]] due to the increased risk if also infected.<ref name=AFP2010 /> Use of [[acetaminophen]] is generally considered safe at reduced doses.<ref name=Kim2016>{{cite journal|last1=Kim|first1=A|title=Hepatitis C Virus|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=September 2016|volume=165|issue=5|pages=ITC33\u2013ITC48|doi=10.7326/AITC201609060|pmid=27595226|type=Review}}</ref> [[Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug]]s (NSAIDs) are not recommended in those with advanced liver disease due to an increased risk of bleeding.<ref name=Kim2016/> [[Ultrasound]] surveillance for [[hepatocellular carcinoma]] is recommended in those with accompanying cirrhosis.<ref name=AFP2010 /> [[Coffee]] consumption has been associated with a slower rate of liver [[fibrosis|scarring]] in those infected with HCV.<ref name=Kim2016/>\n\n=== Medications ===\nApproximately 90% of chronic cases clear with treatment.<ref name=WHO2015 /> Treatment with [[antiviral medication]] is recommended in all people with proven chronic hepatitis C who are not at high risk of dying from other causes.<ref name=IDSA2015>{{cite journal|last1=AASLD/IDSA HCV Guidance|first1=Panel|title=Hepatitis C guidance: AASLD-IDSA recommendations for testing, managing, and treating adults infected with hepatitis C virus.|journal=Hepatology|date=September 2015|volume=62|issue=3|pages=932\u201354|pmid=26111063|doi=10.1002/hep.27950|doi-access=free}}</ref> People with the highest complication risk should be treated first, with the risk of complications based on the degree of liver scarring.<ref name=IDSA2015 /> The initial recommended treatment depends on the type of hepatitis C virus, if the person has received previous hepatitis C treatment, and whether or not a person has cirrhosis.<ref name=IDSA2017/> [[Direct-acting antivirals]] (DAAs) may reduce the number of the infected people.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jakobsen |first1=JC |last2=Nielsen |first2=EE |last3=Feinberg |first3=J |last4=Katakam |first4=KK |last5=Fobian |first5=K |last6=Hauser |first6=G |last7=Poropat |first7=G |last8=Djurisic |first8=S |last9=Weiss |first9=KH |last10=Bjelakovic |first10=M |last11=Bjelakovic |first11=G |last12=Klingenberg |first12=SL |last13=Liu |first13=JP |last14=Nikolova |first14=D |last15=Koretz |first15=RL |last16=Gluud |first16=C |title=Direct-acting antivirals for chronic hepatitis C. |journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |date=18 September 2017 |volume=9 |pages=CD012143 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD012143.pub3 |pmid=28922704|pmc=6484376 }}</ref>\n\n====No prior treatment====\n*HCV genotype 1a (no cirrhosis): 8 weeks of [[glecaprevir/pibrentasvir]] or [[ledipasvir/sofosbuvir]] (the latter for people who do not have [[HIV/AIDS]], are not [[African-American]], and have less than 6 million HCV viral copies per milliliter of blood) or 12 weeks of [[elbasvir/grazoprevir]], ledipasvir/sofosbuvir, or [[sofosbuvir/velpatasvir]].<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype1a\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment-Naive Genotype 1a Without Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt1a/no-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref> [[Sofosbuvir]] with either [[daclatasvir]] or [[simeprevir]] may also be used.<ref name=IDSA2017>{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C|url=http://hcvguidelines.org/sites/default/files/full-guidance-pdf/HCVGuidance_April_12_2017_b.pdf|accessdate=28 July 2017|date=12 April 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710035751/http://hcvguidelines.org/sites/default/files/full-guidance-pdf/HCVGuidance_April_12_2017_b.pdf|archivedate=2017-07-10}}</ref>\n*HCV genotype 1a (with compensated cirrhosis): 12 weeks of elbasvir/grazoprevir, glecaprevir/pibrentasvir, ledipasvir/sofosbuvir, or sofosbuvir/velpatasvir. An alternative treatment regimen of elbasvir/grazoprevir with weight-based ribavirin for 16 weeks can be used if the HCV is found to have antiviral resistance mutations against NS5A protease inhibitors.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype1acompensated\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment-Naive Genotype 1a With Compensated Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt1a/compensated-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref> \n*HCV genotype 1b (no cirrhosis): 8 weeks of glecaprevir/pibrentasvir or ledipasvir/sofosbuvir (with the aforementioned limitations for the latter as above) or 12 weeks of elbasvir/grazoprevir, ledipasvir/sofosbuvir, or sofosbuvir/velpatasvir. Alternative regimens include 12 weeks of [[ombitasvir/paritaprevir/ritonavir]] with [[dasabuvir]] or 12 weeks of sofosbuvir with either daclatasvir or simeprevir.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype1b\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment-Naive Genotype 1b Without Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt1b/no-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref> \n*HCV genotype 1b (with compensated cirrhosis): 12 weeks of elbasvir/grazoprevir, glecaprevir/pibrentasvir, ledipasvir/sofosbuvir, or sofosbuvir/velpatasvir. A 12-week course of paritaprevir/ritonavir/ombitasvir with dasabuvir may also be used.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype1bcompensated\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment \u2013 Naive Genotype 1b With Compensated Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt1b/compensated-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*HCV genotype 2 (no cirrhosis): 8 weeks of glecaprevir/pibrentasvir or 12 weeks of sofosbuvir/velpatasvir. Alternatively, 12 weeks of sofosbuvir/daclatasvir can be used.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype2\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment-Naive Genotype 2 Without Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt2/no-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*HCV genotype 2 (with compensated cirrhosis): 12 weeks of sofosbuvir/velpatasvir or glecaprevir/pibrentasvir. An alternative regimen of sofosbuvir/daclatasvir can be used for 16\u201324 weeks.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype2compensated\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment-Naive Genotype 2 With Compensated Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt2/compensated-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*HCV genotype 3 (no cirrhosis): 8 weeks of glecaprevir/pibrentasvir or 12 weeks of sofosbuvir/velpatasvir or sofosbuvir and daclatasvir.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype3\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment \u2013 Naive Genotype 3 Without Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt3/no-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*HCV genotype 3 (with compensated cirrhosis): 12 weeks of glecaprevir/pibrentasvir, sofosbuvir/velpatasvir, or if certain antiviral mutations are present, 12 weeks of sofosbuvir/velpatasvir/[[voxilaprevir]] (when certain antiviral mutations are present), or 24 weeks of sofosbuvir and daclatasvir.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype3compensated\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment \u2013 Naive Genotype 3 With Compensated Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt3/compensated-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*HCV genotype 4 (no cirrhosis): 8 weeks of glecaprevir/pibrentasvir or 12 weeks of sofosbuvir/velpatasvir, elbasvir/grazoprevir, or ledipasvir/sofosbuvir. A 12-week regimen of ombitasvir/paritaprevir/ritonavir is also acceptable in combination with weight-based [[ribavirin]].<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype4\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment \u2013 Naive Genotype 4 Without Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt4/no-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*HCV genotype 4 (with compensated cirrhosis): A 12-week regimen of sofosbuvir/velpatasvir, glecaprevir/pibrentasavir, elbasvir/grazoprevir, or ledipasvir/sofosbuvir is recommended. A 12-week course of ombitasvir/paritaprevir/ritonavir  with weight-based ribavirin is an acceptable alternative.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype4compensated\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment-Naive Genotype 4 With Compensated Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt4/compensated-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*HCV genotype 5 or 6 (with or without compensated cirrhosis): If no cirrhosis is present, then 8 weeks of glecaprevir/pibrentasvir is recommended. If cirrhosis is present, then a 12-week course of glecaprevir/pibrentasvir, sofosbuvir/velpatasvir, or ledipasvir/sofosbuvir is warranted.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotypes5and6\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment \u2013 Naive Genotype 5 or 6|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt5-6|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nChronic infection can be cured in more than 90% of people with medications.<ref name=CDC2019>{{cite web |title=Hepatitis C Questions and Answers for Health Professionals |url=https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/hcv/hcvfaq.htm |website=www.cdc.gov |accessdate=23 July 2019 |language=en-us |date=2 July 2019}}</ref><!-- Quote = Over 90% of HCV infected persons can be cured of HCV infection regardless of HCV genotype, with 8-12 weeks of oral therapy --> Getting access to these treatments however can be expensive.<ref name=WHO2015 /> The combination of [[Sofosbuvir/velpatasvir/voxilaprevir|sofosbuvir, velpatasvir, and voxilaprevir]] may be used in those who have previously been treated with sofosbuvir or other drugs that inhibit NS5A and were not cured.<ref>{{cite press release | title=FDA approves Vosevi for Hepatitis C|url=https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-approves-vosevi-hepatitis-c |website=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) |accessdate=27 July 2017|date=18 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170723062106/https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/ucm567467.htm|archivedate=23 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 2011, treatments consisted of a combination of [[pegylated interferon]] alpha and ribavirin for a period of 24 or 48 weeks, depending on HCV [[genotype]].<ref name=AFP2010 /> This produces cure rates of between 70 and 80% for genotype 2 and 3, respectively, and 45 to 70% for genotypes 1 and 4.<ref name=NEJM2013>{{cite journal|last=Liang|first=TJ|author2=Ghany, MG|title=Current and future therapies for hepatitis C virus infection.|journal=The New England Journal of Medicine|date=May 16, 2013|volume=368|issue=20|pages=1907\u201317|pmid=23675659|doi=10.1056/NEJMra1213651|pmc=3893124}}</ref> Adverse effects with these treatments were common, with half of people getting [[Influenza-like illness|flu-like symptoms]] and a third experiencing emotional problems.<ref name=AFP2010 /> Treatment during the first six months is more effective than once {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} has become chronic.<ref name=Tah2009 /> In those with chronic hepatitis B, treatment for hepatitis C results in reactivation of hepatitis B in about 25%.<ref name=M\u00fccke2018>{{cite journal|last1=M\u00fccke|first1=Marcus M|last2=Backus|first2=Lisa I|last3=M\u00fccke|first3=Victoria T|last4=Coppola|first4=Nicola|last5=Preda|first5=Carmen M|last6=Yeh|first6=Ming-Lun|last7=Tang|first7=Lydia S Y|last8=Belperio|first8=Pamela S|last9=Wilson|first9=Eleanor M|last10=Yu|first10=Ming-Lung|last11=Zeuzem|first11=Stefan|last12=Herrmann|first12=Eva|last13=Vermehren|first13=Johannes |title=Hepatitis B virus reactivation during direct-acting antiviral therapy for hepatitis C: a systematic review and meta-analysis |journal=The Lancet Gastroenterology & Hepatology|volume=3|issue=3|pages=172\u201380|date=January 2018 |doi=10.1016/S2468-1253(18)30002-5|pmid=29371017}}</ref>\n\n=== Surgery ===\nCirrhosis due to hepatitis C is a common reason for [[liver transplant]]ation<ref name=Tah2009>{{cite journal|last=Ozaras|first=R|author2=Tahan, V|title=Acute hepatitis C: prevention and treatment|journal=Expert Review of Anti-infective Therapy|date=April 2009|volume=7|issue=3|pages=351\u201361|pmid=19344247|doi=10.1586/eri.09.8}}</ref> though the virus usually (80\u201390% of cases) recurs afterwards.<ref name=NEJM2011 /><ref>{{cite book|last=Sanders|first=Mick|title=Mosby's Paramedic Textbook|year=2011|publisher=Jones & Bartlett Publishers|isbn=978-0-323-07275-5|page=839|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PJyhIH8N8qgC&pg=PA839|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511134533/https://books.google.com/books?id=PJyhIH8N8qgC&pg=PA839|archivedate=2016-05-11}}</ref> Infection of the graft leads to 10\u201330% of people developing cirrhosis within five years.<ref name=Ciria2013>{{cite journal  |vauthors=Ciria R, Pleguezuelo M, Khorsandi SE, etal |title=Strategies to reduce hepatitis C virus recurrence after liver transplantation |journal=World J Hepatol |volume=5 |issue=5 |pages=237\u201350 |date=May 2013 |pmid=23717735 |pmc=3664282 |doi=10.4254/wjh.v5.i5.237 |url=}}</ref> Treatment with pegylated interferon and ribavirin post-transplant decreases the risk of recurrence to 70%.<ref name=Coilly2013>{{cite journal |vauthors=Coilly A, Roche B, Samuel D |title=Current management and perspectives for HCV recurrence after liver transplantation |journal=Liver Int. |volume=33 Suppl 1 |issue= |pages=56\u201362 |date=February 2013 |pmid=23286847 |doi=10.1111/liv.12062 |url=}}</ref> A 2013 review found unclear evidence regarding if antiviral medication was useful if the graft became reinfected.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gurusamy |first1=KS |last2=Tsochatzis |first2=E |last3=Toon |first3=CD |last4=Xirouchakis |first4=E |last5=Burroughs |first5=AK |last6=Davidson |first6=BR |title=Antiviral interventions for liver transplant patients with recurrent graft infection due to hepatitis C virus. |journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |date=4 December 2013 |issue=12 |pages=CD006803 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD006803.pub4 |pmid=24307460}}</ref>\n\n=== Alternative medicine ===\nSeveral [[alternative medicine|alternative therapies]] are claimed by their proponents to be helpful for {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} including [[Silybum marianum|milk thistle]], [[ginseng]], and [[colloidal silver]].<ref name=NCCAM>[http://nccam.nih.gov/health/providers/digest/hepatitisC-science.htm Hepatitis C and CAM: What the Science Says] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110320175202/http://nccam.nih.gov/health/providers/digest/hepatitisC-science.htm |date=2011-03-20 }}. [[National Center for Complementary and Alternative Medicine]] (NCCAM). March 2011. (Retrieved 7 March 2011)</ref> However, no alternative therapy has been shown to improve outcomes in {{nowrap|hepatitis C}}, and no evidence exists that alternative therapies have any effect on the virus at all.<ref name=NCCAM /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Liu|first=J|author2=Manheimer E |author3=Tsutani K |author4=Gluud C  |title=Medicinal herbs for hepatitis C virus infection: a Cochrane hepatobiliary systematic review of randomized trials|journal=The American Journal of Gastroenterology|date=March 2003|volume=98|issue=3|pages=538\u201344|pmid=12650784|doi=10.1111/j.1572-0241.2003.07298.x|doi-broken-date=2020-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rambaldi|first1=A|last2=Jacobs|first2=BP|last3=Gluud|first3=C|title=Milk thistle for alcoholic and/or hepatitis B or C virus liver diseases.|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|date=17 October 2007|issue=4|pages=CD003620|pmid=17943794|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD003620.pub3}}</ref>\n\n== Prognosis ==\n{{anchor|Sustained viral response}}\n[[File:Hepatitis C world map - DALY - WHO2004.svg|thumb|upright=1.3|[[Disability-adjusted life year]] for hepatitis C in 2004 per 100,000&nbsp;inhabitants\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n{{legend|#b3b3b3|no data}}\n{{legend|#ffff65|<10}}\n{{legend|#fff200|10\u201315}}\n{{legend|#ffdc00|15\u201320}}\n{{legend|#ffc600|20\u201325}}\n{{legend|#ffb000|25\u201330}}\n{{legend|#ff9a00|30\u201335}}\n{{Col-break}}\n{{legend|#ff8400|35\u201340}}\n{{legend|#ff6e00|40\u201345}}\n{{legend|#ff5800|45\u201350}}\n{{legend|#ff4200|50\u201375}}\n{{legend|#ff2c00|75\u2013100}}\n{{legend|#cb0000|>100}}\n{{col-end}}]]\nThe responses to treatment is measured by ''sustained viral response'' (SVR), defined as the absence of detectable [[RNA]] of the [[hepatitis C virus]] in [[serum (blood)|blood serum]] for at least 24 weeks after discontinuing the treatment,<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Helms|editor1-first=Richard A.|editor2-last=Quan|editor2-first=David J.|title=Textbook of Therapeutics: Drug and Disease Management|date=2006|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|location=Philadelphia, PA [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-7817-5734-8|page=1340|edition=8.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YjrQla7JPD0C|accessdate=7 November 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151205070808/https://books.google.com/books?id=YjrQla7JPD0C|archivedate=5 December 2015}}</ref> and rapid virological response (RVR) defined as undetectable levels achieved within four weeks of treatment. Successful treatment decreases the future risk of hepatocellular carcinoma by 75%.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Morgan RL, Baack B, Smith BD, Yartel A, Pitasi M, Falck-Ytter Y |title=Eradication of Hepatitis C Virus Infection and the Development of Hepatocellular Carcinoma: A Meta-analysis of Observational Studies |journal=Annals of Internal Medicine |volume=158 |issue=5 Pt 1 |pages=329\u201337 |date=March 2013 |pmid=23460056 |doi=10.7326/0003-4819-158-5-201303050-00005 |url=|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nPrior to 2012 sustained response occurs in about 40\u201350% in people with HCV genotype 1 given 48 weeks of treatment.<ref name=NEJM2011 /> A sustained response is seen in 70\u201380% of people with HCV genotypes 2 and 3 with 24 weeks of treatment.<ref name=NEJM2011 /> A sustained response occurs about 65% in those with genotype 4 after 48 weeks of treatment. The evidence for treatment in genotype 6 disease is sparse and what evidence there is supports 48 weeks of treatment at the same doses used for genotype 1 disease.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Fung J |title=Chronic hepatitis C virus genotype 6 infection: response to pegylated interferon and ribavirin |journal=The Journal of Infectious Diseases |volume=198 |issue=6 |pages=808\u201312 |date=September 2008 |pmid=18657036 |doi=10.1086/591252 |name-list-format=vanc |author2=Lai CL |author3=Hung I |display-authors=3 |last4=Young |first4=John |last5=Cheng |first5=Charles |last6=Wong |first6=Danny |last7=Yuen |first7=Man\u2013Fung |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n=== Spontaneous resolution ===\nAbout 15\u201345% of those infected spontaneously clear the virus within 6 months, with the rest going on the develop chronic infection.<ref name=\"WHO2015\" /> Spontaneous resolution following acute infection appears more common in females, and younger persons, and appears to also be influenced by genetic factors.<ref name=Book2011p4/> Chronic infection may also resolve spontaneously months or years after the acute phase, though this is unusual.<ref name=\"Book2011p4\" />\n\n== Epidemiology ==\n[[File:HCV prevalence 1999.png|left|thumb|upright=1.3|Prevalence of hepatitis C worldwide in 1999]]\nIt is estimated that 143&nbsp;million people (2%) of people globally are living with chronic {{nowrap|hepatitis C}}.<ref name=GBD2015Pre/> About 3\u20134&nbsp;million people are infected per year, and more than 350,000 people die yearly from hepatitis C-related diseases.<ref name=WHO2011 /> During 2010 it is estimated that 16,000 people died from acute infections while 196,000 deaths occurred from liver cancer secondary to the infection.<ref name=Loz2012>{{cite journal|last=Lozano|first=R|title=Global and regional mortality from 235 causes of death for 20 age groups in 1990 and 2010: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2010.|journal=Lancet|date=2012-12-15|volume=380|issue=9859|pages=2095\u2013128|pmid=23245604|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(12)61728-0|hdl=10536/DRO/DU:30050819}}</ref> Rates have increased substantially in the 20th century due to a combination of intravenous drug abuse and reused but poorly sterilized medical equipment.<ref name=\"World2007\" />\n\nRates are high (>3.5% population infected) in Central and East Asia, North Africa and the Middle East, they are intermediate (1.5%-3.5%) in South and Southeast Asia, sub-Saharan Africa, Andean, Central and Southern Latin America, Caribbean, Oceania, Australasia and Central, Eastern and Western Europe; and they are low (<1.5%) in Asia-Pacific, Tropical Latin America and North America.<ref name=Mohd2013>{{cite journal|last=Mohd Hanafiah|first=K|author2=Groeger, J |author3=Flaxman, AD |author4= Wiersma, ST |title=Global epidemiology of hepatitis C virus infection: new estimates of age-specific antibody to HCV seroprevalence.|journal=Hepatology|date=April 2013|volume=57|issue=4|pages=1333\u201342|pmid=23172780|doi=10.1002/hep.26141}}</ref>\n\nAmong those chronically infected, the risk of [[cirrhosis]] after 20 years varies between studies but has been estimated at ~10\u201315% for men and ~1\u20135% for women. The reason for this difference is not known. Once cirrhosis is established, the rate of developing [[hepatocellular carcinoma]] is ~1\u20134% per year.<ref name=Yu2009>{{cite journal | author = Yu ML |author2=Chuang WL | title = Treatment of chronic hepatitis C in Asia: when East meets West | journal = J. Gastroenterol. Hepatol. | volume = 24 | issue = 3 | pages = 336\u201345 |date=March 2009 | pmid = 19335784 | doi = 10.1111/j.1440-1746.2009.05789.x }}</ref> Rates of new infections have decreased in the Western world since the 1990s due to improved screening of blood before transfusion.<ref name=Tah2009 />\n\nIn the United States, about 2% of people have chronic {{nowrap|hepatitis C}}.<ref name=AFP2010 /> In 2014, an estimated 30,500 new acute hepatitis C cases occurred (0.7 per 100,000 population), an increase from 2010\u20132012.<ref>{{cite web |title = U.S. 2014 Surveillance Data for Viral Hepatitis, Statistics & Surveillance, Division of Viral Hepatitis |publisher = CDC |url = https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/statistics/2014surveillance/commentary.htm#bkgrndC |accessdate = 2016-08-04 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160808042215/http://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/statistics/2014surveillance/commentary.htm#bkgrndC |archivedate = 2016-08-08 }}</ref> The number of deaths from hepatitis C has increased to 15,800 in 2008<ref>{{cite web|last=Table 4.5|title=Number and rate of deaths with hepatitis C listed as a cause of death, by demographic characteristic and year \u2014 United States, 2004\u20132008|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/Statistics/2010Surveillance/Table4.5.htm|work=Viral Hepatitis on the CDC web site|publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, Atlanta, GA|accessdate=28 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309141408/http://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/Statistics/2010Surveillance/Table4.5.htm|archivedate=9 March 2014}}</ref> having overtaken HIV/AIDS as a cause of death in the US in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hepatitis Death Rate Creeps past AIDS|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/28/health/research/hepatitis-c-deaths-creep-past-aids-study-finds.html?_r=0|accessdate=28 July 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=27 February 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630112442/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/28/health/research/hepatitis-c-deaths-creep-past-aids-study-finds.html?_r=0|archivedate=30 June 2017}}</ref> In 2014 it was the single greatest cause of infectious death in the United States.<ref name=\"CDC2016a\">{{cite web|title=Hepatitis C Kills More Americans than Any Other Infectious Disease|url=https://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2016/p0504-hepc-mortality.html|publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|accessdate=3 August 2016|date=May 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809080556/http://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2016/p0504-hepc-mortality.html|archivedate=9 August 2016}}</ref> This mortality rate is expected to increase, as those infected by transfusion before HCV testing become apparent.<ref name=Cola2004>{{cite book |editor1-last=Colacino |editor1-first=J. M. |editor2-last=Heinz |editor2-first=B. A. |last1=Blatt |first1=L. M. |last2=Tong |first2=M. |title=Hepatitis prevention and treatment |year=2004 |publisher=Birkh\u00e4user |location=Basel |isbn=978-3-7643-5956-0 |page=32 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KwSWN_QtVLUC&pg=PA32 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624071639/https://books.google.com/books?id=KwSWN_QtVLUC&pg=PA32 |archivedate=2016-06-24 }}</ref> In Europe the percentage of people with chronic infections has been estimated to be between 0.13 and 3.26%.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Blachier M, Leleu H, Peck-Radosavljevic M, Valla DC, Roudot-Thoraval F |title=The burden of liver disease in Europe: a review of available epidemiological data |journal=J. Hepatol. |volume=58 |issue=3 |pages=593\u2013608 |date=March 2013 |pmid=23419824 |doi=10.1016/j.jhep.2012.12.005 |url=|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nIn England about 160,000 people are chronically infected.<ref name=UK2015 /> Between 2006 and 2011 28,000, about 3%, received treatment.<ref name=UK2015>{{cite news|title=Commissioning supplement: Health inequalities tell a tale of data neglect|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/resource-centre/supplements/commissioning-supplement-health-inequalities-tell-a-tale-of-data-neglect/5083351.article#.VUKckYq4_eM|accessdate=30 April 2015|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=19 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728084950/http://www.hsj.co.uk/resource-centre/supplements/commissioning-supplement-health-inequalities-tell-a-tale-of-data-neglect/5083351.article#.VUKckYq4_eM|archivedate=28 July 2015}}</ref> About half of people using a needle exchange in London in 2017/8 tested positive for hepatitis C of which half were unaware of they had it.<ref>{{cite news |title=More than half of patients using needle exchange pilot tested positive for Hepatitis C |url=https://www.pharmaceutical-journal.com/20204857.article |accessdate=15 August 2018 |publisher=Pharmaceutical Journal |date=17 May 2018}}</ref>  As part of a bid to eradicate hepatitis C by 2025 [[NHS England]] conducted a large procurement exercise in 2019. [[Merck Sharp & Dohme]], [[Gilead Sciences]], and [[Abbvie]] were awarded contracts, which, together, are worth up to \u00a31 billion over five years.<ref>{{cite news |title=Legal action firm among winners for largest medicines procurement |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/quality-and-performance/legal-action-firm-among-winners-for-largest-medicines-procurement/7024966.article |accessdate=9 June 2019 |publisher=Health Service Journal |date=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe total number of people with this infection is higher in some countries in [[Africa]] and [[Asia]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Scott |last=Holmberg |editor1-first=Gary W. |editor1-last=Brunette |editor2-first=Phyllis E. |editor2-last=Kozarsky |editor3-first=Alan J. |editor3-last=Magill |editor4-first=David R. |editor4-last=Shlim |editor5-first=Amanda D. |editor5-last=Whatley |title=CDC Health Information for International Travel 2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=978-0-19-976901-8 |page=[https://archive.org/details/cdchealthinforma0000unse/page/231 231] |url=https://archive.org/details/cdchealthinforma0000unse/page/231 |url-status=live |date=2011-05-12 |url-access=registration }}</ref> Countries with particularly high rates of infection include Egypt (22%), Pakistan (4.8%) and China (3.2%).<ref name=WHO2011>{{cite web |title=Hepatitis C |publisher=World Health Organization (WHO) |url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs164/en/index.html |date=June 2011 |accessdate=2011-07-13 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712194903/http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs164/en/index.html |archivedate=2011-07-12 }}</ref> It is believed that the high prevalence in Egypt is linked to a now-discontinued mass-treatment campaign for [[schistosomiasis]], using improperly sterilized glass syringes.<ref name=World2007 />\n\nSince 2014, extremely effective medication have been available to eradication the disease in 8-12 weeks in most people.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Lombardi|first=Andrea|last2=Mondelli|first2=Mario U.|last3=ESCMID Study Group for Viral Hepatitis (ESGVH)|date=March 2019|title=Hepatitis C: Is eradication possible?|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30472772|journal=Liver International: Official Journal of the International Association for the Study of the Liver|volume=39|issue=3|pages=416\u2013426|doi=10.1111/liv.14011|issn=1478-3231|pmid=30472772|doi-access=free}}</ref> In 2015 about 950,000 people were treated while 1.7 million new infections occurred, meaning that overall the number of people with HCV increased.<ref name=\":0\" /> These numbers differ by country and improved in 2016, with some countries achieving higher cure rates than new infection rates (mostly high income countries).<ref name=\":0\" /> By 2018, twelve countries are on track to achieve HCV elimination.<ref name=\":0\" /> While DAAs will curb new infections, it is less clear whether they impact overall deaths and morbidity.<ref name=\":0\" /> Furthermore, for DAAs to be effective, people need to be aware of their infection - it is currently estimated that worldwide only 20% of infected people are aware of their infection (in the US fewer than half were aware).<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== History ==\nIn the mid-1970s, [[Harvey J. Alter]], Chief of the Infectious Disease Section in the Department of Transfusion Medicine at the [[National Institutes of Health]], and his research team demonstrated how most post-[[blood transfusion|transfusion]] hepatitis cases were not due to [[hepatitis A]] or [[Hepatitis B|B]] viruses. Despite this discovery, international research efforts to identify the virus, initially called ''non-A, non-B hepatitis'' (NANBH), failed for the next decade. In 1987, [[Michael Houghton (virologist)|Michael Houghton]], [[Qui-Lim Choo]], and [[George Kuo]] at [[Chiron Corporation]], collaborating with [[Daniel W. Bradley]] at the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]], used a novel [[molecular cloning]] approach to identify the unknown organism and develop a diagnostic test.<ref name = Boyer>{{cite book | isbn = 978-0-7923-8760-2 | last = Boyer | first = JL | title = Liver cirrhosis and its development: proceedings of the Falk Symposium 115 | pages = [https://books.google.com/books?id=n5P696E7T0wC&pg=PA344#v=onepage&q&f=false 344] | publisher = [[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]] | year = 2001 }}</ref> In 1988, Alter confirmed the virus by verifying its presence in a panel of NANBH specimens. In April 1989, the discovery of HCV was published in two articles in the journal ''Science''.<ref name=\"choo\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Choo QL, Kuo G, Weiner AJ, Overby LR, Bradley DW, Houghton M |author-link4=Lacy Overby |title=Isolation of a cDNA clone derived from a blood-borne non-A, non-B viral hepatitis genome |journal=Science |volume=244 |issue=4902 |pages=359\u201362 |date=April 1989 |pmid=2523562 |doi=10.1126/science.2523562|url=http://courses.washington.edu/conj504/readings/polyak_reading1.pdf |citeseerx=10.1.1.469.3592 |bibcode=1989Sci...244..359C }}</ref><ref name=\"kuo\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kuo G, Choo QL, Alter HJ, Gitnick G, Redeker A, Purcell R, Miyamura T, Dienstag J, Alter M |title=An assay for circulating antibodies to a major etiologic virus of human non-A, non-B hepatitis |journal=Science |volume=244 |issue=4902 |pages=362\u20134 |date=April 1989 |pmid=2496467 |doi=10.1126/science.2496467 |display-authors=3|bibcode=1989Sci...244..362K }}</ref> The discovery led to significant improvements in diagnosis and improved antiviral treatment.<ref name=Web2015 /><ref name = Boyer /> In 2000, Drs. Alter and Houghton were honored with the [[Lasker Award]] for Clinical Medical Research for \"pioneering work leading to the discovery of the virus that causes hepatitis C and the development of screening methods that reduced the risk of blood transfusion-associated hepatitis in the U.S. from 30% in 1970 to virtually zero in 2000.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laskerfoundation.org/awards/library/2000clinical.shtml |title=2000 Winners Albert Lasker Award for Clinical Medical Research |accessdate=2006-04-21 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080225184627/http://www.laskerfoundation.org/awards/library/2000clinical.shtml |archivedate=February 25, 2008 }}. Retrieved 20 February 2008.</ref>\n\nChiron filed for several patents on the virus and its diagnosis.<ref name=\"houghton\">{{cite patent | country = EP | number = 0318216 | status = patent | title = NANBV diagnostics | gdate = 1989-05-31 | invent1 = Houghton, M | invent2 = Choo, Q-L | invent3 = Kuo, G | assign1 = Chiron }}</ref> A competing patent application by the CDC was dropped in 1990 after Chiron paid $1.9&nbsp;million to the CDC and $337,500 to Bradley. In 1994, Bradley sued Chiron, seeking to invalidate the patent, have himself included as a coinventor, and receive damages and royalty income. He dropped the suit in 1998 after losing before an appeals court.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilken |title=United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit |url=http://www.ll.georgetown.edu/federal/judicial/fed/opinions/96opinions/96-1536.html |publisher=United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit |accessdate=11 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091119144520/http://www.ll.georgetown.edu/federal/judicial/fed/opinions/96opinions/96-1536.html |archivedate=19 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Society and culture ==\n{{See also|List of people with hepatitis C}}\n[[World Hepatitis Day]], held on July 28, is coordinated by the World Hepatitis Alliance.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Eurosurveillance editorial team|title=World Hepatitis Day 2011|journal=[[Eurosurveillance]]|date=2011-07-28|volume=16|issue=30|pmid=21813077|url=http://www.eurosurveillance.org/images/dynamic/EE/V16N30/art19926.pdf|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111125163506/http://eurosurveillance.org/images/dynamic/EE/V16N30/art19926.pdf|archivedate=2011-11-25}}</ref> The economic costs of hepatitis C are significant both to the individual and to society. In the United States the average lifetime cost of the disease was estimated at US$33,407 in 2003<ref name=Cost2006>{{cite journal|last=Wong|first=JB|title=Hepatitis C: cost of illness and considerations for the economic evaluation of antiviral therapies |journal=PharmacoEconomics |year=2006 |volume=24 |issue=7 |pages=661\u201372 |pmid=16802842|doi=10.2165/00019053-200624070-00005}}</ref> with the cost of a liver transplant {{as of|2011|lc=y}} costing approximately US$200,000.<ref name=Cost2011 /> In Canada the cost of a course of antiviral treatment is as high as 30,000&nbsp;CAD in 2003,<ref>{{cite web|title=Hepatitis C Prevention, Support and Research ProgramHealth Canada|url=http://www.phac-aspc.gc.ca/hepc/pubs/psrpmideval-ppsrevalinter/i_problem-eng.php|publisher=Public Health Agency of Canada|accessdate=10 January 2012|date=Nov 2003|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322182718/http://www.phac-aspc.gc.ca/hepc/pubs/psrpmideval-ppsrevalinter/i_problem-eng.php|archivedate=22 March 2011}}</ref> while the United States costs are between 9,200 and 17,600 in 1998 USD.<ref name=Cost2006 /> In many areas of the world, people are unable to afford treatment with antivirals as they either lack insurance coverage or the insurance they have will not pay for antivirals.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-first=Howard|editor1-last=Thomas|editor2-first=Stanley|editor2-last=Lemon|editor3-first=Arie|editor3-last=Zuckerman|title=Viral Hepatitis|year=2008|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|location=Oxford|isbn=978-1-4051-4388-2|pages=532|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nT2dauLXoYAC&pg=PA532|edition=3rd|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617164927/https://books.google.com/books?id=nT2dauLXoYAC&pg=PA532|archivedate=2016-06-17}}</ref> In the English [[National Health Service]] treatment rates for hepatitis C are higher among wealthier groups per 2010\u20132012 data.<ref name=UK2015 /> Spanish anaesthetist [[Juan Maeso]] infected 275 patients between 1988 and 1997 as he used the same needles to give both himself and the patients opioids.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spanish Anesthetist Infected Patients|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/15/AR2007051500921.html|accessdate=13 July 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=15 May 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822072146/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/15/AR2007051500921.html|archivedate=22 August 2016}}</ref> For this he was jailed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spanish Hep C anaesthetist jailed|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/6657509.stm|accessdate=13 July 2016|work=BBC|date=15 May 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071023220711/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/6657509.stm|archivedate=23 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Special populations ==\n\n=== Children and pregnancy ===\n{{Main|HCV in children and pregnancy}}\nCompared with adults, infection in children is much less well understood. Worldwide the prevalence of hepatitis C virus infection in pregnant women and children has been estimated to 1\u20138% and 0.05\u20135% respectively.<ref name=Arshad2011>{{cite journal |vauthors=Arshad M, El-Kamary SS, Jhaveri R |title=Hepatitis C virus infection during pregnancy and the newborn period\u2014are they opportunities for treatment? |journal=J. Viral Hepat. |volume=18 |issue=4 |pages=229\u201336 |date=April 2011 |pmid=21392169 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2893.2010.01413.x }}</ref> The [[Vertically transmitted infection|vertical transmission]] rate has been estimated to be 3\u20135% and there is a high rate of spontaneous clearance (25\u201350%) in the children. Higher rates have been reported for both vertical transmission (18%, 6\u201336% and 41%).<ref name=Hunt1997>{{cite journal |vauthors=Hunt CM, Carson KL, Sharara AI |title=Hepatitis C in pregnancy |journal=Obstet Gynecol |volume=89 |issue=5 Pt 2 |pages=883\u201390 |date=May 1997 |pmid=9166361 |doi=10.1016/S0029-7844(97)81434-2 }}</ref><ref name=Thomas1998>{{cite journal |vauthors=Thomas SL, Newell ML, Peckham CS, Ades AE, Hall AJ |title=A review of hepatitis C virus (HCV) vertical transmission: risks of transmission to infants born to mothers with and without HCV viraemia or human immunodeficiency virus infection |journal=Int J Epidemiol |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=108\u201317 |date=February 1998 |pmid=9563703 |doi=10.1093/ije/27.1.108|doi-access=free }}</ref> and prevalence in children (15%).<ref name=Fischler2007>{{cite journal |author=Fischler B |title=Hepatitis C virus infection |journal=Semin Fetal Neonatal Med |volume=12 |issue=3 |pages=168\u201373 |date=June 2007 |pmid=17320495 |doi=10.1016/j.siny.2007.01.008 }}</ref>\n\nIn developed countries transmission around the time of birth is now the leading cause of HCV infection. In the absence of virus in the mother's blood transmission seems to be rare.<ref name=Thomas1998 /> Factors associated with an increased rate of infection include membrane rupture of longer than 6 hours before delivery and procedures exposing the infant to maternal blood.<ref name=Indolfi2009>{{cite journal |vauthors=Indolfi G, Resti M |title=Perinatal transmission of hepatitis C virus infection |journal=J. Med. Virol. |volume=81 |issue=5 |pages=836\u201343 |date=May 2009 |pmid=19319981 |doi=10.1002/jmv.21437 }}</ref> Cesarean sections are not recommended. Breastfeeding is considered safe if the nipples are not damaged. Infection around the time of birth in one child does not increase the risk in a subsequent pregnancy. All genotypes appear to have the same risk of transmission.\n\nHCV infection is frequently found in children who have previously been presumed to have non-A, non-B hepatitis and cryptogenic liver disease.<ref name=\"Gonz\u00e1lez-Peralta1997\">{{cite journal |author=Gonz\u00e1lez-Peralta RP |title=Hepatitis C virus infection in pediatric patients |journal=Clin Liver Dis |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=691\u2013705, ix |date=November 1997 |pmid=15560066 |doi=10.1016/s1089-3261(05)70329-9}}</ref> The presentation in childhood may be asymptomatic or with elevated liver function tests.<ref name=Suskind2004>{{cite journal |vauthors=Suskind DL, Rosenthal P |title=Chronic viral hepatitis |journal=Adolesc Med Clin |volume=15 |issue=1 |pages=145\u201358, x\u2013xi |date=February 2004 |pmid=15272262 |doi= 10.1016/j.admecli.2003.11.001}}</ref> While infection is commonly asymptomatic both cirrhosis with liver failure and hepatocellular carcinoma may occur in childhood.\n\n=== Immunosuppressed ===\n{{See also|Hepatitis C and HIV coinfection}}\nThe rate of hepatitis C in immunosuppressed people is higher. This is particularly true in those with  [[human immunodeficiency virus]] infection, recipients of [[organ transplant]]s, and those with [[hypogammaglobulinemia]].<ref name=Einav2002>{{cite journal |vauthors=Einav S, Koziel MJ |title=Immunopathogenesis of hepatitis C virus in the immunosuppressed host |journal=Transpl Infect Dis |volume=4 |issue=2 |pages=85\u201392 |date=June 2002 |pmid=12220245 |doi=10.1034/j.1399-3062.2002.t01-2-02001.x}}</ref> Infection in these people is associated with an unusually rapid progression to cirrhosis. People with stable HIV who never received medication for HCV, may be treated with a combination of [[peginterferon]] plus [[ribavirin]] with caution to the possible side effects.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Iorio |first1=A |last2=Marchesini |first2=E |last3=Awad |first3=T |last4=Gluud |first4=LL |title=Antiviral treatment for chronic hepatitis C in patients with human immunodeficiency virus. |journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |date=20 January 2010 |issue=1 |pages=CD004888 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD004888.pub2 |pmid=20091566}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\n{{As of|2011}}, there are about one hundred medications in development for hepatitis C.<ref name=Cost2011>{{cite journal|last1 = El Khoury | first1 = AC | last2 = Klimack | first2 = WK | last3 = Wallace | first3 = C | last4 = Razavi | first4 = H |title=Economic burden of hepatitis C-associated diseases in the United States|journal=Journal of Viral Hepatitis|date=1 December 2011|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2893.2011.01563.x|volume=19|issue=3|pages=153\u201360|pmid=22329369}}</ref> These include vaccines to treat hepatitis, [[immunomodulators]], and [[cyclophilin]] inhibitors, among others.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ahn|first=J|author2=Flamm, SL|title=Hepatitis C therapy: other players in the game|journal=Clinics in Liver Disease|date=August 2011|volume=15|issue=3|pages=641\u201356|pmid=21867942|doi=10.1016/j.cld.2011.05.008}}</ref> These potential new treatments have come about due to a better understanding of the hepatitis C virus.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Vermehren|first=J|author2=Sarrazin, C|title=New HCV therapies on the horizon|journal=Clinical Microbiology and Infection|date=February 2011|volume=17|issue=2|pages=122\u201334|pmid=21087349|doi=10.1111/j.1469-0691.2010.03430.x }}</ref> There are a number of vaccines under development and some have shown encouraging results.<ref name=Vac2016>{{cite journal|last1=Abdelwahab|first1=KS|last2=Ahmed Said|first2=ZN|title=Status of hepatitis C virus vaccination: Recent update.|journal=World Journal of Gastroenterology|date=14 January 2016|volume=22|issue=2|pages=862\u201373|pmid=26811632|doi=10.3748/wjg.v22.i2.862|pmc=4716084}}</ref>\n\nThe combination of [[sofosbuvir]] and [[velpatasvir]] in one trial (reported in 2015) resulted in cure rates of 99%.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Feld|first1=Jordan J. |last2=Jacobson|first2=Ira M. |last3=H\u00e9zode|first3=Christophe |last4=Asselah|first4=Tarik |last5=Ruane|first5=Peter J. |last6=Gruener|first6=Norbert |last7=Abergel|first7=Armand |last8=Mangia|first8=Alessandra |last9=Lai|first9=Ching-Lung |last10=Chan|first10=Henry L.Y. |last11=Mazzotta|first11=Francesco |last12=Moreno|first12=Christophe |last13=Yoshida|first13=Eric |last14=Shafran|first14=Stephen D.|last15=Towner|first15=William J.|last16=Tran|first16=Tram T.|last17=McNally|first17=John|last18=Osinusi|first18=Anu|last19=Svarovskaia|first19=Evguenia|last20=Zhu|first20=Yanni|last21=Brainard|first21=Diana M.|last22=McHutchison|first22=John G.|last23=Agarwal|first23=Kosh|last24=Zeuzem|first24=Stefan|title=Sofosbuvir and Velpatasvir for HCV Genotype 1, 2, 4, 5, and 6 Infection|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=373 |issue=27 |date=16 November 2015|pages=2599\u20132607|doi=10.1056/NEJMoa1512610|pmid=26571066 |url=http://qmro.qmul.ac.uk/xmlui/handle/123456789/17933 |hdl=10722/226358 |doi-access=free}}</ref> More studies are needed to investigate the role of the preventive antiviral medication against HCV recurrence after transplantation.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gurusamy |first1=KS |last2=Tsochatzis |first2=E |last3=Toon |first3=CD |last4=Davidson |first4=BR |last5=Burroughs |first5=AK |title=Antiviral prophylaxis for the prevention of chronic hepatitis C virus in patients undergoing liver transplantation. |journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |date=2 December 2013 |issue=12 |pages=CD006573 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD006573.pub3 |pmid=24297303|pmc=6599865 }}</ref>\n\n=== Animal models ===\nOne barrier to finding treatments for hepatitis C is the lack of a suitable animal model. Despite moderate success, current research highlights the need for pre-clinical testing in mammalian systems such as [[mouse]], particularly for the development of vaccines in poorer communities. Currently, [[Common chimpanzee|chimpanzees]] remain the available living system to study, yet their use has ethical concerns and regulatory restrictions. While scientists have made use of human cell culture systems such as hepatocytes, questions have been raised about their accuracy in reflecting the body's response to infection.<ref name=Sand2013>{{cite journal|last=Sandmann|first=L|author2=Ploss, A|title=Barriers of hepatitis C virus interspecies transmission.|journal=Virology|date=2013-01-05|volume=435|issue=1|pages=70\u201380|pmid=23217617|doi=10.1016/j.virol.2012.09.044|pmc=3523278}}</ref>\n\nOne aspect of hepatitis research is to reproduce infections in mammalian models. A strategy is to introduce liver tissues from humans into mice, a technique known as xenotransplantation. This is done by generating chimeric mice, and exposing the mice HCV infection. This engineering process is known to create humanized mice, and provide opportunities to study hepatitis C within the 3D architectural design of the liver and evaluating antiviral compounds.<ref name=Sand2013 /> Alternatively, generating inbred mice with susceptibility to HCV would simplify the process of studying mouse models.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical condition classification and resources\n| DiseasesDB      = 5783\n| ICD10           = {{ICD10|B|17|1|b|15}}, {{ICD10|B|18|2|b|15}}\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|070.70}},{{ICD9|070.4}}, {{ICD9|070.5}}\n| OMIM            = 609532\n| MedlinePlus     = 000284\n| eMedicineSubj   = med\n| eMedicineTopic  = 993\n| eMedicine_mult  = {{EMedicine2|ped|979}}\n| MeshID          = D006526\n| SNOMED CT       = 186643004\n}}\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|Hep C en.ogg|2014-07-26}}\n{{commons}}\n*{{curlie|Health/Conditions_and_Diseases/Digestive_Disorders/Liver/Hepatitis/Hepatitis_C|Hepatitis C}}\n* {{cite web|title=Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C|url=http://www.hcvguidelines.org/|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=IDSA/AASLD|accessdate=28 July 2017}}\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|Viruses}}\n{{Viral diseases}}\n{{gastroenterology}}\n\n[[Category:Hepatitis C| ]]\n[[Category:Healthcare-associated infections]]\n[[Category:Infectious causes of cancer]]\n[[Category:RTT(full)]]\n[[Category:RTTEM]]\n[[Category:Viral diseases]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Human viral infection}}\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{Good Article}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Hepatitis C\n| image           = HCV EM picture 2.png\n| caption         = [[Electron micrograph]] of [[hepatitis C virus]] from cell culture (scale = 50&nbsp;[[nanometers]])\n| field           = [[Gastroenterology]], [[Infectious disease (medical specialty)|infectious disease]]\n| symptoms        = Typically none<ref name=CDC2016 />\n| complications   = [[Liver failure]], [[hepatocellular carcinoma|liver cancer]], [[esophageal varices|esophageal]] and [[gastric varices]]<ref name=Sherris2004 />\n| onset           = \n| duration        = Long term (80%)<ref name=CDC2016 />\n| causes          = [[Hepatitis C virus]] usually spread by blood-to-blood contact<ref name=CDC2016 /><ref name=Mah2010/>\n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = Blood testing for [[antibodies]] or viral [[RNA]]<ref name=CDC2016 />\n| differential    = \n| prevention      = Clean needles, testing donated blood<ref name=WHO2015 />\n| treatment       = Medications, [[liver transplant]]<ref name=NEJM2011 />\n| medication      = [[Sofosbuvir]], [[simeprevir]]<ref name=CDC2016 /><ref name=WHO2015 />\n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = 143 million / 2% (2015)<ref name=GBD2015Pre/>\n| deaths          = 496,000 (2015)<ref name=GBD2015De/>\n}}\n<!-- Definition and symptoms -->\n'''Hepatitis C''' is an [[infectious disease]] caused by the [[hepatitis C virus]] (HCV) that primarily affects the [[liver]].<ref name=Sherris2004>{{cite book | title = Sherris Medical Microbiology | edition = 4th | publisher = McGraw Hill | year = 2004 | pages=551\u201352 | isbn = 978-0-8385-8529-0 |veditors=Ryan KJ, Ray CG }}</ref> During the initial infection people often have mild or no symptoms.<ref name=CDC2016 /> Occasionally a fever, dark urine, abdominal pain, and [[jaundice|yellow tinged skin]] occurs.<ref name=CDC2016 /> The virus persists in the liver in about 75% to 85% of those initially infected.<ref name=CDC2016 /> Early on chronic infection typically has no symptoms.<ref name=CDC2016 /> Over many years however, it often leads to [[liver disease]] and occasionally [[cirrhosis]].<ref name=CDC2016 /> In some cases, those with cirrhosis will develop serious complications such as [[liver failure]], [[hepatocellular carcinoma|liver cancer]], or [[esophageal varices|dilated blood vessels in the esophagus]] and [[gastric varices|stomach]].<ref name=Sherris2004 />\n\n<!-- Cause and diagnosis -->\nHCV is spread primarily by blood-to-blood contact associated with [[intravenous drug use]], poorly sterilized medical equipment, [[needlestick injuries]] in healthcare, and [[blood transfusions|transfusions]].<ref name=CDC2016 /><ref name=Mah2010>{{cite journal|last=Maheshwari|first=A|author2=Thuluvath, PJ|title=Management of acute hepatitis C|journal=Clinics in Liver Disease|date=February 2010|volume=14|issue=1|pages=169\u201376, x|pmid=20123448|doi=10.1016/j.cld.2009.11.007}}</ref> Using blood screening, the risk from a transfusion is less than one per two million.<ref name=CDC2016 /> It may also be spread from an infected mother to her baby during birth.<ref name=CDC2016 /> It is not spread by superficial contact.<ref name=WHO2015 /> It is one of five known hepatitis viruses: [[hepatitis A|A]], [[hepatitis B|B]], C, [[hepatitis D|D]], and [[hepatitis E|E]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Viral Hepatitis: A through E and Beyond|url=http://www.niddk.nih.gov/health-information/health-topics/liver-disease/viral-hepatitis-a-through-e/Pages/facts.aspx|website=National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases|accessdate=4 February 2016|date=April 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202083731/http://www.niddk.nih.gov/health-information/health-topics/liver-disease/viral-hepatitis-a-through-e/Pages/facts.aspx|archivedate=2 February 2016}}</ref> Diagnosis is by blood testing to look for either [[antibodies]] to the virus or its [[RNA]].<ref name=CDC2016 /> Testing is recommended in all people who are at risk.<ref name=CDC2016>{{cite web|title=Hepatitis C FAQs for Health Professionals|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/hcv/hcvfaq.htm|website=CDC|accessdate=4 February 2016|date=January 8, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160121073721/http://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/hcv/hcvfaq.htm|archivedate=21 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Prevention and treatment -->\nThere is no [[vaccine]] against hepatitis C.<ref name=CDC2016 /><ref name=Web2015>{{cite journal|last1=Webster|first1=Daniel P|last2=Klenerman|first2=Paul|last3=Dusheiko|first3=Geoffrey M|title=Hepatitis C|journal=The Lancet|volume=385|issue=9973|year=2015|pages=1124\u201335|pmid=25687730|pmc=4878852|issn=0140-6736|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(14)62401-6}}</ref> Prevention includes [[harm reduction]] efforts among people who use intravenous drugs and testing donated blood.<ref name=WHO2015 /> Chronic infection can be cured about 95% of the time with antiviral medications such as [[sofosbuvir]] or [[simeprevir]].<ref name=CDC2016 /><ref name=WHO2015 /> [[Peginterferon]] and [[ribavirin]] were earlier generation treatments that had a cure rate of less than 50% and greater side effects.<ref name=WHO2015/><ref name=Kim2016/> Getting access to the newer treatments however can be expensive.<ref name=WHO2015 /> Those who develop cirrhosis or liver cancer may require a [[liver transplant]].<ref name=NEJM2011 /> Hepatitis C is the leading reason for liver transplantation, though the virus usually recurs after transplantation.<ref name=NEJM2011>{{cite journal|last=Rosen|first=HR|title=Clinical practice. Chronic hepatitis C infection|journal=The New England Journal of Medicine|date=2011-06-23|volume=364|issue=25|pages=2429\u201338|pmid=21696309|doi=10.1056/NEJMcp1006613|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/ee00276a6c2b5e9af4841bce7922b00b92ff20a4}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Epidemiology and history -->\nAn estimated 143 million people (2%) worldwide are infected with hepatitis C {{as of| 2015|lc=yes}}.<ref name=GBD2015Pre>{{cite journal|last1=GBD 2015 Disease and Injury Incidence and Prevalence|first1=Collaborators.|title=Global, regional, and national incidence, prevalence, and years lived with disability for 310 diseases and injuries, 1990\u20132015: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2015.|journal=Lancet|date=8 October 2016|volume=388|issue=10053|pages=1545\u20131602|pmid=27733282|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(16)31678-6|pmc=5055577}}</ref> In 2013, about eleven million new cases occurred.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Global Burden of Disease Study 2013|first1=Collaborators|title=Global, regional, and national incidence, prevalence, and years lived with disability for 301 acute and chronic diseases and injuries in 188 countries, 1990\u20132013: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2013.|journal=Lancet|date=22 August 2015|volume=386|issue=9995|pages=743\u2013800|pmid=26063472|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(15)60692-4|pmc=4561509}}</ref> It occurs most commonly in Africa and Central and East Asia.<ref name=WHO2015>{{cite web|title=Hepatitis C Fact sheet N\u00b0164|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs164/en/|website=WHO|accessdate=4 February 2016|date=July 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131041006/http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs164/en/|archivedate=31 January 2016}}</ref> About 167,000 deaths due to liver cancer and 326,000 deaths due to cirrhosis occurred in 2015 due to hepatitis C.<ref name=GBD2015De>{{cite journal|last1=GBD 2015 Mortality and Causes of Death|first1=Collaborators.|title=Global, regional, and national life expectancy, all-cause mortality, and cause-specific mortality for 249 causes of death, 1980\u20132015: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2015.|journal=Lancet|date=8 October 2016|volume=388|issue=10053|pages=1459\u20131544|pmid=27733281|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(16)31012-1|pmc=5388903}}</ref> The existence of hepatitis C \u2013 originally identifiable only as a type of non-[[Hepatitis A|A]] non-[[Hepatitis B|B]] [[hepatitis]] \u2013 was suggested in the 1970s and proven in 1989.<ref name=\"pmid19781804\">{{cite journal |author=Houghton M |title=The long and winding road leading to the identification of the hepatitis C virus |journal=Journal of Hepatology |volume=51 |issue=5 |pages=939\u201348 |date=November 2009 |pmid=19781804 |doi=10.1016/j.jhep.2009.08.004 |url=http://www.journal-of-hepatology.eu/article/S0168-8278%2809%2900535-2/fulltext|doi-access=free }}</ref> Hepatitis C infects only humans and [[Common chimpanzee|chimpanzees]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Shors|first=Teri|title=Understanding viruses|publisher=Jones & Bartlett Learning|location=Burlington, MA|isbn=978-0-7637-8553-6|pages=535|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Uk8xP5LRHr4C&pg=PA535|edition=2nd|year=2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515225439/https://books.google.com/books?id=Uk8xP5LRHr4C&pg=PA535|archivedate=2016-05-15}}</ref>\n[[File:Wikipedia-VideoWiki-Hepatitis C.webm|thumb|thumbtime=0:28|upright=1.3|Video summary ([[Wikipedia:VideoWiki/Hepatitis C|script]])]]\n\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n== Signs and symptoms ==\n\n=== Acute infection ===\n[[Acute (medicine)|Acute]] symptoms develop in some 20\u201330% of those infected.<ref name=CDC2016/> When this occurs, it is generally 4\u201312 weeks following infection (but it may take from 2 weeks to 6 months for acute symptoms to appear).<ref name=CDC2016/><ref name=\"WHO2015\" />\n\nSymptoms are generally mild and vague, and may include fatigue, [[nausea]] and vomiting, fever, [[myalgia|muscle]] or [[Arthralgia|joint pains]], abdominal pain, [[Anorexia (symptom)|decreased appetite]] and weight loss, jaundice (occurs in ~25% of those infected), dark urine, and clay-coloured stools.<ref name=CDC2016/><ref name=\"Book2011p4\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6G7mff5DnBQC&pg=PA4|title=Chronic Hepatitis C Virus Advances in Treatment, Promise for the Future|publisher=Springer Verlag|year=2011|isbn=978-1-4614-1191-8|page=14|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617181023/https://books.google.com/books?id=6G7mff5DnBQC&pg=PA4|archivedate=2016-06-17|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"AFP2010\">{{cite journal|last=Wilkins|first=T|author2=Malcolm JK|author3=Raina D|author4=Schade RR|title=Hepatitis C: diagnosis and treatment|journal=American Family Physician|date=2010-06-01|volume=81|issue=11|pages=1351\u201357|pmid=20521755|url=http://www.aafp.org/afp/2010/0601/p1351.pdf|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521071850/http://www.aafp.org/afp/2010/0601/p1351.pdf|archivedate=2013-05-21}}</ref> There is no evidence that acute hepatitis C can alone cause [[acute liver failure]], though liver injury and elevated liver enzymes may occur.<ref name=Book2011p4/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Manka|first=Paul|last2=Verheyen|first2=Jens|last3=Gerken|first3=Guido|last4=Canbay|first4=Ali|date=April 2016|title=Liver Failure due to Acute Viral Hepatitis (A\u2013E)|journal=Visceral Medicine|volume=32|issue=2|pages=80\u201385|doi=10.1159/000444915|issn=2297-4725|pmc=4926881|pmid=27413724}}</ref> Symptoms and laboratory findings suggestive of liver disease should prompt further tests and can thus help establish a diagnosis of hepatitis C infection early on.<ref name=AFP2010/>\n\nFollowing the acute phase, the infection may resolve spontaneously in 10\u201350% of affected people; this occurs more frequently in young people, and females.<ref name=\"Book2011p4\" />\n\n=== Chronic infection ===\nAbout 80% of those exposed to the virus develop a chronic infection.<ref name=Lancet2011 /> This is defined as the presence of detectable viral replication for at least six months. Most experience minimal or no symptoms during the initial few decades of the infection.<ref name=Book2011 /> Chronic {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} can be associated with fatigue<ref name=ID2010 /> and mild cognitive problems.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Forton|first=DM|author2=Allsop, JM |author3=Cox, IJ |author4=Hamilton, G |author5=Wesnes, K |author6=Thomas, HC |author7= Taylor-Robinson, SD |title=A review of cognitive impairment and cerebral metabolite abnormalities in patients with hepatitis C infection|journal=AIDS|date=October 2005|volume=19 |issue=Suppl 3|pages=S53\u201363|pmid=16251829|doi=10.1097/01.aids.0000192071.72948.77}}</ref> Chronic infection after several years may cause [[cirrhosis]] or [[liver cancer]].<ref name=NEJM2011 /> The liver enzymes are normal in 7\u201353%.<ref name=Nicot2011 /> Late relapses after apparent cure have been reported, but these can be difficult to distinguish from reinfection.<ref name=Nicot2011 />\n\n[[Steatohepatitis|Fatty changes to the liver]] occur in about half of those infected and are usually present before cirrhosis develops.<ref name=\"El-Zayadi2008\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Paradis|first=V|author2=Bedossa, P|title=Definition and natural history of metabolic steatosis: histology and cellular aspects|journal=Diabetes & Metabolism|date=December 2008|volume=34|issue=6 Pt 2|pages=638\u201342|pmid=19195624|doi=10.1016/S1262-3636(08)74598-1}}</ref> Usually (80% of the time) this change affects less than a third of the liver.<ref name=\"El-Zayadi2008\">{{cite journal|last=El-Zayadi|first=AR|title=Hepatic steatosis: a benign disease or a silent killer.|journal=World Journal of Gastroenterology|date=2008-07-14|volume=14|issue=26|pages=4120\u201326|pmid=18636654|doi=10.3748/wjg.14.4120|pmc=2725370}}</ref> Worldwide hepatitis C is the cause of 27% of cirrhosis cases and 25% of hepatocellular carcinoma.<ref name=World2007>{{cite journal|last=Alter |first=MJ |title=Epidemiology of hepatitis C virus infection |journal=World Journal of Gastroenterology |date=2007-05-07 |volume=13 |issue=17 |pages=2436\u201341 |pmid=17552026 |pmc=4146761 |doi=10.3748/wjg.v13.i17.2436 }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> About 10\u201330% of those infected develop cirrhosis over 30&nbsp;years.<ref name=NEJM2011 /><ref name=AFP2010 /> Cirrhosis is more common in those also infected with [[hepatitis B]], [[schistosoma]], or HIV, in [[alcoholic]]s and in those of male gender.<ref name=AFP2010 /> In those with hepatitis C, excess alcohol increases the risk of developing cirrhosis 100-fold.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mueller|first=S|author2=Millonig G|author3=Seitz HK|title=Alcoholic liver disease and hepatitis C: a frequently underestimated combination|journal=World Journal of Gastroenterology|date=2009-07-28|volume=15|issue=28|pages=3462\u201371|pmid=19630099|doi=10.3748/wjg.15.3462|pmc=2715970|url=http://www.wjgnet.com/downpdf.asp?url=/1007-9327/15/3462|format=PDF}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=Level C |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Those who develop cirrhosis have a 20-fold greater risk of [[hepatocellular carcinoma]]. This transformation occurs at a rate of 1\u20133% per year.<ref name=NEJM2011 /><ref name=AFP2010 /> Being infected with hepatitis B in addition to hepatitis C increases this risk further.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fattovich|first=G|author2=Stroffolini, T |author3=Zagni, I |author4= Donato, F |title=Hepatocellular carcinoma in cirrhosis: incidence and risk factors.|journal=Gastroenterology|date=November 2004|volume=127|issue=5 Suppl 1|pages=S35\u201350|pmid=15508101|doi=10.1053/j.gastro.2004.09.014}}</ref>\n\nLiver cirrhosis may lead to [[portal hypertension]], [[ascites]] (accumulation of fluid in the abdomen), [[coagulopathy|easy bruising or bleeding]], varices (enlarged veins, especially in the stomach and esophagus), [[jaundice]], and a syndrome of cognitive impairment known as [[hepatic encephalopathy]].<ref name=Tah2009 /> Ascites occurs at some stage in more than half of those who have a chronic infection.<ref name=Zaltron2012>{{cite journal|last=Zaltron|first=S|author2=Spinetti, A |author3=Biasi, L |author4=Baiguera, C |author5= Castelli, F |title=Chronic HCV infection: epidemiological and clinical relevance.|journal=BMC Infectious Diseases|year=2012|volume=12 Suppl 2|pages=S2|pmid=23173556|doi=10.1186/1471-2334-12-S2-S2 |pmc=3495628}}</ref>\n\n=== Extrahepatic complications ===\nThe most common problem due to {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} but not involving the liver is mixed [[cryoglobulinemia]] (usually the type II form) \u2013 an [[vasculitis|inflammation of small and medium-sized blood vessels]].<ref name=Cryo2013>{{cite journal| title =Review Article: Therapy for Hepatitis C Virus\u2013Related Cryoglobulinemic Vasculitis| journal =N Engl J Med| date =September 12, 2013| vauthors =Dammacco F, Sansonno D| volume =369| issue =11| pages =1035\u201345| doi =10.1056/NEJMra1208642| pmid =24024840| url =https://semanticscholar.org/paper/0ef3d558b0baf48b389b413380a82c9a6458e1b0}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Iannuzzella | first1 = F | last2 = Vaglio | first2 = A | last3 = Garini | first3 = G |title=Management of hepatitis C virus-related mixed cryoglobulinemia |journal=Am. J. Med. |volume=123 |issue=5 |pages=400\u201308 |date=May 2010 |pmid=20399313 |doi=10.1016/j.amjmed.2009.09.038 |url=}}</ref> {{nowrap|Hepatitis C}} is also associated with autoimmune disorders such as [[Sj\u00f6gren's syndrome]], [[lichen planus]], [[thrombocytopenia|a low platelet count]], [[porphyria cutanea tarda]], [[necrolytic acral erythema]], [[insulin resistance]], [[diabetes mellitus]], [[diabetic nephropathy]], autoimmune [[thyroiditis]], and B-cell [[lymphoproliferative disorder]]s.<ref name=Extrahepatic>{{cite journal | last1 = Zignego | first1 = AL | last2 = Ferri | first2 = C | last3 = Pileri | first3 = SA | last4 = Caini | first4 = P | last5 = Bianchi | first5 = FB |title=Extrahepatic manifestations of Hepatitis C Virus infection: a general overview and guidelines for a clinical approach |journal=Digestive and Liver Disease |volume=39 |issue=1 |pages=2\u201317 |date=January 2007 |pmid=16884964 |doi=10.1016/j.dld.2006.06.008 | display-authors=3 }}</ref><ref name=Ko2012>{{cite journal|last=Ko|first=HM|author2=Hernandez-Prera, JC |author3=Zhu, H |author4=Dikman, SH |author5=Sidhu, HK |author6=Ward, SC |author7= Thung, SN |title=Morphologic features of extrahepatic manifestations of hepatitis C virus infection.|journal=Clinical & Developmental Immunology|year=2012|volume=2012|pages=1\u20139|pmid=22919404|doi=10.1155/2012/740138 |pmc=3420144}}</ref> 20\u201330% of people infected have [[rheumatoid factor]] \u2013 a type of antibody.<ref name=Dammacco2000>{{cite journal|last=Dammacco|first=F|author2=Sansonno, D |author3=Piccoli, C |author4=Racanelli, V |author5=D'Amore, FP |author6= Lauletta, G |title=The lymphoid system in hepatitis C virus infection: autoimmunity, mixed cryoglobulinemia, and Overt B-cell malignancy.|journal=Seminars in Liver Disease|year=2000|volume=20|issue=2|pages=143\u201357|pmid=10946420|doi=10.1055/s-2000-9613}}</ref> Possible associations include [[prurigo nodularis|Hyde's prurigo nodularis]]<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lee|first=MR|author2=Shumack, S|title=Prurigo nodularis: a review|journal=The Australasian Journal of Dermatology|date=November 2005|volume=46|issue=4|pages=211\u201318; quiz 219\u201320|pmid=16197418|doi=10.1111/j.1440-0960.2005.00187.x}}</ref> and [[membranoproliferative glomerulonephritis]].<ref name=ID2010 />  [[Cardiomyopathy]] with associated [[Heart arrhythmia|abnormal heart rhythms]] has also been reported.<ref name=Matsumori2006>{{cite book|last=Matsumori|first=A|title=Role of hepatitis C virus in cardiomyopathies.|journal=Ernst Schering Research Foundation Workshop|volume=55|year=2006|issue=55|pages=99\u2013120|pmid=16329660|doi=10.1007/3-540-30822-9_7|isbn=978-3-540-23971-0}}</ref> A variety of [[central nervous system]] disorders has been reported.<ref name=Monaco2012>{{cite journal|last=Monaco|first=S|author2=Ferrari, S |author3=Gajofatto, A |author4=Zanusso, G |author5= Mariotto, S |title=HCV-related nervous system disorders.|journal=Clinical & Developmental Immunology|year=2012|volume=2012|pages=1\u20139|pmid=22899946|doi=10.1155/2012/236148 |pmc=3414089}}</ref> Chronic infection seems to be associated with an increased risk of [[pancreatic cancer]].<ref name=Web2015 /><ref name=Xu2013>{{cite journal|last=Xu|first=JH|author2=Fu, JJ |author3=Wang, XL |author4=Zhu, JY |author5=Ye, XH |author6= Chen, SD |title=Hepatitis B or C viral infection and risk of pancreatic cancer: A meta-analysis of observational studies.|journal=World Journal of Gastroenterology|date=2013-07-14|volume=19|issue=26|pages=4234\u201341|pmid=23864789|doi=10.3748/wjg.v19.i26.4234 |pmc=3710428}}</ref> People may experience other issues in the mouth such as [[xerostomia|dryness]], [[sialadenitis|salivary duct stones]], and crusted lesions around the mouth.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1998-07-01|title=Hepatitis C virus infection: Review and implications for the dentist|journal=Oral Surgery, Oral Medicine, Oral Pathology, Oral Radiology, and Endodontology|volume=86|issue=1|pages=8\u201322|doi=10.1016/S1079-2104(98)90143-3|pmid=9690239|issn=1079-2104|last1=Lodi|first1=G.|last2=Porter|first2=S.R|last3=Scully|first3=C.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Carrozzo|first=M.|last2=Gandolfo|first2=S.|date=2003-03-01|title=Oral Diseases Possibly Associated with Hepatitis C Virus|journal=Critical Reviews in Oral Biology & Medicine|volume=14|issue=2|pages=115\u201327|doi=10.1177/154411130301400205|pmid=12764074|issn=1045-4411|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Dental Management of the Medically Compromised Patient|year=2013|isbn=978-0323080286|location=|page=151|last1=Little|first1=James W.|last2=Falace|first2=Donald A. |first3=Craig |last3=Miller |first4=Nelson L. |last4=Rhodus}}</ref>\n\n=== Occult infection ===\nPersons who have been infected with hepatitis C may appear to clear the virus but remain infected.<ref name=Sugden2012>{{cite journal|last=Sugden|first=PB|author2=Cameron, B |author3=Bull, R |author4=White, PA |author5= Lloyd, AR |title=Occult infection with hepatitis C virus: friend or foe?|journal=Immunology and Cell Biology|date=September 2012|volume=90|issue=8|pages=763\u201373|pmid=22546735|doi=10.1038/icb.2012.20}}</ref> The virus is not detectable with conventional testing but can be found with ultra-sensitive tests.<ref name=\"Carre\u00f1o2006\">{{cite journal|last=Carre\u00f1o|first=V|title=Occult hepatitis C virus infection: a new form of hepatitis C.|journal=World Journal of Gastroenterology|date=2006-11-21|volume=12|issue=43|pages=6922\u201325|pmid=17109511|pmc=4087333|doi=10.3748/wjg.12.6922}}</ref> The original method of detection was by demonstrating the viral [[genome]] within liver biopsies, but newer methods include an antibody test for the virus' core protein and the detection of the viral genome after first concentrating the viral particles by [[ultracentrifugation]].<ref name=\"Carre\u00f1oGarc\u00eda2011\">{{cite journal|last=Carre\u00f1o Garc\u00eda|first=V|author2=Nebreda, JB |author3=Aguilar, IC |author4= Quiroga Est\u00e9vez, JA |title=[Occult hepatitis C virus infection].|journal=Enfermedades Infecciosas y Microbiologia Clinica|date=March 2011|volume=29 Suppl 3|pages=14\u201319|pmid=21458706|doi=10.1016/S0213-005X(11)70022-2}}</ref> A form of infection with persistently moderately elevated serum liver enzymes but without antibodies to hepatitis C has also been reported.<ref name=Pham2010>{{cite journal|last=Pham|first=TN|author2=Coffin, CS |author3=Michalak, TI |title=Occult hepatitis C virus infection: what does it mean?|journal=Liver International|date=April 2010|volume=30|issue=4|pages=502\u201311|pmid=20070513|doi=10.1111/j.1478-3231.2009.02193.x}}</ref> This form is known as cryptogenic occult infection.\n\nSeveral clinical pictures have been associated with this type of infection.<ref name=\"Carre\u00f1o2012\">{{cite journal|last=Carre\u00f1o|first=V|author2=Bartolom\u00e9, J |author3=Castillo, I |author4= Quiroga, JA |title=New perspectives in occult hepatitis C virus infection.|journal=World Journal of Gastroenterology|date=2012-06-21|volume=18|issue=23|pages=2887\u201394|pmid=22736911|doi=10.3748/wjg.v18.i23.2887 |pmc=3380315}}</ref> It may be found in people with anti-hepatitis-C antibodies but with normal serum levels of liver enzymes; in antibody-negative people with ongoing elevated liver enzymes of unknown cause; in healthy populations without evidence of liver disease; and in groups at risk for HCV infection including those on hemodialysis or family members of people with occult HCV. The clinical relevance of this form of infection is under investigation.<ref name=\"Carre\u00f1o2008\">{{cite journal|last=Carre\u00f1o|first=V|author2=Bartolom\u00e9, J |author3=Castillo, I |author4= Quiroga, JA |title=Occult hepatitis B virus and hepatitis C virus infections.|journal=Reviews in Medical Virology|date=May\u2013June 2008|volume=18|issue=3|pages=139\u201357|pmid=18265423|doi=10.1002/rmv.569}}</ref> The consequences of occult infection appear to be less severe than with chronic infection but can vary from minimal to hepatocellular carcinoma.<ref name=\"Carre\u00f1oGarc\u00eda2011\" />\n\nThe rate of occult infection in those apparently cured is controversial but appears to be low.<ref name=Nicot2011>{{cite book|last=Nicot|first=F|title=Occult hepatitis C virus infection: Where are we now?|year=2004|isbn=978-953-307-883-0|chapter=Chapter 19. Liver biopsy in modern medicine.}}</ref> 40% of those with hepatitis but with both negative hepatitis C serology and the absence of detectable viral genome in the serum have hepatitis C virus in the liver on biopsy.<ref name=Scott2007>{{cite journal|last=Scott|first=JD|author2=Gretch, DR|title=Molecular diagnostics of hepatitis C virus infection: a systematic review.|journal=JAMA: The Journal of the American Medical Association|date=2007-02-21|volume=297|issue=7|pages=724\u201332|pmid=17312292|doi=10.1001/jama.297.7.724|doi-access=free}}</ref> How commonly this occurs in children is unknown.<ref name=Robinson2008>{{cite journal|last=Robinson|first=JL|title=Vertical transmission of the hepatitis C virus: Current knowledge and issues|journal=Paediatr Child Health|date=July 4, 2008|volume=13|issue=6|pages=529\u201334|pmc=2532905|pmid=19436425|doi=10.1093/pch/13.6.529}}</ref>\n\n== Virology ==\n{{Main|Hepatitis C virus}}\n\nThe [[hepatitis C virus]] (HCV) is a small, enveloped, single-stranded, positive-sense [[RNA virus]].<ref name=NEJM2011 /> It is a member of the genus ''[[Hepacivirus]]'' in the family ''[[Flaviviridae]]''.<ref name=ID2010>{{cite book | last1 = Ray | first1 = Stuart C. | last2 = Thomas | first2 = David L. |editor1-first = Gerald L. | editor1-last = Mandell | editor2-first = John E. | editor2-last = Bennett | editor3-last = Dolin | editor3-first = Raphael |title=Mandell, Douglas, and Bennett's principles and practice of infectious diseases|year=2009|publisher=Churchill Livingstone |location=Philadelphia, PA|isbn=978-0-443-06839-3|chapter=Chapter 154: Hepatitis C |edition=7th}}</ref> There are seven major genotypes of HCV, which are known as genotypes one to seven.<ref name=Nakano2011>{{cite journal | last1 = Nakano | first1 = T | last2 = Lau | first2 = GM | last3 = Lau | first3 = GM | last4 = Sugiyama | first4 = M | last5 = Mizokami | first5 = M |title=An updated analysis of hepatitis C virus genotypes and subtypes based on the complete coding region |journal=Liver Int. |date=December 2011 |pmid=22142261 |doi=10.1111/j.1478-3231.2011.02684.x |volume=32 |issue=2 |pages=339\u201345 | display-authors=3 }}</ref> The genotypes are divided into several subtypes with the number of subtypes depending on the genotype. In the United States, about 70% of cases are caused by genotype 1, 20% by genotype 2 and about 1% by each of the other genotypes.<ref name=AFP2010 /> Genotype 1 is also the most common in South America and Europe.<ref name=NEJM2011 />\n\nThe half life of the virus particles in the serum is around 3 hours and may be as short as 45 minutes.<ref name=Lerat2004 /><ref>{{cite book|last=Pockros|first=Paul|title=Novel and Combination Therapies for Hepatitis C Virus, An Issue of Clinics in Liver Disease|year=2011|isbn=978-1-4557-7198-1|page=47|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gm6aXv8A8cUC&pg=PT47|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160521235637/https://books.google.com/books?id=Gm6aXv8A8cUC&pg=PT47|archivedate=2016-05-21}}</ref> In an infected person, about 10<sup>12</sup> virus particles are produced each day.<ref name=Lerat2004>{{cite journal|last=Lerat|first=H|author2=Hollinger, FB|title=Hepatitis C virus (HCV) occult infection or occult HCV RNA detection?|journal=The Journal of Infectious Diseases|date=2004-01-01|volume=189|issue=1|pages=3\u20136|pmid=14702146|doi=10.1086/380203|doi-access=free}}</ref> In addition to replicating in the liver the virus can multiply in lymphocytes.<ref name=Zignego2012>{{cite journal|last=Zignego|first=AL|author2=Giannini, C |author3=Gragnani, L |author4=Piluso, A |author5= Fognani, E |title=Hepatitis C virus infection in the immunocompromised host: a complex scenario with variable clinical impact.|journal=Journal of Translational Medicine|date=2012-08-03|volume=10|pages=158|pmid=22863056|doi=10.1186/1479-5876-10-158 |issue=1 |pmc=3441205}}</ref>\n\n== Transmission ==\n[[File:Hepatitis C infection by source (CDC) - en.svg|thumb|upright=1.4|Hepatitis C infection in the United States by source]]\n\nThe primary route of transmission in the [[developed world]] is [[intravenous drug use]] (IDU), while in the [[developing world]] the main methods are [[blood transfusions]] and unsafe medical procedures.<ref name=Mah2010 /> The cause of transmission remains unknown in 20% of cases;<ref name=Pon2011>{{cite journal|last=Pond\u00e9|first=RA |title=Hidden hazards of HCV transmission|journal=Medical Microbiology and Immunology|date=February 2011|volume=200|issue=1|pages=7\u201311|pmid=20461405|doi=10.1007/s00430-010-0159-9 }}</ref> however, many of these are believed to be accounted for by IDU.<ref name=Book2011p4 />\n\n=== Drug use ===\nIntravenous drug use (IDU) is a major risk factor for {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} in many parts of the world.<ref name=China2008>{{cite journal|last=Xia|first=X|author2=Luo J |author3=Bai J |author4=Yu R  |title=Epidemiology of HCV infection among injection drug users in China: systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=Public Health|date=October 2008|volume=122|issue=10|pages=990\u20131003|pmid=18486955|doi=10.1016/j.puhe.2008.01.014}}</ref> Of 77 countries reviewed, 25 (including the United States) were found to have prevalences of {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} in the intravenous drug user population of between 60% and 80%.<ref name=Lancet2011>{{cite journal|last=Nelson|first=PK|author2=Mathers BM |author3=Cowie B |author4=Hagan H |author5=Des Jarlais D |author6=Horyniak D |author7=Degenhardt L  |title=Global epidemiology of hepatitis B and hepatitis C in people who inject drugs: results of systematic reviews|journal=Lancet|date=2011-08-13|volume=378|issue=9791|pages=571\u201383|pmid=21802134|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(11)61097-0|pmc=3285467}}</ref><ref name=China2008 />  Twelve countries had rates greater than 80%.<ref name=Lancet2011 /> It is believed that ten million intravenous drug users are infected with {{nowrap|hepatitis C}}; China (1.6&nbsp;million), the United States (1.5&nbsp;million), and Russia (1.3&nbsp;million) have the highest absolute totals.<ref name=Lancet2011 /> [[Infectious diseases within American prisons#Hepatitis C|Occurrence of {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} among prison inmates in the United States]] is 10 to 20 times that of the occurrence observed in the general population; this has been attributed to high-risk behavior in prisons such as IDU and tattooing with nonsterile equipment.<ref name=Jail2010>{{cite journal|last=Imperial|first=JC|title=Chronic hepatitis C in the state prison system: insights into the problems and possible solutions|journal=[[Expert Review of Gastroenterology & Hepatology]]|date=June 2010|volume=4|issue=3|pages=355\u201364|pmid=20528122|doi=10.1586/egh.10.26}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Vescio|first=MF|author2=Longo B |author3=Babudieri S |author4=Starnini G |author5=Carbonara S |author6=Rezza G |author7=Monarca R  |title=Correlates of hepatitis C virus seropositivity in prison inmates: a meta-analysis|journal=Journal of Epidemiology and Community Health|date=April 2008|volume=62|issue=4|pages=305\u201313|pmid=18339822|doi=10.1136/jech.2006.051599}}</ref> Shared intranasal drug use may also be a risk factor.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Moyer|first1=VA|last2=U.S. Preventive Services Task|first2=Force|title=Screening for hepatitis C virus infection in adults: U.S. Preventive Services Task Force recommendation statement.|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=3 September 2013|volume=159|issue=5|pages=349\u201357|pmid=23798026|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-159-5-201309030-00672|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/cc502bd0e6ef93d2c52e48d32c1923eb1f32d8de}}</ref>\n\n=== Healthcare exposure ===\n[[Blood transfusion]], transfusion of blood products, or [[organ transplants]] without HCV screening carry significant risks of infection.<ref name=AFP2010 /> The United States instituted universal screening in 1992<ref name=Rosen2011 /> and Canada instituted universal screening in 1990.<ref>{{cite book|vauthors=Day RA, Paul P, Williams B|title=Brunner & Suddarth's textbook of Canadian medical-surgical nursing|date=2009|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|location=Philadelphia, PA|isbn=978-0-7817-9989-8|page=1237|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SB_-CRXvZPYC&pg=PA1237|edition=Canadian 2nd|display-authors=etal|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425134413/https://books.google.com/books?id=SB_-CRXvZPYC&pg=PA1237|archivedate=2016-04-25}}</ref> This decreased the risk from one in 200 units<ref name=Rosen2011>{{cite book|title=Rosen's emergency medicine: concepts and clinical practice 7th edition |last=Marx |first=John |year=2010|publisher=Mosby/Elsevier |location=Philadelphia, PA |isbn=978-0-323-05472-0 |page=1154 |url=}}</ref> to between one in 10,000 to one in 10,000,000 per unit of blood.<ref name=Book2011p4 /><ref name=Pon2011 /> This low risk remains as there is a period of about 11\u201370&nbsp;days between the potential [[blood donor]]'s acquiring {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} and the blood's testing positive depending on the method.<ref name=Pon2011 /> Some countries do not screen for {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} due to the cost.<ref name=World2007 />\n\nThose who have experienced a [[needle stick injury]] from someone who was HCV positive have about a 1.8% chance of subsequently contracting the disease themselves.<ref name=AFP2010 /> The risk is greater if the needle in question is hollow and the puncture wound is deep.<ref name=World2007 /> There is a risk from mucosal exposures to blood, but this risk is low, and there is no risk if blood exposure occurs on intact skin.<ref name=World2007 />\n\nHospital equipment has also been documented as a method of transmission of {{nowrap|hepatitis C}}, including reuse of needles and syringes; multiple-use medication vials; infusion bags; and improperly sterilized surgical equipment, among others.<ref name=World2007 /> Limitations in the implementation and enforcement of stringent standard precautions in public and private medical and dental facilities are known to be the primary cause of the spread of HCV in [[Egypt]], the country with highest rate of infection in the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www1.albawaba.com/en/news/highest-rates-hepatitis-c-virus-transmission-found-egypt |title=Highest Rates of Hepatitis C Virus Transmission Found in Egypt |publisher=Al Bawaaba |date=2010-08-09 |accessdate=2010-08-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120515221938/http://www.albawaba.com/news/highest-rates-hepatitis-c-virus-transmission-found-egypt |archive-date=2012-05-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Sexual intercourse ===\nSexual transmission of hepatitis C is uncommon.<ref name=Kim2016/> Studies examining the risk of HCV transmission between [[heterosexual]] partners, when one is infected and the other is not, have found very low risks.<ref name=Kim2016/> Sexual practices that involve higher levels of trauma to the [[anogenital area|anogenital]] mucosa, such as [[anal penetration|anal penetrative sex]], or that occur when there is a concurrent [[sexually transmitted infection]], including [[HIV]] or [[genital ulcer]]ation, present greater risks.<ref name=Kim2016/><ref name=Sex2010>{{cite journal|vauthors=Tohme RA, Holmberg SD |title=Is sexual contact a major mode of hepatitis C virus transmission? |journal=Hepatology |volume= 52|issue= 4|pages= 1497\u2013505|date=June 2010|pmid=20635398 |doi=10.1002/hep.23808 }}</ref> The [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]] recommends [[condom]] use to prevent {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} transmission in those with multiple partners, but not those in relationships that involve only a single partner.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hepatitis C Group Education Class|url=http://www.hepatitis.va.gov/products/HCV-education-class-script.asp|publisher=United States Department of Veteran Affairs|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111109105344/http://www.hepatitis.va.gov/products/HCV-education-class-script.asp|archivedate=2011-11-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Body modification ===\n[[Tattooing]] is associated with two to threefold increased risk of {{nowrap|hepatitis C}}.<ref name=Tato2010>{{cite journal|last=Jafari|first=S|author2=Copes R|author3=Baharlou S|author4=Etminan M|author5=Buxton J|title=Tattooing and the risk of transmission of hepatitis C: a systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=International Journal of Infectious Diseases|date=November 2010|volume=14|issue=11|pages=e928\u201340|pmid=20678951|url=http://natap.org/2010/HCV/tatoohcv.pdf|doi=10.1016/j.ijid.2010.03.019|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426085445/http://natap.org/2010/HCV/tatoohcv.pdf|archivedate=2012-04-26}}</ref> This can be due to either improperly sterilized equipment or contamination of the dyes being used.<ref name=Tato2010 /> [[Tattoos]] or [[Body piercing|piercings]] performed either before the mid-1980s, \"underground,\" or nonprofessionally are of particular concern, since sterile techniques in such settings may be lacking. The risk also appears to be greater for larger tattoos.<ref name=Tato2010 /> It is estimated that nearly half of prison inmates share unsterilized tattooing equipment.<ref name=Tato2010 /> It is rare for tattoos in a licensed facility to be directly associated with HCV infection.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hepatitis C|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/HCV/PDFs/HepCGeneralFactSheet.pdf|publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)|accessdate=2 January 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120105131937/http://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/HCV/PDFs/HepCGeneralFactSheet.pdf|archivedate=5 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Shared personal items ===\nPersonal-care items such as razors, toothbrushes, and manicuring or pedicuring equipment can be contaminated with blood. Sharing such items can potentially lead to exposure to HCV.<ref name=\"pmid16907842\">{{cite journal |author=Lock G |title=Hepatitis C \u2013 contamination of toothbrushes: myth or reality? |journal=J. Viral Hepat. |volume=13 |issue=9 |pages=571\u201373 |date=September 2006 |pmid=16907842 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2893.2006.00735.x |url= |name-list-format=vanc|author2=Dirscherl M |author3=Obermeier F |display-authors=3 |last4=Gelbmann |first4=CM |last5=Hellerbrand |first5=C |last6=Knoll |first6=A |last7=Scholmerich |first7=J |last8=Jilg |first8=W }}</ref><ref name=CDC12 /> Appropriate caution should be taken regarding any medical condition that results in [[bleeding]], such as cuts and sores.<ref name=CDC12 /> HCV is not spread through casual contact, such as hugging, kissing, or sharing eating or cooking utensils.<ref name=CDC12>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/HCV/HCVfaq.htm |title= Hepatitis C FAQs for Health Professionals |publisher= Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) |accessdate= 2 January 2012 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120104063744/http://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/hcv/hcvfaq.htm |archivedate= 4 January 2012 }}</ref> Neither is it transmitted through food or water.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Wong T, Lee SS |title=Hepatitis C: a review for primary care physicians |journal=CMAJ |volume=174 |issue=5 |pages=649\u201359 |date=February 2006 |pmid=16505462 |pmc=1389829 |doi=10.1503/cmaj.1030034 |url=}}</ref>\n\n=== Mother-to-child transmission ===\n[[Mother-to-child transmission]] of {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} occurs in fewer than 10% of pregnancies.<ref name=Preg10>{{cite journal|last=Lam|first=NC|author2=Gotsch, PB|author3=Langan, RC|title=Caring for pregnant women and newborns with hepatitis B or C|journal=American Family Physician|date=2010-11-15|volume=82|issue=10|pages=1225\u201329|pmid=21121533|url=http://www.aafp.org/afp/2010/1115/p1225.pdf|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521080102/http://www.aafp.org/afp/2010/1115/p1225.pdf|archivedate=2013-05-21}}</ref> There are no measures that alter this risk.<ref name=Preg10 /> It is not clear when transmission occurs during pregnancy, but it may occur both during gestation and at delivery.<ref name=Pon2011 /> A long labor is associated with a greater risk of transmission.<ref name=World2007 /> There is no evidence that [[breastfeeding]] spreads HCV; however, to be cautious, an infected mother is advised to avoid breastfeeding if her nipples are cracked and bleeding,<ref>{{cite book |author=Mast EE |title=Mother-to-infant hepatitis C virus transmission and breastfeeding |journal=Advances in Experimental Medicine and Biology|volume=554 |pages=211\u201316|year=2004 |pmid=15384578 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-4242-8_18|isbn=978-1-4419-3461-1 }}</ref> or if her viral loads are high.<ref name=Pon2011 />\n\n== Diagnosis ==\n[[File:Hepatitis C serology.png|thumb|upright=1.4|Serologic profile of Hepatitis C infection]]\n\nThere are a number of diagnostic tests for {{nowrap|hepatitis C}}, including HCV [[antibody]] [[ELISA|enzyme immunoassay]] or ELISA, [[Western blot|recombinant immunoblot assay]], and quantitative HCV [[RNA]] [[polymerase chain reaction]] (PCR).<ref name=AFP2010 /> HCV [[RNA]] can be detected by PCR typically one to two weeks after infection, while antibodies can take substantially longer to form and thus be detected.<ref name=Tah2009 />\n\nChronic {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} is defined as infection with the {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} virus persisting for more than six months based on the presence of its RNA.<ref name=Book2011>{{cite book|title=Chronic Hepatitis C Virus Advances in Treatment, Promise for the Future|year=2011|publisher=Springer Verlag|isbn=978-1-4614-1191-8|pages=103\u201304|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6G7mff5DnBQC&pg=PA104|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529054409/https://books.google.com/books?id=6G7mff5DnBQC&pg=PA104|archivedate=2016-05-29}}</ref> Chronic infections are typically asymptomatic during the first few decades,<ref name=Book2011 /> and thus are most commonly discovered following the investigation of [[Liver function tests|elevated liver enzyme levels]] or during a routine screening of high-risk individuals. Testing is not able to distinguish between acute and chronic infections.<ref name=World2007 /> Diagnosis in the infant is difficult as maternal antibodies may persist for up to 18 months.<ref name=Robinson2008 />\n\n=== Serology ===\n{{nowrap|Hepatitis C}} testing typically begins with [[serology|blood testing]] to detect the presence of antibodies to the HCV, using an enzyme immunoassay.<ref name=AFP2010 /> If this test is positive, a confirmatory test is then performed to verify the immunoassay and to determine the [[viral load]].<ref name=AFP2010 /> A recombinant immunoblot assay is used to verify the immunoassay and the viral load is determined by an HCV RNA polymerase chain reaction.<ref name=AFP2010 /> If there is no RNA and the immunoblot is positive, it means that the person tested had a previous infection but cleared it either with treatment or spontaneously; if the immunoblot is negative, it means that the immunoassay was wrong.<ref name=AFP2010 /> It takes about 6\u20138 weeks following infection before the immunoassay will test positive.<ref name=ID2010 /> A number of tests are available as [[point of care testing]] which means that results are available within 30&nbsp;minutes.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Shivkumar|first=S|author2=Peeling, R |author3=Jafari, Y |author4=Joseph, L |author5= Pant Pai, N |title=Accuracy of Rapid and Point-of-Care Screening Tests for Hepatitis C: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis.|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=2012-10-16|volume=157|issue=8|pages=558\u201366|pmid=23070489|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-157-8-201210160-00006|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/562197b7c0b56dd4f55f8a2f743261005ac1c079}}</ref>\n\nLiver enzymes are variable during the initial part of the infection<ref name=Book2011 /> and on average begin to rise at seven weeks after infection.<ref name=ID2010 /> The elevation of liver enzymes does not closely follow disease severity.<ref name=ID2010 />\n\nThere are reports of negative plasma PCR for the viral genome with positive PCR for the viral genome within peripheral blood monocytes of liver cells.<ref name=Austria2018/> This condition has been termed occult HCV infection and it was first recognized in 2004.<ref name=Austria2018>{{cite journal |last1=Austria |first1=A |last2=Wu |first2=GY |title=Occult Hepatitis C Virus Infection: A Review. |journal=Journal of Clinical and Translational Hepatology |date=28 June 2018 |volume=6 |issue=2 |pages=155\u201360 |doi=10.14218/JCTH.2017.00053 |pmid=29951360|pmc=6018308 }}</ref>\n\n=== Biopsy ===\n[[Liver biopsy|Liver biopsies]] are used to determine the degree of liver damage present; however, there are risks from the procedure.<ref name=NEJM2011 /> The typical changes seen are [[lymphocyte]]s within the parenchyma, [[lymphoid follicles]] in [[portal triad]], and changes to the bile ducts.<ref name=NEJM2011 /> There are a number of blood tests available that try to determine the degree of [[hepatic fibrosis]] and alleviate the need for biopsy.<ref name=NEJM2011 />\n\n=== Screening ===\nIt is believed that only 5\u201350% of those infected in the United States and Canada are aware of their status.<ref name=Tato2010 /> Routine screening for those between the ages of 18 and 79 was recommended by the [[United States Preventive Services Task Force]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owens |first1=Douglas K. |last2=Davidson |first2=Karina W. |last3=Krist |first3=Alex H. |last4=Barry |first4=Michael J. |last5=Cabana |first5=Michael |last6=Caughey |first6=Aaron B. |last7=Donahue |first7=Katrina |last8=Doubeni |first8=Chyke A. |last9=Epling |first9=John W. |last10=Kubik |first10=Martha |last11=Ogedegbe |first11=Gbenga |last12=Pbert |first12=Lori |last13=Silverstein |first13=Michael |last14=Simon |first14=Melissa A. |last15=Tseng |first15=Chien-Wen |last16=Wong |first16=John B. |title=Screening for Hepatitis C Virus Infection in Adolescents and Adults |journal=JAMA |volume=323 |issue=10 |pages=970 |date=2 March 2020 |doi=10.1001/jama.2020.1123|pmid=32119076 |doi-access=free }}</ref> Previously testing was recommended for those at high risk, which includes injection drug users, those who have received blood transfusions before 1992,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Moyer|first=VA (on behalf of the U.S. Preventive Services Task Force)|title=Screening for Hepatitis C Virus Infection in Adults: U.S. Preventive Services Task Force Recommendation Statement.|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=2013-06-25|pmid=23798026|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-159-5-201309030-00672|volume=159|issue=5|pages=349\u201357|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/cc502bd0e6ef93d2c52e48d32c1923eb1f32d8de}}</ref> those who have been in jail, those on long term [[hemodialysis]],<ref name=Moyer2013>{{cite journal|last=Moyer|first=VA (U.S. Preventive Services Task Force)|title=Screening for hepatitis C virus infection in adults: U.S. Preventive Services Task Force recommendation statement.|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=2013-09-03|volume=159|issue=5|pages=349\u201357|pmid=23798026|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-159-5-201309030-00672|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/cc502bd0e6ef93d2c52e48d32c1923eb1f32d8de}}</ref> and those with tattoos.<ref name=Tato2010 /> Screening is also recommended in those with elevated liver enzymes, as this is frequently the only sign of chronic hepatitis.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Senadhi|first=V|title=A paradigm shift in the outpatient approach to liver function tests|journal=Southern Medical Journal|date=July 2011|volume=104|issue=7|pages=521\u201325|pmid=21886053|doi=10.1097/SMJ.0b013e31821e8ff5}}</ref> {{As of|2012}}, the U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) recommends a single screening test for those born between 1945 and 1965.<ref>{{cite journal  |vauthors=Smith BD, Morgan RL, Beckett GA, etal |title=Recommendations for the identification of chronic hepatitis C virus infection among persons born during 1945\u20131965 |journal=MMWR Recomm Rep |volume=61 |issue=RR-4 |pages=1\u201332 |date=August 2012 |pmid=22895429 |doi= |url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/pdf/rr/rr6104.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Testing Recommendations for Hepatitis C Virus Infection \u2013 HCV \u2013  Division of Viral Hepatitis | website=U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) | date=12 June 2019 | url=https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/hcv/guidelinesc.htm | access-date=11 January 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=People Born 1945\u20131965 (Baby Boomers) \u2013 Populations and Settings \u2013 Division of Viral Hepatitis | website=U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) | date=26 July 2019 | url=https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/populations/1945-1965.htm | access-date=11 January 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191022221926/https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/populations/1945-1965.htm | archive-date=22 October 2019 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Final Update Summary: Hepatitis C: Screening | website=US Preventive Services Task Force | url=https://www.uspreventiveservicestaskforce.org/Page/Document/UpdateSummaryFinal/hepatitis-c-screening | access-date=11 January 2020}}</ref> In Canada one time screening is recommended for those born between 1945 and 1975.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shah |first1=Hemant |last2=Bilodeau |first2=Marc |last3=Burak |first3=Kelly W. |last4=Cooper |first4=Curtis |last5=Klein |first5=Marina |last6=Ramji |first6=Alnoor |last7=Smyth |first7=Dan |last8=Feld |first8=Jordan J. |title=The management of chronic hepatitis C: 2018 guideline update from the Canadian Association for the Study of the Liver |journal=CMAJ |date=4 June 2018 |volume=190 |issue=22 |pages=E677\u201387 |doi=10.1503/cmaj.170453 |pmid=29866893 |pmc=5988519 |issn=0820-3946}}</ref>\n\n== Prevention ==\n{{See also|Hepatitis C vaccine}}\n{{As of|2016}}, no approved [[vaccine]] protects against contracting {{nowrap|hepatitis C}}.<ref name=Vac2016 /> A combination of [[harm reduction]] strategies, such as the [[needle exchange programs|provision of new needles and syringes]] and treatment of [[substance abuse|substance use]], decreases the risk of {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} in intravenous drug users by about 75%.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Hagan|first=H|author2=Pouget, ER|author3=Des Jarlais, DC|title=A systematic review and meta-analysis of interventions to prevent hepatitis C virus infection in people who inject drugs|journal=The Journal of Infectious Diseases|date=2011-07-01|volume=204|issue=1|pages=74\u201383|pmid=21628661|doi=10.1093/infdis/jir196|pmc=3105033}}</ref> The screening of blood donors is important at a national level, as is adhering to [[universal precautions]] within healthcare facilities.<ref name=ID2010 /> In countries where there is an insufficient supply of sterile [[syringes]], medications should be given orally rather than via injection (when possible).<ref name=World2007 />\n\n== Treatment ==\nThose with chronic {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} are advised to avoid [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]] and medications [[Hepatotoxicity|toxic to the liver]].<ref name=AFP2010 /> They should also be [[vaccinated]] against [[hepatitis A]] and [[hepatitis B]] due to the increased risk if also infected.<ref name=AFP2010 /> Use of [[acetaminophen]] is generally considered safe at reduced doses.<ref name=Kim2016>{{cite journal|last1=Kim|first1=A|title=Hepatitis C Virus|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=September 2016|volume=165|issue=5|pages=ITC33\u2013ITC48|doi=10.7326/AITC201609060|pmid=27595226|type=Review}}</ref> [[Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug]]s (NSAIDs) are not recommended in those with advanced liver disease due to an increased risk of bleeding.<ref name=Kim2016/> [[Ultrasound]] surveillance for [[hepatocellular carcinoma]] is recommended in those with accompanying cirrhosis.<ref name=AFP2010 /> [[Coffee]] consumption has been associated with a slower rate of liver [[fibrosis|scarring]] in those infected with HCV.<ref name=Kim2016/>\n\n=== Medications ===\nApproximately 90% of chronic cases clear with treatment.<ref name=WHO2015 /> Treatment with [[antiviral medication]] is recommended in all people with proven chronic hepatitis C who are not at high risk of dying from other causes.<ref name=IDSA2015>{{cite journal|last1=AASLD/IDSA HCV Guidance|first1=Panel|title=Hepatitis C guidance: AASLD-IDSA recommendations for testing, managing, and treating adults infected with hepatitis C virus.|journal=Hepatology|date=September 2015|volume=62|issue=3|pages=932\u201354|pmid=26111063|doi=10.1002/hep.27950|doi-access=free}}</ref> People with the highest complication risk should be treated first, with the risk of complications based on the degree of liver scarring.<ref name=IDSA2015 /> The initial recommended treatment depends on the type of hepatitis C virus, if the person has received previous hepatitis C treatment, and whether or not a person has cirrhosis.<ref name=IDSA2017/> [[Direct-acting antivirals]] (DAAs) may reduce the number of the infected people.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Jakobsen |first1=JC |last2=Nielsen |first2=EE |last3=Feinberg |first3=J |last4=Katakam |first4=KK |last5=Fobian |first5=K |last6=Hauser |first6=G |last7=Poropat |first7=G |last8=Djurisic |first8=S |last9=Weiss |first9=KH |last10=Bjelakovic |first10=M |last11=Bjelakovic |first11=G |last12=Klingenberg |first12=SL |last13=Liu |first13=JP |last14=Nikolova |first14=D |last15=Koretz |first15=RL |last16=Gluud |first16=C |title=Direct-acting antivirals for chronic hepatitis C. |journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |date=18 September 2017 |volume=9 |pages=CD012143 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD012143.pub3 |pmid=28922704|pmc=6484376 }}</ref>\n\n====No prior treatment====\n*HCV genotype 1a (no cirrhosis): 8 weeks of [[glecaprevir/pibrentasvir]] or [[ledipasvir/sofosbuvir]] (the latter for people who do not have [[HIV/AIDS]], are not [[African-American]], and have less than 6 million HCV viral copies per milliliter of blood) or 12 weeks of [[elbasvir/grazoprevir]], ledipasvir/sofosbuvir, or [[sofosbuvir/velpatasvir]].<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype1a\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment-Naive Genotype 1a Without Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt1a/no-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref> [[Sofosbuvir]] with either [[daclatasvir]] or [[simeprevir]] may also be used.<ref name=IDSA2017>{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C|url=http://hcvguidelines.org/sites/default/files/full-guidance-pdf/HCVGuidance_April_12_2017_b.pdf|accessdate=28 July 2017|date=12 April 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710035751/http://hcvguidelines.org/sites/default/files/full-guidance-pdf/HCVGuidance_April_12_2017_b.pdf|archivedate=2017-07-10}}</ref>\n*HCV genotype 1a (with compensated cirrhosis): 12 weeks of elbasvir/grazoprevir, glecaprevir/pibrentasvir, ledipasvir/sofosbuvir, or sofosbuvir/velpatasvir. An alternative treatment regimen of elbasvir/grazoprevir with weight-based ribavirin for 16 weeks can be used if the HCV is found to have antiviral resistance mutations against NS5A protease inhibitors.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype1acompensated\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment-Naive Genotype 1a With Compensated Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt1a/compensated-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref> \n*HCV genotype 1b (no cirrhosis): 8 weeks of glecaprevir/pibrentasvir or ledipasvir/sofosbuvir (with the aforementioned limitations for the latter as above) or 12 weeks of elbasvir/grazoprevir, ledipasvir/sofosbuvir, or sofosbuvir/velpatasvir. Alternative regimens include 12 weeks of [[ombitasvir/paritaprevir/ritonavir]] with [[dasabuvir]] or 12 weeks of sofosbuvir with either daclatasvir or simeprevir.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype1b\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment-Naive Genotype 1b Without Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt1b/no-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref> \n*HCV genotype 1b (with compensated cirrhosis): 12 weeks of elbasvir/grazoprevir, glecaprevir/pibrentasvir, ledipasvir/sofosbuvir, or sofosbuvir/velpatasvir. A 12-week course of paritaprevir/ritonavir/ombitasvir with dasabuvir may also be used.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype1bcompensated\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment \u2013 Naive Genotype 1b With Compensated Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt1b/compensated-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*HCV genotype 2 (no cirrhosis): 8 weeks of glecaprevir/pibrentasvir or 12 weeks of sofosbuvir/velpatasvir. Alternatively, 12 weeks of sofosbuvir/daclatasvir can be used.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype2\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment-Naive Genotype 2 Without Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt2/no-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*HCV genotype 2 (with compensated cirrhosis): 12 weeks of sofosbuvir/velpatasvir or glecaprevir/pibrentasvir. An alternative regimen of sofosbuvir/daclatasvir can be used for 16\u201324 weeks.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype2compensated\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment-Naive Genotype 2 With Compensated Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt2/compensated-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*HCV genotype 3 (no cirrhosis): 8 weeks of glecaprevir/pibrentasvir or 12 weeks of sofosbuvir/velpatasvir or sofosbuvir and daclatasvir.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype3\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment \u2013 Naive Genotype 3 Without Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt3/no-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*HCV genotype 3 (with compensated cirrhosis): 12 weeks of glecaprevir/pibrentasvir, sofosbuvir/velpatasvir, or if certain antiviral mutations are present, 12 weeks of sofosbuvir/velpatasvir/[[voxilaprevir]] (when certain antiviral mutations are present), or 24 weeks of sofosbuvir and daclatasvir.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype3compensated\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment \u2013 Naive Genotype 3 With Compensated Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt3/compensated-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*HCV genotype 4 (no cirrhosis): 8 weeks of glecaprevir/pibrentasvir or 12 weeks of sofosbuvir/velpatasvir, elbasvir/grazoprevir, or ledipasvir/sofosbuvir. A 12-week regimen of ombitasvir/paritaprevir/ritonavir is also acceptable in combination with weight-based [[ribavirin]].<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype4\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment \u2013 Naive Genotype 4 Without Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt4/no-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*HCV genotype 4 (with compensated cirrhosis): A 12-week regimen of sofosbuvir/velpatasvir, glecaprevir/pibrentasavir, elbasvir/grazoprevir, or ledipasvir/sofosbuvir is recommended. A 12-week course of ombitasvir/paritaprevir/ritonavir  with weight-based ribavirin is an acceptable alternative.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotype4compensated\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment-Naive Genotype 4 With Compensated Cirrhosis|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt4/compensated-cirrhosis|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n*HCV genotype 5 or 6 (with or without compensated cirrhosis): If no cirrhosis is present, then 8 weeks of glecaprevir/pibrentasvir is recommended. If cirrhosis is present, then a 12-week course of glecaprevir/pibrentasvir, sofosbuvir/velpatasvir, or ledipasvir/sofosbuvir is warranted.<ref name=\"HCVGuidelinesGenotypes5and6\">{{cite web|title=HCV Guidance: Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C: Treatment \u2013 Naive Genotype 5 or 6|url=https://www.hcvguidelines.org/treatment-naive/gt5-6|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nChronic infection can be cured in more than 90% of people with medications.<ref name=CDC2019>{{cite web |title=Hepatitis C Questions and Answers for Health Professionals |url=https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/hcv/hcvfaq.htm |website=www.cdc.gov |accessdate=23 July 2019 |language=en-us |date=2 July 2019}}</ref><!-- Quote = Over 90% of HCV infected persons can be cured of HCV infection regardless of HCV genotype, with 8-12 weeks of oral therapy --> Getting access to these treatments however can be expensive.<ref name=WHO2015 /> The combination of [[Sofosbuvir/velpatasvir/voxilaprevir|sofosbuvir, velpatasvir, and voxilaprevir]] may be used in those who have previously been treated with sofosbuvir or other drugs that inhibit NS5A and were not cured.<ref>{{cite press release | title=FDA approves Vosevi for Hepatitis C|url=https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-approves-vosevi-hepatitis-c |website=U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) |accessdate=27 July 2017|date=18 July 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170723062106/https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/ucm567467.htm|archivedate=23 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 2011, treatments consisted of a combination of [[pegylated interferon]] alpha and ribavirin for a period of 24 or 48 weeks, depending on HCV [[genotype]].<ref name=AFP2010 /> This produces cure rates of between 70 and 80% for genotype 2 and 3, respectively, and 45 to 70% for genotypes 1 and 4.<ref name=NEJM2013>{{cite journal|last=Liang|first=TJ|author2=Ghany, MG|title=Current and future therapies for hepatitis C virus infection.|journal=The New England Journal of Medicine|date=May 16, 2013|volume=368|issue=20|pages=1907\u201317|pmid=23675659|doi=10.1056/NEJMra1213651|pmc=3893124}}</ref> Adverse effects with these treatments were common, with half of people getting [[Influenza-like illness|flu-like symptoms]] and a third experiencing emotional problems.<ref name=AFP2010 /> Treatment during the first six months is more effective than once {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} has become chronic.<ref name=Tah2009 /> In those with chronic hepatitis B, treatment for hepatitis C results in reactivation of hepatitis B in about 25%.<ref name=M\u00fccke2018>{{cite journal|last1=M\u00fccke|first1=Marcus M|last2=Backus|first2=Lisa I|last3=M\u00fccke|first3=Victoria T|last4=Coppola|first4=Nicola|last5=Preda|first5=Carmen M|last6=Yeh|first6=Ming-Lun|last7=Tang|first7=Lydia S Y|last8=Belperio|first8=Pamela S|last9=Wilson|first9=Eleanor M|last10=Yu|first10=Ming-Lung|last11=Zeuzem|first11=Stefan|last12=Herrmann|first12=Eva|last13=Vermehren|first13=Johannes |title=Hepatitis B virus reactivation during direct-acting antiviral therapy for hepatitis C: a systematic review and meta-analysis |journal=The Lancet Gastroenterology & Hepatology|volume=3|issue=3|pages=172\u201380|date=January 2018 |doi=10.1016/S2468-1253(18)30002-5|pmid=29371017}}</ref>\n\n=== Surgery ===\nCirrhosis due to hepatitis C is a common reason for [[liver transplant]]ation<ref name=Tah2009>{{cite journal|last=Ozaras|first=R|author2=Tahan, V|title=Acute hepatitis C: prevention and treatment|journal=Expert Review of Anti-infective Therapy|date=April 2009|volume=7|issue=3|pages=351\u201361|pmid=19344247|doi=10.1586/eri.09.8}}</ref> though the virus usually (80\u201390% of cases) recurs afterwards.<ref name=NEJM2011 /><ref>{{cite book|last=Sanders|first=Mick|title=Mosby's Paramedic Textbook|year=2011|publisher=Jones & Bartlett Publishers|isbn=978-0-323-07275-5|page=839|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PJyhIH8N8qgC&pg=PA839|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511134533/https://books.google.com/books?id=PJyhIH8N8qgC&pg=PA839|archivedate=2016-05-11}}</ref> Infection of the graft leads to 10\u201330% of people developing cirrhosis within five years.<ref name=Ciria2013>{{cite journal  |vauthors=Ciria R, Pleguezuelo M, Khorsandi SE, etal |title=Strategies to reduce hepatitis C virus recurrence after liver transplantation |journal=World J Hepatol |volume=5 |issue=5 |pages=237\u201350 |date=May 2013 |pmid=23717735 |pmc=3664282 |doi=10.4254/wjh.v5.i5.237 |url=}}</ref> Treatment with pegylated interferon and ribavirin post-transplant decreases the risk of recurrence to 70%.<ref name=Coilly2013>{{cite journal |vauthors=Coilly A, Roche B, Samuel D |title=Current management and perspectives for HCV recurrence after liver transplantation |journal=Liver Int. |volume=33 Suppl 1 |issue= |pages=56\u201362 |date=February 2013 |pmid=23286847 |doi=10.1111/liv.12062 |url=}}</ref> A 2013 review found unclear evidence regarding if antiviral medication was useful if the graft became reinfected.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gurusamy |first1=KS |last2=Tsochatzis |first2=E |last3=Toon |first3=CD |last4=Xirouchakis |first4=E |last5=Burroughs |first5=AK |last6=Davidson |first6=BR |title=Antiviral interventions for liver transplant patients with recurrent graft infection due to hepatitis C virus. |journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |date=4 December 2013 |issue=12 |pages=CD006803 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD006803.pub4 |pmid=24307460}}</ref>\n\n=== Alternative medicine ===\nSeveral [[alternative medicine|alternative therapies]] are claimed by their proponents to be helpful for {{nowrap|hepatitis C}} including [[Silybum marianum|milk thistle]], [[ginseng]], and [[colloidal silver]].<ref name=NCCAM>[http://nccam.nih.gov/health/providers/digest/hepatitisC-science.htm Hepatitis C and CAM: What the Science Says] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110320175202/http://nccam.nih.gov/health/providers/digest/hepatitisC-science.htm |date=2011-03-20 }}. [[National Center for Complementary and Alternative Medicine]] (NCCAM). March 2011. (Retrieved 7 March 2011)</ref> However, no alternative therapy has been shown to improve outcomes in {{nowrap|hepatitis C}}, and no evidence exists that alternative therapies have any effect on the virus at all.<ref name=NCCAM /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Liu|first=J|author2=Manheimer E |author3=Tsutani K |author4=Gluud C  |title=Medicinal herbs for hepatitis C virus infection: a Cochrane hepatobiliary systematic review of randomized trials|journal=The American Journal of Gastroenterology|date=March 2003|volume=98|issue=3|pages=538\u201344|pmid=12650784|doi=10.1111/j.1572-0241.2003.07298.x|doi-broken-date=2020-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rambaldi|first1=A|last2=Jacobs|first2=BP|last3=Gluud|first3=C|title=Milk thistle for alcoholic and/or hepatitis B or C virus liver diseases.|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|date=17 October 2007|issue=4|pages=CD003620|pmid=17943794|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD003620.pub3}}</ref>\n\n== Prognosis ==\n{{anchor|Sustained viral response}}\n[[File:Hepatitis C world map - DALY - WHO2004.svg|thumb|upright=1.3|[[Disability-adjusted life year]] for hepatitis C in 2004 per 100,000&nbsp;inhabitants\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n{{legend|#b3b3b3|no data}}\n{{legend|#ffff65|<10}}\n{{legend|#fff200|10\u201315}}\n{{legend|#ffdc00|15\u201320}}\n{{legend|#ffc600|20\u201325}}\n{{legend|#ffb000|25\u201330}}\n{{legend|#ff9a00|30\u201335}}\n{{Col-break}}\n{{legend|#ff8400|35\u201340}}\n{{legend|#ff6e00|40\u201345}}\n{{legend|#ff5800|45\u201350}}\n{{legend|#ff4200|50\u201375}}\n{{legend|#ff2c00|75\u2013100}}\n{{legend|#cb0000|>100}}\n{{col-end}}]]\nThe responses to treatment is measured by ''sustained viral response'' (SVR), defined as the absence of detectable [[RNA]] of the [[hepatitis C virus]] in [[serum (blood)|blood serum]] for at least 24 weeks after discontinuing the treatment,<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Helms|editor1-first=Richard A.|editor2-last=Quan|editor2-first=David J.|title=Textbook of Therapeutics: Drug and Disease Management|date=2006|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|location=Philadelphia, Pa. [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-7817-5734-8|page=1340|edition=8.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YjrQla7JPD0C|accessdate=7 November 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151205070808/https://books.google.com/books?id=YjrQla7JPD0C|archivedate=5 December 2015}}</ref> and rapid virological response (RVR) defined as undetectable levels achieved within four weeks of treatment. Successful treatment decreases the future risk of hepatocellular carcinoma by 75%.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Morgan RL, Baack B, Smith BD, Yartel A, Pitasi M, Falck-Ytter Y |title=Eradication of Hepatitis C Virus Infection and the Development of Hepatocellular Carcinoma: A Meta-analysis of Observational Studies |journal=Annals of Internal Medicine |volume=158 |issue=5 Pt 1 |pages=329\u201337 |date=March 2013 |pmid=23460056 |doi=10.7326/0003-4819-158-5-201303050-00005 |url=|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nPrior to 2012 sustained response occurs in about 40\u201350% in people with HCV genotype 1 given 48 weeks of treatment.<ref name=NEJM2011 /> A sustained response is seen in 70\u201380% of people with HCV genotypes 2 and 3 with 24 weeks of treatment.<ref name=NEJM2011 /> A sustained response occurs about 65% in those with genotype 4 after 48 weeks of treatment. The evidence for treatment in genotype 6 disease is sparse and what evidence there is supports 48 weeks of treatment at the same doses used for genotype 1 disease.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Fung J |title=Chronic hepatitis C virus genotype 6 infection: response to pegylated interferon and ribavirin |journal=The Journal of Infectious Diseases |volume=198 |issue=6 |pages=808\u201312 |date=September 2008 |pmid=18657036 |doi=10.1086/591252 |name-list-format=vanc |author2=Lai CL |author3=Hung I |display-authors=3 |last4=Young |first4=John |last5=Cheng |first5=Charles |last6=Wong |first6=Danny |last7=Yuen |first7=Man\u2013Fung |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n=== Spontaneous resolution ===\nAbout 15-45% of those infected spontaneously clear the virus within 6 months, with the rest going on the develop chronic infection.<ref name=\"WHO2015\" /> Spontaneous resolution following acute infection appears more common in females, and younger persons, and appears to also be influenced by genetic factors.<ref name=Book2011p4/> Chronic infection may also resolve spontaneously months or years after the acute phase, though this is unusual.<ref name=\"Book2011p4\" />\n\n== Epidemiology ==\n[[File:HCV prevalence 1999.png|left|thumb|upright=1.3|Prevalence of hepatitis C worldwide in 1999]]\nIt is estimated that 143&nbsp;million people (2%) of people globally are living with chronic {{nowrap|hepatitis C}}.<ref name=GBD2015Pre/> About 3\u20134&nbsp;million people are infected per year, and more than 350,000 people die yearly from hepatitis C-related diseases.<ref name=WHO2011 /> During 2010 it is estimated that 16,000 people died from acute infections while 196,000 deaths occurred from liver cancer secondary to the infection.<ref name=Loz2012>{{cite journal|last=Lozano|first=R|title=Global and regional mortality from 235 causes of death for 20 age groups in 1990 and 2010: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2010.|journal=Lancet|date=2012-12-15|volume=380|issue=9859|pages=2095\u2013128|pmid=23245604|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(12)61728-0|hdl=10536/DRO/DU:30050819}}</ref> Rates have increased substantially in the 20th century due to a combination of intravenous drug abuse and reused but poorly sterilized medical equipment.<ref name=\"World2007\" />\n\nRates are high (>3.5% population infected) in Central and East Asia, North Africa and the Middle East, they are intermediate (1.5%-3.5%) in South and Southeast Asia, sub-Saharan Africa, Andean, Central and Southern Latin America, Caribbean, Oceania, Australasia and Central, Eastern and Western Europe; and they are low (<1.5%) in Asia-Pacific, Tropical Latin America and North America.<ref name=Mohd2013>{{cite journal|last=Mohd Hanafiah|first=K|author2=Groeger, J |author3=Flaxman, AD |author4= Wiersma, ST |title=Global epidemiology of hepatitis C virus infection: new estimates of age-specific antibody to HCV seroprevalence.|journal=Hepatology|date=April 2013|volume=57|issue=4|pages=1333\u201342|pmid=23172780|doi=10.1002/hep.26141}}</ref>\n\nAmong those chronically infected, the risk of [[cirrhosis]] after 20 years varies between studies but has been estimated at ~10\u201315% for men and ~1\u20135% for women. The reason for this difference is not known. Once cirrhosis is established, the rate of developing [[hepatocellular carcinoma]] is ~1\u20134% per year.<ref name=Yu2009>{{cite journal | author = Yu ML |author2=Chuang WL | title = Treatment of chronic hepatitis C in Asia: when East meets West | journal = J. Gastroenterol. Hepatol. | volume = 24 | issue = 3 | pages = 336\u201345 |date=March 2009 | pmid = 19335784 | doi = 10.1111/j.1440-1746.2009.05789.x }}</ref> Rates of new infections have decreased in the Western world since the 1990s due to improved screening of blood before transfusion.<ref name=Tah2009 />\n\nIn the United States, about 2% of people have chronic {{nowrap|hepatitis C}}.<ref name=AFP2010 /> In 2014, an estimated 30,500 new acute hepatitis C cases occurred (0.7 per 100,000 population), an increase from 2010\u20132012.<ref>{{cite web |title = U.S. 2014 Surveillance Data for Viral Hepatitis, Statistics & Surveillance, Division of Viral Hepatitis |publisher = CDC |url = https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/statistics/2014surveillance/commentary.htm#bkgrndC |accessdate = 2016-08-04 |url-status = live |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160808042215/http://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/statistics/2014surveillance/commentary.htm#bkgrndC |archivedate = 2016-08-08 }}</ref> The number of deaths from hepatitis C has increased to 15,800 in 2008<ref>{{cite web|last=Table 4.5|title=Number and rate of deaths with hepatitis C listed as a cause of death, by demographic characteristic and year \u2014 United States, 2004\u20132008|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/Statistics/2010Surveillance/Table4.5.htm|work=Viral Hepatitis on the CDC web site|publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, Atlanta, GA|accessdate=28 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309141408/http://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis/Statistics/2010Surveillance/Table4.5.htm|archivedate=9 March 2014}}</ref> having overtaken HIV/AIDS as a cause of death in the US in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hepatitis Death Rate Creeps past AIDS|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/28/health/research/hepatitis-c-deaths-creep-past-aids-study-finds.html?_r=0|accessdate=28 July 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=27 February 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630112442/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/28/health/research/hepatitis-c-deaths-creep-past-aids-study-finds.html?_r=0|archivedate=30 June 2017}}</ref> In 2014 it was the single greatest cause of infectious death in the United States.<ref name=\"CDC2016a\">{{cite web|title=Hepatitis C Kills More Americans than Any Other Infectious Disease|url=https://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2016/p0504-hepc-mortality.html|publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|accessdate=3 August 2016|date=May 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809080556/http://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2016/p0504-hepc-mortality.html|archivedate=9 August 2016}}</ref> This mortality rate is expected to increase, as those infected by transfusion before HCV testing become apparent.<ref name=Cola2004>{{cite book |editor1-last=Colacino |editor1-first=J. M. |editor2-last=Heinz |editor2-first=B. A. |last1=Blatt |first1=L. M. |last2=Tong |first2=M. |title=Hepatitis prevention and treatment |year=2004 |publisher=Birkh\u00e4user |location=Basel |isbn=978-3-7643-5956-0 |page=32 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KwSWN_QtVLUC&pg=PA32 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624071639/https://books.google.com/books?id=KwSWN_QtVLUC&pg=PA32 |archivedate=2016-06-24 }}</ref> In Europe the percentage of people with chronic infections has been estimated to be between 0.13 and 3.26%.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Blachier M, Leleu H, Peck-Radosavljevic M, Valla DC, Roudot-Thoraval F |title=The burden of liver disease in Europe: a review of available epidemiological data |journal=J. Hepatol. |volume=58 |issue=3 |pages=593\u2013608 |date=March 2013 |pmid=23419824 |doi=10.1016/j.jhep.2012.12.005 |url=|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nIn England about 160,000 people are chronically infected.<ref name=UK2015 /> Between 2006 and 2011 28,000, about 3%, received treatment.<ref name=UK2015>{{cite news|title=Commissioning supplement: Health inequalities tell a tale of data neglect|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/resource-centre/supplements/commissioning-supplement-health-inequalities-tell-a-tale-of-data-neglect/5083351.article#.VUKckYq4_eM|accessdate=30 April 2015|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=19 March 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728084950/http://www.hsj.co.uk/resource-centre/supplements/commissioning-supplement-health-inequalities-tell-a-tale-of-data-neglect/5083351.article#.VUKckYq4_eM|archivedate=28 July 2015}}</ref> About half of people using a needle exchange in London in 2017/8 tested positive for hepatitis C of which half were unaware of they had it.<ref>{{cite news |title=More than half of patients using needle exchange pilot tested positive for Hepatitis C |url=https://www.pharmaceutical-journal.com/20204857.article |accessdate=15 August 2018 |publisher=Pharmaceutical Journal |date=17 May 2018}}</ref>  As part of a bid to eradicate hepatitis C by 2025 [[NHS England]] conducted a large procurement exercise in 2019. [[Merck Sharp & Dohme]], [[Gilead Sciences]], and [[Abbvie]] were awarded contracts, which, together, are worth up to \u00a31 billion over five years.<ref>{{cite news |title=Legal action firm among winners for largest medicines procurement |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/quality-and-performance/legal-action-firm-among-winners-for-largest-medicines-procurement/7024966.article |accessdate=9 June 2019 |publisher=Health Service Journal |date=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe total number of people with this infection is higher in some countries in [[Africa]] and [[Asia]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Scott |last=Holmberg |editor1-first=Gary W. |editor1-last=Brunette |editor2-first=Phyllis E. |editor2-last=Kozarsky |editor3-first=Alan J. |editor3-last=Magill |editor4-first=David R. |editor4-last=Shlim |editor5-first=Amanda D. |editor5-last=Whatley |title=CDC Health Information for International Travel 2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=978-0-19-976901-8 |page=[https://archive.org/details/cdchealthinforma0000unse/page/231 231] |url=https://archive.org/details/cdchealthinforma0000unse/page/231 |url-status=live |date=2011-05-12 |url-access=registration }}</ref> Countries with particularly high rates of infection include Egypt (22%), Pakistan (4.8%) and China (3.2%).<ref name=WHO2011>{{cite web |title=Hepatitis C |publisher=World Health Organization (WHO) |url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs164/en/index.html |date=June 2011 |accessdate=2011-07-13 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712194903/http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs164/en/index.html |archivedate=2011-07-12 }}</ref> It is believed that the high prevalence in Egypt is linked to a now-discontinued mass-treatment campaign for [[schistosomiasis]], using improperly sterilized glass syringes.<ref name=World2007 />\n\nSince 2014, extremely effective medication have been available to eradication the disease in 8-12 weeks in most people.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Lombardi|first=Andrea|last2=Mondelli|first2=Mario U.|last3=ESCMID Study Group for Viral Hepatitis (ESGVH)|date=March 2019|title=Hepatitis C: Is eradication possible?|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30472772|journal=Liver International: Official Journal of the International Association for the Study of the Liver|volume=39|issue=3|pages=416\u2013426|doi=10.1111/liv.14011|issn=1478-3231|pmid=30472772|doi-access=free}}</ref> In 2015 about 950,000 people were treated while 1.7 million new infections occurred, meaning that overall the number of people with HCV increased.<ref name=\":0\" /> These numbers differ by country and improved in 2016, with some countries achieving higher cure rates than new infection rates (mostly high income countries).<ref name=\":0\" /> By 2018, twelve countries are on track to achieve HCV elimination.<ref name=\":0\" /> While DAAs will curb new infections, it is less clear whether they impact overall deaths and morbidity.<ref name=\":0\" /> Furthermore, for DAAs to be effective, people need to be aware of their infection - it is currently estimated that worldwide only 20% of infected people are aware of their infection (in the US fewer than half were aware).<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== History ==\nIn the mid-1970s, [[Harvey J. Alter]], Chief of the Infectious Disease Section in the Department of Transfusion Medicine at the [[National Institutes of Health]], and his research team demonstrated how most post-[[blood transfusion|transfusion]] hepatitis cases were not due to [[hepatitis A]] or [[Hepatitis B|B]] viruses. Despite this discovery, international research efforts to identify the virus, initially called ''non-A, non-B hepatitis'' (NANBH), failed for the next decade. In 1987, [[Michael Houghton (virologist)|Michael Houghton]], [[Qui-Lim Choo]], and [[George Kuo]] at [[Chiron Corporation]], collaborating with [[Daniel W. Bradley]] at the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]], used a novel [[molecular cloning]] approach to identify the unknown organism and develop a diagnostic test.<ref name = Boyer>{{cite book | isbn = 978-0-7923-8760-2 | last = Boyer | first = JL | title = Liver cirrhosis and its development: proceedings of the Falk Symposium 115 | pages = [https://books.google.com/books?id=n5P696E7T0wC&pg=PA344#v=onepage&q&f=false 344] | publisher = [[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]] | year = 2001 }}</ref> In 1988, Alter confirmed the virus by verifying its presence in a panel of NANBH specimens. In April 1989, the discovery of HCV was published in two articles in the journal ''Science''.<ref name=\"choo\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Choo QL, Kuo G, Weiner AJ, Overby LR, Bradley DW, Houghton M |author-link4=Lacy Overby |title=Isolation of a cDNA clone derived from a blood-borne non-A, non-B viral hepatitis genome |journal=Science |volume=244 |issue=4902 |pages=359\u201362 |date=April 1989 |pmid=2523562 |doi=10.1126/science.2523562|url=http://courses.washington.edu/conj504/readings/polyak_reading1.pdf |citeseerx=10.1.1.469.3592 |bibcode=1989Sci...244..359C }}</ref><ref name=\"kuo\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kuo G, Choo QL, Alter HJ, Gitnick G, Redeker A, Purcell R, Miyamura T, Dienstag J, Alter M |title=An assay for circulating antibodies to a major etiologic virus of human non-A, non-B hepatitis |journal=Science |volume=244 |issue=4902 |pages=362\u20134 |date=April 1989 |pmid=2496467 |doi=10.1126/science.2496467 |display-authors=3|bibcode=1989Sci...244..362K }}</ref> The discovery led to significant improvements in diagnosis and improved antiviral treatment.<ref name=Web2015 /><ref name = Boyer /> In 2000, Drs. Alter and Houghton were honored with the [[Lasker Award]] for Clinical Medical Research for \"pioneering work leading to the discovery of the virus that causes hepatitis C and the development of screening methods that reduced the risk of blood transfusion-associated hepatitis in the U.S. from 30% in 1970 to virtually zero in 2000.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laskerfoundation.org/awards/library/2000clinical.shtml |title=2000 Winners Albert Lasker Award for Clinical Medical Research |accessdate=2006-04-21 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080225184627/http://www.laskerfoundation.org/awards/library/2000clinical.shtml |archivedate=February 25, 2008 }}. Retrieved 20 February 2008.</ref>\n\nChiron filed for several patents on the virus and its diagnosis.<ref name=\"houghton\">{{cite patent | country = EP | number = 0318216 | status = patent | title = NANBV diagnostics | gdate = 1989-05-31 | invent1 = Houghton, M | invent2 = Choo, Q-L | invent3 = Kuo, G | assign1 = Chiron }}</ref> A competing patent application by the CDC was dropped in 1990 after Chiron paid $1.9&nbsp;million to the CDC and $337,500 to Bradley. In 1994, Bradley sued Chiron, seeking to invalidate the patent, have himself included as a coinventor, and receive damages and royalty income. He dropped the suit in 1998 after losing before an appeals court.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilken |title=United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit |url=http://www.ll.georgetown.edu/federal/judicial/fed/opinions/96opinions/96-1536.html |publisher=United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit |accessdate=11 January 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091119144520/http://www.ll.georgetown.edu/federal/judicial/fed/opinions/96opinions/96-1536.html |archivedate=19 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Society and culture ==\n{{See also|List of people with hepatitis C}}\n[[World Hepatitis Day]], held on July 28, is coordinated by the World Hepatitis Alliance.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Eurosurveillance editorial team|title=World Hepatitis Day 2011|journal=[[Eurosurveillance]]|date=2011-07-28|volume=16|issue=30|pmid=21813077|url=http://www.eurosurveillance.org/images/dynamic/EE/V16N30/art19926.pdf|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111125163506/http://eurosurveillance.org/images/dynamic/EE/V16N30/art19926.pdf|archivedate=2011-11-25}}</ref> The economic costs of hepatitis C are significant both to the individual and to society. In the United States the average lifetime cost of the disease was estimated at US$33,407 in 2003<ref name=Cost2006>{{cite journal|last=Wong|first=JB|title=Hepatitis C: cost of illness and considerations for the economic evaluation of antiviral therapies |journal=PharmacoEconomics |year=2006 |volume=24 |issue=7 |pages=661\u201372 |pmid=16802842|doi=10.2165/00019053-200624070-00005}}</ref> with the cost of a liver transplant {{as of|2011|lc=y}} costing approximately US$200,000.<ref name=Cost2011 /> In Canada the cost of a course of antiviral treatment is as high as 30,000&nbsp;CAD in 2003,<ref>{{cite web|title=Hepatitis C Prevention, Support and Research ProgramHealth Canada|url=http://www.phac-aspc.gc.ca/hepc/pubs/psrpmideval-ppsrevalinter/i_problem-eng.php|publisher=Public Health Agency of Canada|accessdate=10 January 2012|date=Nov 2003|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322182718/http://www.phac-aspc.gc.ca/hepc/pubs/psrpmideval-ppsrevalinter/i_problem-eng.php|archivedate=22 March 2011}}</ref> while the United States costs are between 9,200 and 17,600 in 1998 USD.<ref name=Cost2006 /> In many areas of the world, people are unable to afford treatment with antivirals as they either lack insurance coverage or the insurance they have will not pay for antivirals.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-first=Howard|editor1-last=Thomas|editor2-first=Stanley|editor2-last=Lemon|editor3-first=Arie|editor3-last=Zuckerman|title=Viral Hepatitis|year=2008|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|location=Oxford|isbn=978-1-4051-4388-2|pages=532|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nT2dauLXoYAC&pg=PA532|edition=3rd|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617164927/https://books.google.com/books?id=nT2dauLXoYAC&pg=PA532|archivedate=2016-06-17}}</ref> In the English [[National Health Service]] treatment rates for hepatitis C are higher among wealthier groups per 2010\u20132012 data.<ref name=UK2015 /> Spanish anaesthetist [[Juan Maeso]] infected 275 patients between 1988 and 1997 as he used the same needles to give both himself and the patients opioids.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spanish Anesthetist Infected Patients|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/15/AR2007051500921.html|accessdate=13 July 2016|work=The Washington Post|date=15 May 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822072146/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/05/15/AR2007051500921.html|archivedate=22 August 2016}}</ref> For this he was jailed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spanish Hep C anaesthetist jailed|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/6657509.stm|accessdate=13 July 2016|work=BBC|date=15 May 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071023220711/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/6657509.stm|archivedate=23 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Special populations ==\n\n=== Children and pregnancy ===\n{{Main|HCV in children and pregnancy}}\nCompared with adults, infection in children is much less well understood. Worldwide the prevalence of hepatitis C virus infection in pregnant women and children has been estimated to 1\u20138% and 0.05\u20135% respectively.<ref name=Arshad2011>{{cite journal |vauthors=Arshad M, El-Kamary SS, Jhaveri R |title=Hepatitis C virus infection during pregnancy and the newborn period\u2014are they opportunities for treatment? |journal=J. Viral Hepat. |volume=18 |issue=4 |pages=229\u201336 |date=April 2011 |pmid=21392169 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2893.2010.01413.x }}</ref> The [[Vertically transmitted infection|vertical transmission]] rate has been estimated to be 3\u20135% and there is a high rate of spontaneous clearance (25\u201350%) in the children. Higher rates have been reported for both vertical transmission (18%, 6\u201336% and 41%).<ref name=Hunt1997>{{cite journal |vauthors=Hunt CM, Carson KL, Sharara AI |title=Hepatitis C in pregnancy |journal=Obstet Gynecol |volume=89 |issue=5 Pt 2 |pages=883\u201390 |date=May 1997 |pmid=9166361 |doi=10.1016/S0029-7844(97)81434-2 }}</ref><ref name=Thomas1998>{{cite journal |vauthors=Thomas SL, Newell ML, Peckham CS, Ades AE, Hall AJ |title=A review of hepatitis C virus (HCV) vertical transmission: risks of transmission to infants born to mothers with and without HCV viraemia or human immunodeficiency virus infection |journal=Int J Epidemiol |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=108\u201317 |date=February 1998 |pmid=9563703 |doi=10.1093/ije/27.1.108|doi-access=free }}</ref> and prevalence in children (15%).<ref name=Fischler2007>{{cite journal |author=Fischler B |title=Hepatitis C virus infection |journal=Semin Fetal Neonatal Med |volume=12 |issue=3 |pages=168\u201373 |date=June 2007 |pmid=17320495 |doi=10.1016/j.siny.2007.01.008 }}</ref>\n\nIn developed countries transmission around the time of birth is now the leading cause of HCV infection. In the absence of virus in the mother's blood transmission seems to be rare.<ref name=Thomas1998 /> Factors associated with an increased rate of infection include membrane rupture of longer than 6 hours before delivery and procedures exposing the infant to maternal blood.<ref name=Indolfi2009>{{cite journal |vauthors=Indolfi G, Resti M |title=Perinatal transmission of hepatitis C virus infection |journal=J. Med. Virol. |volume=81 |issue=5 |pages=836\u201343 |date=May 2009 |pmid=19319981 |doi=10.1002/jmv.21437 }}</ref> Cesarean sections are not recommended. Breastfeeding is considered safe if the nipples are not damaged. Infection around the time of birth in one child does not increase the risk in a subsequent pregnancy. All genotypes appear to have the same risk of transmission.\n\nHCV infection is frequently found in children who have previously been presumed to have non-A, non-B hepatitis and cryptogenic liver disease.<ref name=\"Gonz\u00e1lez-Peralta1997\">{{cite journal |author=Gonz\u00e1lez-Peralta RP |title=Hepatitis C virus infection in pediatric patients |journal=Clin Liver Dis |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=691\u2013705, ix |date=November 1997 |pmid=15560066 |doi=10.1016/s1089-3261(05)70329-9}}</ref> The presentation in childhood may be asymptomatic or with elevated liver function tests.<ref name=Suskind2004>{{cite journal |vauthors=Suskind DL, Rosenthal P |title=Chronic viral hepatitis |journal=Adolesc Med Clin |volume=15 |issue=1 |pages=145\u201358, x\u2013xi |date=February 2004 |pmid=15272262 |doi= 10.1016/j.admecli.2003.11.001}}</ref> While infection is commonly asymptomatic both cirrhosis with liver failure and hepatocellular carcinoma may occur in childhood.\n\n=== Immunosuppressed ===\n{{See also|Hepatitis C and HIV coinfection}}\nThe rate of hepatitis C in immunosuppressed people is higher. This is particularly true in those with  [[human immunodeficiency virus]] infection, recipients of [[organ transplant]]s, and those with [[hypogammaglobulinemia]].<ref name=Einav2002>{{cite journal |vauthors=Einav S, Koziel MJ |title=Immunopathogenesis of hepatitis C virus in the immunosuppressed host |journal=Transpl Infect Dis |volume=4 |issue=2 |pages=85\u201392 |date=June 2002 |pmid=12220245 |doi=10.1034/j.1399-3062.2002.t01-2-02001.x}}</ref> Infection in these people is associated with an unusually rapid progression to cirrhosis. People with stable HIV who never received medication for HCV, may be treated with a combination of [[peginterferon]] plus [[ribavirin]] with caution to the possible side effects.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Iorio |first1=A |last2=Marchesini |first2=E |last3=Awad |first3=T |last4=Gluud |first4=LL |title=Antiviral treatment for chronic hepatitis C in patients with human immunodeficiency virus. |journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |date=20 January 2010 |issue=1 |pages=CD004888 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD004888.pub2 |pmid=20091566}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\n{{As of|2011}}, there are about one hundred medications in development for hepatitis C.<ref name=Cost2011>{{cite journal|last1 = El Khoury | first1 = AC | last2 = Klimack | first2 = WK | last3 = Wallace | first3 = C | last4 = Razavi | first4 = H |title=Economic burden of hepatitis C-associated diseases in the United States|journal=Journal of Viral Hepatitis|date=1 December 2011|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2893.2011.01563.x|volume=19|issue=3|pages=153\u201360|pmid=22329369}}</ref> These include vaccines to treat hepatitis, [[immunomodulators]], and [[cyclophilin]] inhibitors, among others.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ahn|first=J|author2=Flamm, SL|title=Hepatitis C therapy: other players in the game|journal=Clinics in Liver Disease|date=August 2011|volume=15|issue=3|pages=641\u201356|pmid=21867942|doi=10.1016/j.cld.2011.05.008}}</ref> These potential new treatments have come about due to a better understanding of the hepatitis C virus.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Vermehren|first=J|author2=Sarrazin, C|title=New HCV therapies on the horizon|journal=Clinical Microbiology and Infection|date=February 2011|volume=17|issue=2|pages=122\u201334|pmid=21087349|doi=10.1111/j.1469-0691.2010.03430.x }}</ref> There are a number of vaccines under development and some have shown encouraging results.<ref name=Vac2016>{{cite journal|last1=Abdelwahab|first1=KS|last2=Ahmed Said|first2=ZN|title=Status of hepatitis C virus vaccination: Recent update.|journal=World Journal of Gastroenterology|date=14 January 2016|volume=22|issue=2|pages=862\u201373|pmid=26811632|doi=10.3748/wjg.v22.i2.862|pmc=4716084}}</ref>\n\nThe combination of [[sofosbuvir]] and [[velpatasvir]] in one trial (reported in 2015) resulted in cure rates of 99%.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Feld|first1=Jordan J. |last2=Jacobson|first2=Ira M. |last3=H\u00e9zode|first3=Christophe |last4=Asselah|first4=Tarik |last5=Ruane|first5=Peter J. |last6=Gruener|first6=Norbert |last7=Abergel|first7=Armand |last8=Mangia|first8=Alessandra |last9=Lai|first9=Ching-Lung |last10=Chan|first10=Henry L.Y. |last11=Mazzotta|first11=Francesco |last12=Moreno|first12=Christophe |last13=Yoshida|first13=Eric |last14=Shafran|first14=Stephen D.|last15=Towner|first15=William J.|last16=Tran|first16=Tram T.|last17=McNally|first17=John|last18=Osinusi|first18=Anu|last19=Svarovskaia|first19=Evguenia|last20=Zhu|first20=Yanni|last21=Brainard|first21=Diana M.|last22=McHutchison|first22=John G.|last23=Agarwal|first23=Kosh|last24=Zeuzem|first24=Stefan|title=Sofosbuvir and Velpatasvir for HCV Genotype 1, 2, 4, 5, and 6 Infection|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=373 |issue=27 |date=16 November 2015|pages=2599\u20132607|doi=10.1056/NEJMoa1512610|pmid=26571066 |url=http://qmro.qmul.ac.uk/xmlui/handle/123456789/17933 |hdl=10722/226358 |doi-access=free}}</ref> More studies are needed to investigate the role of the preventive antiviral medication against HCV recurrence after transplantation.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gurusamy |first1=KS |last2=Tsochatzis |first2=E |last3=Toon |first3=CD |last4=Davidson |first4=BR |last5=Burroughs |first5=AK |title=Antiviral prophylaxis for the prevention of chronic hepatitis C virus in patients undergoing liver transplantation. |journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |date=2 December 2013 |issue=12 |pages=CD006573 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD006573.pub3 |pmid=24297303|pmc=6599865 }}</ref>\n\n=== Animal models ===\nOne barrier to finding treatments for hepatitis C is the lack of a suitable animal model. Despite moderate success, current research highlights the need for pre-clinical testing in mammalian systems such as [[mouse]], particularly for the development of vaccines in poorer communities. Currently, [[Common chimpanzee|chimpanzees]] remain the available living system to study, yet their use has ethical concerns and regulatory restrictions. While scientists have made use of human cell culture systems such as hepatocytes, questions have been raised about their accuracy in reflecting the body's response to infection.<ref name=Sand2013>{{cite journal|last=Sandmann|first=L|author2=Ploss, A|title=Barriers of hepatitis C virus interspecies transmission.|journal=Virology|date=2013-01-05|volume=435|issue=1|pages=70\u201380|pmid=23217617|doi=10.1016/j.virol.2012.09.044|pmc=3523278}}</ref>\n\nOne aspect of hepatitis research is to reproduce infections in mammalian models. A strategy is to introduce liver tissues from humans into mice, a technique known as xenotransplantation. This is done by generating chimeric mice, and exposing the mice HCV infection. This engineering process is known to create humanized mice, and provide opportunities to study hepatitis C within the 3D architectural design of the liver and evaluating antiviral compounds.<ref name=Sand2013 /> Alternatively, generating inbred mice with susceptibility to HCV would simplify the process of studying mouse models.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical condition classification and resources\n| DiseasesDB      = 5783\n| ICD10           = {{ICD10|B|17|1|b|15}}, {{ICD10|B|18|2|b|15}}\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|070.70}},{{ICD9|070.4}}, {{ICD9|070.5}}\n| OMIM            = 609532\n| MedlinePlus     = 000284\n| eMedicineSubj   = med\n| eMedicineTopic  = 993\n| eMedicine_mult  = {{EMedicine2|ped|979}}\n| MeshID          = D006526\n| SNOMED CT       = 186643004\n}}\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|Hep C en.ogg|2014-07-26}}\n{{commons}}\n*{{curlie|Health/Conditions_and_Diseases/Digestive_Disorders/Liver/Hepatitis/Hepatitis_C|Hepatitis C}}\n* {{cite web|title=Recommendations for Testing, Managing, and Treating Hepatitis C|url=http://www.hcvguidelines.org/|website=www.hcvguidelines.org|publisher=IDSA/AASLD|accessdate=28 July 2017}}\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|Viruses}}\n{{Viral diseases}}\n{{gastroenterology}}\n\n[[Category:Hepatitis C| ]]\n[[Category:Healthcare-associated infections]]\n[[Category:Infectious causes of cancer]]\n[[Category:RTT(full)]]\n[[Category:RTTEM]]\n[[Category:Viral diseases]]\n", "name_user": "Srich32977", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hepatitis_C"}
{"title_page": "Philip Treacy", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2018}}\n{{short description|Irish-born haute couture milliner}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name           = Philip Anthony Treacy\n|honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBEh}}\n|image          = Philip Treacy, The Master Millner.jpg\n|caption        = Treacy wearing his own creation\n|birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1967|5|26|df=y}}<ref name=\"clan\"/>\n|birth_place    = [[Ahascragh]], [[Galway]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n|nationality    = Irish\n|education      = [[National College of Art and Design]] (NCAD) Dublin, (1987)\n|alma_mater     = [[Royal College of Art]] London, (MA, 1990)\n|awards         = {{Plain list | \n* [[The Fashion Awards|British Accessory Designer of the Year]] {{small|(1991, 1992, 1993, 1996, 1997)}}\n* International Designer of the Year {{small|([[China Fashion Week]], Shanghi, 2004)}}\n* Doctorate of Fine Arts<br>{{small|[[University College Dublin]] (2004)}}\n* [[Order of the British Empire]]<br>(OBE) ({{small|2007)}} }}\n|known_for      = \n|occupation     = [[Milliner]], hat designer,{{efn|name=\"hat\"}} designer\n|religion       = \n|spouse         = Stefan Bartlett<br>{{small|married 2017}}\n|father         = James Vincent Treacy<br>{{small|(d. 1978)}}<ref name=\"clan\">{{cite website | url=http://www.traceyclann.com/files/renowned%20Traceys%20arts.htm | title=The Tracey Clan: Arts: Crafts | quote=Philip Anthony Treacy, b. 26 May 1967 Ballinasloe, Co. Galway, son of the late James Vincent Treacy and Katie Agnes Treacy. His parents owned a baker's shop in Ahascragh, Co. Galway.|website=TreacyClann.com | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n|mother         = Katie Agnes Treacy<br>{{small|(d. 1993)}}<ref name=\"clan\"/>\n|website        = {{URL|1=http://www.philiptreacy.co.uk|2=Philip Treacy}}\n}}\n'''Philip Anthony Treacy''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBEh}} (born 26 May 1967), is an award-winning [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]]-born [[haute couture]] [[Hatmaking|milliner]], or hat-designer,{{efn|name=\"hat\"|Treacy prefers to use the term \"hat-designer\".<ref name=\"examiner\"/>}} who has been mostly based in [[London]] for his career, and who was described by ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' magazine as \"perhaps the greatest living milliner\".{{efn|''Vogue'' magazine has made this comment, and slight variations of it, on a number of occasions.<ref name=\"vog2\"/><ref name=\"vog1\"/>}}  In 2000, Treacy became the first milliner in eighty years to be invited to exhibit at the Paris haute couture shows.<ref name=\"guar\"/> He has won British Accessory Designer of the Year at the [[British Fashion Awards]] five times, and has received public honours in both Britain and Ireland.   His designs have been displayed at the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] and  the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].\n\nIn 1989, Treacy was discovered and then mentored by fashion editor [[Isabella Blow]], who Treacy described as the \"biggest inspiration\" on his life.  Blow would wear and promote Treacy's designs at important fashion events, and helped Treacy to break into some of the main fashion houses, particularly [[Chanel]] and [[Givenchy]].  Treacy is associated with celebrities such as [[Lady Gaga]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Sarah Jessica Parker]]. He has also been associated with British royalty and has designed hats for royal occasions, including the controversial fascinator (or \"pretzel hat\") worn by [[Princess Beatrice]] in 2011.\n\n==Early life==\nPhilip Anthony Treacy was born on 26 May 1967 in the small village of [[Ahascragh]], in [[County Galway]] in the [[Republic of Ireland]], whose population was circa 500.<ref name=\"clan\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Reed|first1=Paula|last2=Etherington-Smith |first2=Meredith |authorlink2=Meredith Etherington-Smith |title=Philip Treacy: unlikely sculpture |date=2002 |publisher=Charta |location=Milano |isbn=9788881583553 |page=53 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?ei=hYFvVLToMJPVauK-gfgJ&id=Hw7GpY1MOqIC&dq=Ahascragh | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Treacy says that his interest in sewing started at age five,<ref name=\"kampen\"/> and that his obsession with the [[wedding]]s in the catholic church across the road from his house inspired an early passion for fashion.<ref name=\"egan\"/>  In 1985, at age 17, Treacy moved to [[Dublin]] to study fashion at the [[National College of Art and Design]], where he spent a 6-week work experience with British milliner [[Stephen Jones (milliner)|Stephen Jones]].<ref name=colm>{{cite website | first=Colm | last=\u00d3 Briain | title=Text of the introductory address delivered by: PROFESSOR COLM \u00d3 BRIAIN, on the occasion of the conferring of the Degree of Doctor of Fine Arts, honoris causa, on PHILIP TREACY | url=http://www.nui.ie/college/docs/citations/2006/treacy.pdf | website=[[National University of Ireland]] | accessdate=21 November 2014 |date=7 April 2006}}</ref>  In 1988, Treacy won an [[Master of Arts|MA]] scholarship for the Fashion Design course at the [[Royal College of Art]] in London, and graduated in 1990 with first class honours.<ref name=colm/><ref name=\"irisharts\">{{cite magazine| url=https://www.irishartsreview.com/crown-prince/ | title=Crown Prince | first=Deirdre | last=McQuillan | website=Irish Arts Review | date=July 2014 | accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|When I was interviewed [for the Royal College of Art] I didn\u2019t know whether to play down the hats or play up the hats, but they were thinking of setting up a hat course so I became their guinea pig. After one day there I said to my tutor [[Sheilagh Brown]]: \u201cWhat should I do? Should I make hats or clothes?\u2019 She said: \u2018make hats.\u2019 It was very practical, not a great revelation.|source=Philip Treacy, ''[[Irish Independent]]'', February 2011<ref name=\"kampen\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.independent.ie/style/fashion/philip-treacy-on-his-new-collection-26705462.html | title=Philip Treacy on his new collection | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | date=16 February 2011 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Sinead | last=Van Kampen}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1989, he took one of his hats to Michael Roberts, fashion editor of ''[[Tatler]]'' magazine, and his style editor [[Isabella Blow]].<ref name=jayne>{{cite book | last1=Sheridan | first1=Jayne | title=Fashion, media, promotion: the new black magic | date=2010 | publisher=Wiley | location=Hoboken | isbn=9781118815021 |page=27 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wXyuAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA27 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Blow asked Treacy to make a hat for her wedding,<ref name=\"egan\"/> and soon after in 1990, invited him to live with her and her new husband Detmar Blow, in their [[Belgravia]] home in London, where Treacy worked in their basement.<ref name=jayne/>  [[Alexander McQueen]], another Blow discovery, also shared her Belgravia home.<ref name=\"bryony\"/><ref>{{cite newspaper | url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG7231469/Alexander-McQueen-and-Isabella-Blow.html | title=Alex McQueen and Isabella Blow | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=14 February 2010 | first=Detmar | last=Blow | quote=I first met Alexander when Isabella invited him to live with us at 67 Elizabeth Street in Belgravia. We were on the top floor, [the milliner] Philip Treacy on the first, and Alexander was on the ground. Issie was working at British Vogue at the time and had come across Alexander at his graduate fashion show in 1992 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2002, the [[Design Museum]] in London, hosted an exhibition of the 30 most iconic hats Treacy designed for Blow, titled: ''When Philip met Isabella''.<ref name=\"irisharts\"/>  The exhibition was so well received that it went on a world tour for several years and drew a record attendance of circa 43,000 when shown in Dublin in 2005.<ref name=\"irisharts\"/>  In a 2011 interview, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' said: \"She made him famous. He made her look like an icon. When you think of the late, great Blow, you think of her in one of his creations, be it a giant disc or a replica sailing ship.\"<ref name=\"bryony\">{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/royal-wedding/8454151/Philip-Treacy-Ive-been-busy-what-with-the-wedding.html|title=Philip Treacy: 'I've been busy, what with the wedding' | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | first=Bryony |last=Gordon | date=18 April 2011 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n{{quote|My biggest inspiration has been Isabella Blow. [..] In twenty years I have met all my heroes and for me nobody has surpassed her. She was incredible. I thought there must be others like her, but there wasn't. Everyone was boring in comparison to her.|source=Philip Treacy, ''[[Irish Independent]]'', February 2011<ref name=\"kampen\"/>}}\n\n==Career==\n\n===Haute couture===\n\n[[File:Beauxbatons Academy Students (Orlando).jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|Treacy designed the [[Beauxbatons]] hats for [[Harry Potter]] in 2005]]\n\nIn 1991, Treacy, aged 23, on the prompting of Blow,<ref name=\"flowerhats\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gardening/10741693/Philip-Treacy-how-my-flower-hats-blossomed.html | title=Philip Treacy: how my flower hats blossomed | date=5 April 2014 | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Christopher | last=Woodward}}</ref> got his \"big break\",<ref name=\"examiner\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/lifestyle/features/philip-treacys-crowning-glory-357687.html | title=Philip Treacy\u2019s crowning glory | newspaper=[[The Irish Examiner]] | date=6 October 2015 | first=Rachel Marie | last=Walsh | quote=The hat designer (a description he prefers to milliner) pinpoints being summoned to Paris by Karl Lagerfeld in 1991 as his big break, comparable to an American Idol win | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>  being asked by [[Karl Lagerfeld]] to come to the [[Chanel]] showrooms in Paris, in what was to be the start of a long\u2013term working relationship.  The first hat that Treacy designed for Chanel appeared on the cover of ''[[British Vogue]]'' worn by model [[Linda Evangelista]].{{efn|The hat was called ''Twisted Birdcage'' and was photographed by French fashion photographer, [[Patrick Demarchelier]].<ref name=\"scmp\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.scmp.com/node/568036 | title=Philip Treacy | first=Carrie | last=Chan | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] | date=18 October 2006 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>  Treacy chose another Linda Evangelista photograph as the cover of his 2015 biography.<ref name=\"examiner\"/>}}\n\n{{quote|I was 23 and I'd just left [art] school, I didn't know whether to call him Mr. Lagerfeld or whatever. I was totally intimidated but Issie [Blow] was exactly herself. She just walked into the house of Chanel and said: \"We'd like some tea please\".  I would design hats for Chanel for the next decade.|source=Philip Treacy, ''[[Irish Independent]]'', February 2011<ref name=\"kampen\"/>}}\n\nIn 1991, Treacy opened his first showroom in London, and won his first of five British Accessory Designer of the Year awards.<ref name=\"egan\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.independent.ie/woman/celeb-news/an-audience-with-prince-philip-26215107.html|title=An audience with Prince Philip | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | first=Barry | last=Egan | date=20 November 2005 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>  In 1993, Treacy held his first fashion show during [[London Fashion Week]] in ''[[Harvey Nichols]]'', with [[Naomi Campbell]], [[Yasmin le Bon]], [[Kate Moss]], [[Christy Turlington]] and [[Stella Tennant]] modelling in return for keeping Treacy's hats, which were all black.<ref name=\"egan\"/><ref name=\"scmp\"/>  In 1994, he opened up his boutique at 69 Elizabeth Street, in Belgravia, London, right beside Isabella Blow's residence at number 67.<ref name=\"flowerhats\"/><ref name=\"scmp\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londontown.com/LondonInformation/Shopping/Philip_Tracey/5b5f/|title=69 Elizabeth Street|publisher=LondonTown Guide|quote=Treacy opened this elegant shop in Elizabeth Street in 1994, next door to Blow's old house at 67 Elizabeth Street \u2013 where Treacy's business first began in the basement}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Treacy's first solo show in 1993 saw him debut on the fashion and celebrity radar when no fewer than five of the most famous supermodels of the era \u2013 Naomi Campbell, Yasmin Le Bon, Kate Moss, Stella Tennant, and Christy Turlington \u2013 appeared on his catwalk. Playing down his star appeal, Treacy is humble about his overnight success story. \"London was in a lull then,\" he said. \"The media went crazy when all those girls did my show, but it completely changed perceptions of the hat.|source=Philip Treacy, ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'', 2007<ref name=\"smh\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/fashion/most-popular-man-in-fashion-20030526-gdgtnu.html | title=Most popular man in fashion | newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | date=26 May 2003 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Philip Treacy London Boutique.jpg|thumb|Philip Treacy's boutique, 69 Elizabeth Street, Belgravia, London.]]\n\nTreacy has designed hats for [[Alexander McQueen]] (another discovery of Isabella Blow),{{efn|For McQueen's first Givenchy exhibition in 1997, Blow had the horns cut from a ram in her flock of rare\u2013breed sheep, which Treacy then sprayed with gold, and which Naomi Campbell then wore on the runway.<ref name=\"smh\"/>}} including his 1999 ''white collection'' for [[Givenchy]] [[Haute Couture]] in Paris, for [[Karl Lagerfeld]] at [[Chanel]], and for [[Valentino Garavani|Valentino]], [[Ralph Lauren]], [[Donna Karan]], [[Versace]] and [[Rifat \u00d6zbek]].  In January 2000, he became the first milliner for eighty years to be invited to exhibit at the Paris shows.{{efn|name=\"orch\"}}<ref name=\"guar\"/><ref name=\"orchid2\"/> In November 2015, ''Vogue'' magazine ran a feature of Treacy's 20 \"most awe\u2013inspiring chapeaux\" from the runways.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.vogue.com/article/philip-treacy-book-best-hats | title=20 of Philip Treacy\u2019s Most Jaw\u2013Dropping Couture Chapeaux | magazine=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue Magazine]] \n |date=13 November 2015 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Kristin | last=Anderson}}</ref>\n\n===Wider fashion===\n\nOutside of ''[[haute couture]]'', Treacy has designed hats for films, including [[Harry Potter films|Harry Potter]] (most notably the [[Beauxbatons]] hat, for [[The Goblet of Fire]] in 2005).<ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/attractions/harry-potter-s-wardrobe-is-brimful-of-secrets-a3587376.html | title=Harry Potter\u2019s wardrobe is brimful of secrets | newspaper=The Standard | date=13 July 2017 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Jennifer | last=Ruby}}</ref> [[Sarah Jessica Parker]] has worn his hats at [[Sex and the City (film)|''Sex and the City'']] premi\u00e8res (2008, 2011), and [[Met Gala]]s (2013, 2015).{{efn|Sarah Jessica Parker's 2015 Met Gala Treacy hat was nominated by ''Vogue'' in May 2018, as one of the ''16 Craziest Celebrity Moments in Met Gala History''.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.vogue.com/article/best-met-gala-celebrity-moments-of-all-time|title=The Craziest Celebrity Moments in Met Gala History|date=2 May 2018 | magazine=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] | quote=You gotta give it to SJP: She never phones it in. The Philip Treacy headpiece she wore for the 2015 Met Gala, \u201cChina: Through the Looking Glass,\u201d will always be remembered as the hat that launched a thousand memes | accessdate=15 April 2020 }}</ref>}} Treacy designed [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s gold headpiece for her 2012 [[Super Bowl]] half\u2013time show.<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG9200192/Exclusive-Philip-Treacy-on-designing-Madonnas-Super-Bowl-hat.html|title=Exclusive: Philip Treacy on designing Madonna's Super Bowl hat | date=12 April 2012 | first=Phong | last=Luu | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | quote=Treacy made Madonna's jewelled Egyptian-ish fanned headpiece for her Super Bowl performance. He shows off the mock-up he made of it, and, even as a dummy run, it's impressive. | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> [[Lady Gaga]] described Treacy as \"the greatest milliner of all time\", while hosting his 2012 London Week fashion show.<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2012/sep/16/lady-gaga-philip-treacy-london-fashion-week | title=Lady Gaga pays tribute to milliner Philip Treacy at London fashion week | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | first=Jess | last=Cartner-Morley | date=16 September 2012 | quote=How extraordinary was Philip Treacy's London fashion week catwalk show? Put it this way: when Lady Gaga appeared wearing a floor-length neon pink veil and towering Alexander McQueen Armadillo shoes, she did not immediately attract much attention. It was that kind of night | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Notable designs for Lady Gaga include a ''telephone-shaped headpiece with a removable handset'' hat, worn for her appearance on [[Friday Night with Jonathan Ross]] in 2010 (now in permanent display at [[Madame Tussauds]]),<ref>{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | quote=In the London Madame Tussauds, a waxwork figure of the singer wearing a show\u2013stopping Philip Treacy telephone hat which she wore on Friday Night with Jonathan Ross in March 2010 was unveiled, teamed with a Giorgio Armani Priv\u00e9 outfit with pagoda\u2013style shoulders and vertiginous heels | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/dec/09/lady-gaga-outfits-madame-tussauds | date=9 December 2010 | first=Alexandra | last=Topping | title=Lady Gaga appears in eight different outfits at eight Madame Tussauds | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> and a ''lightning-bolt'' hat she wore for the 2010 [[Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.independent.ie/style/fashion/fashion-fix/lady-gaga-shares-a-laugh-with-genius-philip-treacy-30706941.html | title=Lady Gaga shares a laugh with 'genius' Philip Treacy | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | first=Elaine | last=McCahill | date=31 October 2014 | quote=Gaga was wearing Treacy's unique hats as far back as 2010 when she wore an eye\u2013catching outfit to the Grammy Awards | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite website|url=http://hepburnette.com/blog/138_5-Crazy-Lady-Gaga-Philip-Treacy-Hats | title=5 Crazy Lady Gaga Philip Treacy Hats | website=Hepburnette.com | date=2014 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs well as Isabella Blow, Sarah Jessica Parker, and Lady Gaga, other notable muses for Treacy's hats are socialite [[Daphne Guinness]],<ref>{{cite website | url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/gallery/philip-treacy-hat-designer-book/all | title=Philip Treacy\u2019s Trippiest, Most Dazzling Hats | date=25 October 2015 | website=Architectural Digest | quote=\"Daphne is a rare bird. She\u2019s a fashion contradiction. No designer owns her. Whatever Daphne wears, she owns.\" Treacy says of Guinness | first=Colleen | last=Egan | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> model [[Naomi Campbell]],<ref name=\"examiner\"/><ref name=\"power\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.independent.ie/style/fashion/top-hat-philip-treacys-two-decades-of-creating-masterpieces-31609729.html | title=Top Hat... Philip Treacy's two decades of creating masterpieces | date=18 October 2015 | first=Bairbre | last=Power | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> and singer, and model, [[Grace Jones]],<ref name=\"grace\"/> who used Treacy as art director and designer for her 2009 ''Hurricane'' tour.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.essence.com/news/hats-off-to-grace-jones-favorite-head-topper/|title=Hats Off To Grace Jones' Favorite Head Topper|magazine=[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]| first=Patrik | last=Henry Bass | date=10 November 2011 | quote=The style icon tapped the milliner as art director and designer for her 2009 sold\u2013out \u201cHurricane\u201d tour. Long before that collaboration, Grace was sporting the milliner\u2019s works of art in videos and special appearances. | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn a July 2011 interview with ''[[The Guardian]]'', Treacy distilled what he felt a hat should do (a Treacy quote which is often reproduced):<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.independent.ie/style/fashion/top-hat-philip-treacys-two-decades-of-creating-masterpieces-31609729.html | title=Top Hat... Philip Treacy's two decades of creating masterpieces | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | date=18 October 2015 | quote=Philip Treacy's mission as a hat designer is to be creative and, as he says himself, he likes \"to make hats that make the heart beat faster\". | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Bairbre | last=Power}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Princess Beatrice's hat.jpg|thumb|150px|Princess Beatrice's [[fascinator]] \"pretzel hat\" by Philip Treacy in April 2011]]\n\n{{quote|''The Guardian'': Does a person carry off a hat or a hat carry off a person?<br>''Philip Treacy'': A person carries off the hat. Hats are about emotion. It is all about how it makes you feel. I like hats that make the heart beat faster. | source=Philip Treacy, ''[[The Guardian]]'', July 2011.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2011/jul/10/philip-treacy-milliner-interview | title=Philip Treacy: 'I like hats that make the heart beat faster' | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | date=10 July 2011 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Kate | last=Kellaway}}</ref>}}\n\nTreacy had previously written a piece for ''The Guardian'' in May 2001 on what defines the \"perfect hat\".<ref>{{cite newspaper |  url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2001/may/27/life1.lifemagazine3|title=The perfect hat | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | first=Philip |last=Treacy | date=22 May 2001 | quote=Everyone thinks you need confidence to wear a beautiful hat, but this perfect hat will instead give you the courage and the energy to carry it off. | accessdate=15 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Royal occasions===\n\nTreacy's hats are also associated with English royalty, with thirty six worn at the [[Wedding of Prince William, Duke of Cambridge, and Catherine Middleton|29 April 2011 Royal wedding]] of [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]] and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|Catherine Middleton]],<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=http://www.independent.ie/world-news/royal-wedding/philip-treacy-king-of-royal-wedding-hats-2633003.html | title=Philip Treacy: King of Royal wedding hats | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | date=29 April 2011 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> including the controversial [[fascinator]] style hat worn by [[Princess Beatrice of York]].  This so\u2013called \"pretzel hat\" was auctioned for charity by Princess Beatrice on eBay for $130,000 (\u00a380,100) on the 22 May 2011.<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/gossip/2011/05/princess-beatrices-royal-wedding-hat-sells-for-a-whopping-130000-on-ebay.html | title=Princess Beatrice\u2019s royal wedding hat sells for more than $130,000 on EBay | newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=22 May 2011 | quote=The princess plans to give the money (final bid: 81,100.01 pounds, which is around $131,134) from the 10-day auction to UNICEF UK and Children in Crisis via her Little Bee Initiative campaign. | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Emily | last=Christianson}}</ref>  Treacy felt the criticism regarding the \"pretzel hat\" was extreme (the hat had its own Facebook page with over 140,000 connections), and in July 2011 said: \"In the future, we'll look back and think she looked wild\".<ref name=\"guardian\"/>  In a July 2018 Radio 4 [[Desert Island Discs]] interview, Treacy said: \"There was a moment where I thought I would find myself with my head on a spike outside the Tower of London\", from the controversy of the \"pretzel hat\".<ref>{{cite website |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-44755082 | title=Royal hat-maker Philip Treacy 'feared head on spike' | website=[[BBC News]] | date=8 July 2018 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>  The hat resides at the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].<ref>{{cite website | url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/171324|title=PHILIP TREACY HAT (c. 2011): Gift of Melinda B. Hildebrand, 2012| website=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] | quote=Accession Number: 2012.519 (search item 171324) | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nTreacy designed over twenty hats that were worn at the 19 May 2018 [[Wedding of Prince Harry and Meghan Markle]], including by [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]], by [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]], and by [[Oprah Winfrey]].<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.independent.ie/style/fashion/fashion-news/irish-designer-philip-treacy-created-20-hats-for-the-british-royal-wedding-including-oprahs-36923734.html | title=Irish designer Philip Treacy created 20 hats for the British royal wedding - including Oprah's | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | date=19 May 2018 | quote=Treacy designed hats for [[Oprah Winfrey]], Priyanka Chopra, Camilla, the Duchess of Cornwall, and Kate Middleton for Meghan and Harry's big day | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Karen | last=Birney}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/celebrity/latest/g20106557/meghan-markle-prince-harry-royal-wedding-hats/?slide=1 | title=All the Hats at Meghan Markle and Prince Harry's Wedding | magazine=[[Harper's Bazaar]] | date=19 May 2018 | quote=There was a lot of Philip Treacy. | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Tamara | last=Abraham}}</ref>  [[Megan Markle]] chose a Treacy hat for her first official royal event in December 2017.<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.independent.ie/style/fashion/meghan-markle-chose-irish-designer-philip-treacy-hat-for-first-royal-outing-36438983.html | title=Meghan Markle chose Irish designer Philip Treacy hat for first 'royal outing' | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | date=27 December 2017 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Bairbre |last=Power}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/meghan-s-first-official-duty-tops-off-hat-maker-philip-treacy-s-rise-wtwpq6g77 | title=Meghan's first official duty tops off hat-maker Philip Treacy\u2019s rise | first=Jennifer | last=O'Brien | newspaper=[[The Times]] | date=24 May 2018 | quote=Hats off to him. Philip Treacy, the Galway-born milliner, has cemented his position as the primary choice of hatmaker for the royal family. | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Treacy credited the [[Elizabeth II|Queen]] with \"single-handedly saving the British hat industry\".<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/07/07/queenspatronage-has-single-handedly-saved-british-hat-industry/ | title=Queen's patronage has single-handedly saved the British hat industry, Philip Treacy says | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=8 July 2018 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first= Hannah | last=Furness}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n\n[[File:Duchess of Cornwall 2012.JPG|thumb|150px|[[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]] wearing a Treacy hat in June 2012]]\n\nTreacy won the title of British Accessory Designer of the Year at the [[British Fashion Awards]] five times during the 1990s (1991, 1992, 1993, 1996 and 1997).<ref>{{cite website |title=Philip Treacy 'Hatforms' at IMMA Thursday|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2001/0405/treacyp.html|website=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]]|date=5 April 2001 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>  In January 2000, Treacy was invited by the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration fran\u00e7aise de la couture|Chambre Syndicale de la Haute Couture]] to participate in Paris fashion shows, the first milliner to be invited in 80 years.{{efn|name=\"orch\"|Treacy exhibited his ''Orchid Collection'' at the Paris 2000 haute couture shows.<ref name=\"orchid\">{{cite newspaper |url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG3363781/Philip-Treacy-Madcap-milliner-receives-OBE.html | title=Madcap milliner receives OBE| newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | first=Hillary |last=Alexander | date=19 November 2007 | quote=In 2000, he made millinery history by staging his 'Orchid' collection of haute couture hats in Paris | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>}}<ref name=\"guar\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2002/apr/16/fashion|title=Who wants to be a milliner|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|first=Jess | last=Cartner-Morley|date=16 April 2002|quote=He has created hats to accompany the catwalk collections of Alexander McQueen and Valentino, has been named British Accessory Designer of the Year five times, and was the first milliner in 80 years to be invited by French fashion's governing body, the Chambre Syndicale, to take part in the Parisian haute couture shows | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"orchid2\">{{cite magazine | url=https://www.vogue.it/en/fashion/news/2010/03/09/philip-treacy/?refresh_ce= |title=Philip Treacy | magazine=[[Vogue Italia]] | date=9 March 2010 | quote=In 2000, he was the first milliner in 70 years to be invited by the Chambre Syndicale to show his collection during the Haute Couture fashion week in Paris | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2004, Treacy was named the International Designer of the Year, at the [[China Fashion Week|China Fashion Awards]] in Shanghai.<ref name=\"scmp\"/>  In April 2006, he was awarded a Doctorate of Fine Arts, by the [[National University of Ireland]] at [[University College Dublin]] (\"UCD\").<ref name=colm/><ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/irish-hat-designer-philip-treacy-turns-royal-heads-with-obe-award-48391.html|title=Irish hat designer Philip Treacy turns royal heads with OBE award|newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]]|date=20 November 2007| accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe was awarded an honorary [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] (Order of the British Empire) for services to the British fashion industry by [[Prince Charles]] and [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]] at a special ceremony in [[Clarence House]] in November 2007.{{efn|Because Treacy is Irish, and not sworn to allegiance to the Crown, the ceremony was not held with the Queen in Buckingham Palace.  Normally, in such cases, a Government Minister would perform the ceremony, however, Prince Charles intervened to host the ceremony in Clarence House.}}<ref name=\"personal\">{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.independent.ie/style/fashion/prince-honours-king-of-the-hats-26333118.html | title=Prince honours king of the hats | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | quote=Irishman Philip Treacy (40) received an honorary OBE at a special ceremony hosted by Prince Charles and his wife, Camilla Parker Bowles, at their Clarence House home. The fashion designer was appointed an honorary Officer of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire (OBE). The honour was conferred on Philip by Queen Elizabeth in recognition of his services to the British Fashion industry | date=20 November 2007 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Bairbre |last=Power}}</ref>  Treacy designed the headdress worn by the Duchess of Cornwall for [[Wedding of Charles, Prince of Wales, and Camilla Parker Bowles|the couple's wedding]].<ref name=\"personal\"/>\n\nIn July 2010, Treacy was one of six contemporary and internationally renowned Irish fashion designers honoured by a set of [[Postage stamps of Ireland|Irish postage stamps]] issued by [[An Post]]. The other designers were [[Paul Costelloe]], [[Louise Kennedy]], [[John Rocha]], [[Lainey Keogh]] and [[Orla Kiely]].<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/fashion/stamp-of-approval-1.620308 | newspaper=[[Irish Times]] | date=10 July 2010 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Deirdre | last=McQuillan | title=Stamp Of Approval}}</ref><ref>{{cite website | title=Magnificent Irish fashionista stamps | url=http://www.worldstampnews.com/2010/07/magnificent-irish-fashionista-stamps/ | accessdate=23 January 2014 | website=World Stamp News | date=18 July 2010|url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203001930/http://www.worldstampnews.com/2010/07/magnificent-irish-fashionista-stamps/|archivedate=3 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nTreacy's hats have been exhibited, and are housed in the collections of design museums including the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]],<ref name=\"orchid2\"/><ref>{{cite website |url=https://collections.vam.ac.uk/search/?listing_type=&offset=0&limit=15&narrow=&extrasearch=&q=Philip+Treacy&commit=Search&quality=0&objectnamesearch=&placesearch=&after=&before=&namesearch=&materialsearch=&mnsearch=&locationsearch=|title=Victoria & Albert: Philip Treacy | website=Victoria and Albert Museum | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]],<ref name=\"orchid2\"/><ref>{{cite website | url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search#!?q=Philip%20Treacy|title=Search The Met Collection: Philip Treacy | website=MetMuseum.com | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> and the ''Galleria del Costume'' of the [[Palazzo Pitti]] in Florence.<ref>{{cite website |url=http://www.firenzemadeintuscany.com/en/arts/articles/hats-between-art-and-extravaganza-in-florence/|title=Exhibition in Florence: The Hat Between Art and Extravaganza|date=28 November 2013|quote=Despite prevailing specimens of known names of the fashion house such as Christian Dior, Givenchy, Chanel, Yves Saint Laurent, Prada, Gianfranco Ferre and international famous milliners of the present and the past like Philip Treacy, [[Stephen Jones (milliner)|Stephen Jones]], [[Caroline Reboux]], [[Claude Saint-Cyr]], and [Madame] Paulette [..]|website=FIRENZE | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> ''Vogue'' magazine has described Treacy, on a number of occasions, as being the \"greatest milliner in the world\".<ref name=\"vog2\">{{cite magazine | url=https://www.vogue.com/article/best-summer-hats| title=7 Chic Hats We've Fallen Head Over Heels For This Summer | magazine=Vogue|first=Lynn | last=Yaeger|date=24 June 2015|quote=As Philip Treacy, one of our greatest living milliners, once said, \"Wearing a hat is fun! People have a good time when they're wearing a hat\". | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vog1\">{{cite magazine | url=https://www.vogue.com/article/thriller-night-at-philip-treacy-the-king-of-pops-wardrobe-meets-its-millinery-match | title=Thriller Night: At Philip Treacy, the King of Pop's Wardrobe Meets Its Millinery Match | magazine=Vogue | first=Lynn | last=Yaeger |date=17 September 2012 | quote=On one thing, at least, the ecstatic throng can agree\u2014it is a London show like none other, and Gaga is right: Treacy is perhaps the greatest milliner in the world | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTreacy is gay and in May 2017 he married his long\u2013term partner of over 21 years, Stefan Bartlett, in a ceremony in Las Vegas.<ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.independent.ie/style/celebrity/irish-designer-philip-treacy-weds-long-term-love-in-las-vegas-and-celebrates-with-cher-35688627.html|title=Irish designer Philip Treacy weds long\u2013term love in Las Vegas - and celebrates with Cher|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]]|date=7 May 2017 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Patricia | last=Murphy}}</ref>\n\nTreacy has noted the support his parents{{efn|Treacy's father was a baker and his mother was a housewife,<ref name=\"cul\">{{cite website|url=http://www.culch.ie/2009/06/03/philip-treacy-the-culchie-interview/|title=Philip Treacy Interview|website=Culch.ie|date=3 June 2009|first=Darragh|last= Doyle|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> however, his father had a weak heart which prevented him from working as a full-time baker, and he eventually died when Philip was age 11 from a heart attack; Treacy's mother died in 1993, when Philip was 25.<ref name=\"egan\"/>}} gave him in pursuing his love of millinery, noting that his father would say: \"whatever makes him happy\".<ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/fashion/irish-milliner-philip-treacy-feared-head-on-spike-over-beatrice-hat-1.3557971|title=Irish milliner Philip Treacy 'feared head on spike' over Beatrice hat|newspaper=[[Irish Times]] | date=8 July 2018 | quote=One of the strongest memories I have is being in somebody's house and my father's friend saying don't you think that's a little odd, don't you think it's a bit strange this child is doing this?'  And I remember distinctly my father saying: 'Whatever makes him happy'. It moves me still. | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/raise-your-hat-to-philip-26248191.html|title=Raise your hat to Philip|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | first=Mary | last=O'Sullivan | date=15 April 2001 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>  Treacy called his friendship with his mentor, Isabella Blow, as: \"an affair without sex\".<ref name=\"bryony\"/> Treacy also highlights the importance of fashion model [[Grace Jones]] as a collaborator and friend.<ref name=\"grace\">{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/fashion/irish-milliner-philip-treacy-feared-head-on-spike-over-beatrice-hat-1.3557971|title=Irish milliner Philip Treacy|date=8 July 2018|newspaper=[[Irish Times]] | quote=Treacy also spoke candidly to Young about how he has overcome some of the losses in his life with the help of close friend and eccentric collaborator Grace Jones. \"If you told somebody you were getting advice from Grace Jones they would probably tell you you need your head examined,\" said Treacy. \"But she actually gives really good advice\".|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nTreacy is the second youngest of a large family and has one sister,<ref name=\"ia\"/> and seven brothers.<ref name=\"personal\"/><ref name=\"cul\"/>  He is particularly close to his sister, Marion Tubbing,<ref name=\"personal\"/> the eldest sibling, whom he credits with supplying him with editions of ''[[Harper's and Queen]]'' and ''Vogue'' while living in Galway (Tubbing was working in London at the time),<ref name=\"ia\">{{cite magazine | url=https://irishamerica.com/2007/02/the-master-hatter/ | title=The Master Hatter | magazine=[[Irish America (magazine)|Irish America]] | date=March 2007 | quote=Being the second youngest of seven boys, and with one sister who was the eldest child, Philip recollects, \"I thought my sister, Marion, was the most glamorous girl in the world. She was a huge inspiration to me. She was my introduction to fashion and magazines. She worked as a nurse in London and used to come home on holidays with all these great magazines like Harper's and Queen and Vogue, which I'd never seen.\"|first=Marilyn |last=Cole Lownes|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> and for whom, along with his partner Stefan Bartlett, Treacy dedicated his 2015 biography: ''Philip Treacy: Hat Designer''.<ref name=\"power\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Designs by Philip Treacy}}\n{{Portal|Ireland|Fashion}}\n* [[John Boyd (milliner)|John Boyd]], milliner\n* [[Stephen Jones (milliner)|Stephen Jones]], milliner\n* [[Claude Saint-Cyr]], milliner\n* [[Caroline Reboux]], milliner\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Blow\n  | first = Isabella\n  | title = Philip Treacy (Memoire) \n  | publisher = Assouline\n  | isbn = 978-2843233937\n  | year = 2011\n   }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Davies\n  | first = Kevin\n  | title = Philip Treacy\n  | publisher = Phaidon Press\n  | isbn = 978-0714865270\n  | year = 2013\n   }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Hume\n  | first = Marion\n  | title = Philip Treacy: Hat Designer\n  | publisher = Rizzoli International Publications\n  | isbn = 978-0847846504\n  | year = 2015\n   }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Reed\n  | first = Paula\n  | title = Philip Treacy\n  | publisher = Charta\n  | isbn = 978-8881583553\n  | year = 2001\n   }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Treacy\n  | first = Philip\n  | title = Philip Treacy: \"When Philip Met Isabella\"\n  | publisher =  Assouline\n  | isbn = 978-2843233722\n  | year = 2003\n   }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://www.philiptreacy.co.uk/en}}\n*[http://www.fashionencyclopedia.com/To-Vi/Treacy-Philip.html Philip Treacy] at Fashion Encyclopedia\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/philip-treacy Philip Treacy] at [[The Guardian]]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?reload=9&v=Z3WUWHDf_8g Wizarding World of Harry Potter: Philip Treacy Hats]\n\n{{Designer labels}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Treacy, Philip}}\n[[Category:Irish businesspeople in fashion]]\n[[Category:Irish fashion designers]]\n[[Category:LGBT fashion designers]]\n[[Category:Gay artists]]\n[[Category:Milliners]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the National College of Art and Design]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Art]]\n[[Category:Honorary Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in England]]\n[[Category:People from Ballinasloe]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2018}}\n{{short description|Irish-born haute couture milliner}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name           = Philip Anthony Treacy\n|honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBEh}}\n|image          = Philip Treacy, The Master Millner.jpg\n|caption        = Treacy wearing his own creation\n|birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1967|5|26|df=y}}<ref name=\"clan\"/>\n|birth_place    = [[Ahascragh]], [[Galway]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n|nationality    = Irish\n|education      = [[National College of Art and Design]] (NCAD) Dublin, (1987)\n|alma_mater     = [[Royal College of Art]] London, (MA, 1990)\n|awards         = {{Plain list | \n* [[The Fashion Awards|British Accessory Designer of the Year]] {{small|(1991, 1992, 1993, 1996, 1997)}}\n* International Designer of the Year {{small|([[China Fashion Week]], Shanghi, 2004)}}\n* Doctorate of Fine Arts<br>{{small|[[University College Dublin]] (2004)}}\n* [[Order of the British Empire]]<br>(OBE) ({{small|2007)}} }}\n|known_for      = \n|occupation     = [[Milliner]], hat designer,{{efn|name=\"hat\"}} designer\n|religion       = \n|spouse         = Stefan Bartlett<br>{{small|married 2017}}\n|father         = James Vincent Treacy<br>{{small|(d. 1978)}}<ref name=\"clan\">{{cite website | url=http://www.traceyclann.com/files/renowned%20Traceys%20arts.htm | title=The Tracey Clan: Arts: Crafts | quote=Philip Anthony Treacy, b. 26 May 1967 Ballinasloe, Co. Galway, son of the late James Vincent Treacy and Katie Agnes Treacy. His parents owned a baker's shop in Ahascragh, Co. Galway.|website=TreacyClann.com | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n|mother         = Katie Agnes Treacy<br>{{small|(d. 1993)}}<ref name=\"clan\"/>\n|website        = {{URL|1=http://www.philiptreacy.co.uk|2=Philip Treacy}}\n}}\n'''Philip Anthony Treacy''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBEh}} (born 26 May 1967), is an award-winning [[Republic of Ireland|Irish]]-born [[haute couture]] [[Hatmaking|milliner]], or hat-designer,{{efn|name=\"hat\"|Treacy prefers to use the term \"hat-designer\".<ref name=\"examiner\"/>}} who has been mostly based in [[London]] for his career, and who was described by ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' magazine as \"perhaps the greatest living milliner\".{{efn|''Vogue'' magazine has made this comment, and slight variations of it, on a number of occasions.<ref name=\"vog2\"/><ref name=\"vog1\"/>}}  In 2000, Treacy became the first milliner in eighty years to be invited to exhibit at the Paris haute couture shows.<ref name=\"guar\"/> He has won British Accessory Designer of the Year at the [[British Fashion Awards]] five times, and has received public honours in both Britain and Ireland.   His designs have been displayed at the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] and  the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].\n\nIn 1989, Treacy was discovered and then mentored by fashion editor [[Isabella Blow]], who Treacy described as the \"biggest inspiration\" on his life.  Blow would wear and promote Treacy's designs at important fashion events, and helped Treacy to break into some of the main fashion houses, particularly [[Chanel]] and [[Givenchy]].  Treacy is associated with celebrities such as [[Lady Gaga]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Sarah Jessica Parker]]. He has also been associated with British royalty and has designed hats for royal occasions, including the controversial fascinator (or \"pretzel hat\") worn by [[Princess Beatrice]] in 2011.\n\n==Early life==\nPhilip Anthony Treacy was born on 26 May 1967 in the small village of [[Ahascragh]], in [[County Galway]] in the [[Republic of Ireland]], whose population was circa 500.<ref name=\"clan\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Reed|first1=Paula|last2=Etherington-Smith |first2=Meredith |authorlink2=Meredith Etherington-Smith |title=Philip Treacy: unlikely sculpture |date=2002 |publisher=Charta |location=Milano |isbn=9788881583553 |page=53 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?ei=hYFvVLToMJPVauK-gfgJ&id=Hw7GpY1MOqIC&dq=Ahascragh | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Treacy says that his interest in sewing started at age five,<ref name=\"kampen\"/> and that his obsession with the [[wedding]]s in the catholic church across the road from his house inspired an early passion for fashion.<ref name=\"egan\"/>  In 1985, at age 17, Treacy moved to [[Dublin]] to study fashion at the [[National College of Art and Design]], where he spent a 6-week work experience with British milliner [[Stephen Jones (milliner)|Stephen Jones]].<ref name=colm>{{cite website | first=Colm | last=\u00d3 Briain | title=Text of the introductory address delivered by: PROFESSOR COLM \u00d3 BRIAIN, on the occasion of the conferring of the Degree of Doctor of Fine Arts, honoris causa, on PHILIP TREACY | url=http://www.nui.ie/college/docs/citations/2006/treacy.pdf | website=[[National University of Ireland]] | accessdate=21 November 2014 |date=7 April 2006}}</ref>  In 1988, Treacy won an [[Master of Arts|MA]] scholarship for the Fashion Design course at the [[Royal College of Art]] in London, and graduated in 1990 with first class honours.<ref name=colm/><ref name=\"irisharts\">{{cite magazine| url=https://www.irishartsreview.com/crown-prince/ | title=Crown Prince | first=Deirdre | last=McQuillan | website=Irish Arts Review | date=July 2014 | accessdate=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|When I was interviewed [for the Royal College of Art] I didn\u2019t know whether to play down the hats or play up the hats, but they were thinking of setting up a hat course so I became their guinea pig. After one day there I said to my tutor [[Sheilagh Brown]]: \u201cWhat should I do? Should I make hats or clothes?\u2019 She said: \u2018make hats.\u2019 It was very practical, not a great revelation.|source=Philip Treacy, ''[[Irish Independent]]'', February 2011<ref name=\"kampen\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.independent.ie/style/fashion/philip-treacy-on-his-new-collection-26705462.html | title=Philip Treacy on his new collection | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | date=16 February 2011 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Sinead | last=Van Kampen}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1989, he took one of his hats to Michael Roberts, fashion editor of ''[[Tatler]]'' magazine, and his style editor [[Isabella Blow]].<ref name=jayne>{{cite book | last1=Sheridan | first1=Jayne | title=Fashion, media, promotion: the new black magic | date=2010 | publisher=Wiley | location=Hoboken | isbn=9781118815021 |page=27 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wXyuAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA27 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Blow asked Treacy to make a hat for her wedding,<ref name=\"egan\"/> and soon after in 1990, invited him to live with her and her new husband Detmar Blow, in their [[Belgravia]] home in London, where Treacy worked in their basement.<ref name=jayne/>  [[Alexander McQueen]], another Blow discovery, also shared her Belgravia home.<ref name=\"bryony\"/><ref>{{cite newspaper | url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG7231469/Alexander-McQueen-and-Isabella-Blow.html | title=Alex McQueen and Isabella Blow | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=14 February 2010 | first=Detmar | last=Blow | quote=I first met Alexander when Isabella invited him to live with us at 67 Elizabeth Street in Belgravia. We were on the top floor, [the milliner] Philip Treacy on the first, and Alexander was on the ground. Issie was working at British Vogue at the time and had come across Alexander at his graduate fashion show in 1992 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2002, the [[Design Museum]] in London, hosted an exhibition of the 30 most iconic hats Treacy designed for Blow, titled: ''When Philip met Isabella''.<ref name=\"irisharts\"/>  The exhibition was so well received that it went on a world tour for several years and drew a record attendance of circa 43,000 when shown in Dublin in 2005.<ref name=\"irisharts\"/>  In a 2011 interview, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' said: \"She made him famous. He made her look like an icon. When you think of the late, great Blow, you think of her in one of his creations, be it a giant disc or a replica sailing ship.\"<ref name=\"bryony\">{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/royal-wedding/8454151/Philip-Treacy-Ive-been-busy-what-with-the-wedding.html|title=Philip Treacy: 'I've been busy, what with the wedding' | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | first=Bryony |last=Gordon | date=18 April 2011 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n{{quote|My biggest inspiration has been Isabella Blow. [..] In twenty years I have met all my heroes and for me nobody has surpassed her. She was incredible. I thought there must be others like her, but there wasn't. Everyone was boring in comparison to her.|source=Philip Treacy, ''[[Irish Independent]]'', February 2011<ref name=\"kampen\"/>}}\n\n==Career==\n\n===Haute couture===\n\n[[File:Beauxbatons Academy Students (Orlando).jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|Treacy designed the [[Beauxbatons]] hats for [[Harry Potter]] in 2005]]\n\nIn 1991, Treacy, aged 23, on the prompting of Blow,<ref name=\"flowerhats\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gardening/10741693/Philip-Treacy-how-my-flower-hats-blossomed.html | title=Philip Treacy: how my flower hats blossomed | date=5 April 2014 | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Christopher | last=Woodward}}</ref> got his \"big break\",<ref name=\"examiner\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/lifestyle/features/philip-treacys-crowning-glory-357687.html | title=Philip Treacy\u2019s crowning glory | newspaper=[[The Irish Examiner]] | date=6 October 2015 | first=Rachel Marie | last=Walsh | quote=The hat designer (a description he prefers to milliner) pinpoints being summoned to Paris by Karl Lagerfeld in 1991 as his big break, comparable to an American Idol win | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>  being asked by [[Karl Lagerfeld]] to come to the [[Chanel]] showrooms in Paris, in what was to be the start of a long\u2013term working relationship.  The first hat that Treacy designed for Chanel appeared on the cover of ''[[British Vogue]]'' worn by model [[Linda Evangelista]].{{efn|The hat was called ''Twisted Birdcage'' and was photographed by French fashion photographer, [[Patrick Demarchelier]].<ref name=\"scmp\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.scmp.com/node/568036 | title=Philip Treacy | first=Carrie | last=Chan | newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]] | date=18 October 2006 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>  Treacy chose another Linda Evangelista photograph as the cover of his 2015 biography.<ref name=\"examiner\"/>}}\n\n{{quote|I was 23 and I'd just left [art] school, I didn't know whether to call him Mr. Lagerfeld or whatever. I was totally intimidated but Issie [Blow] was exactly herself. She just walked into the house of Chanel and said: \"We'd like some tea please\".  I would design hats for Chanel for the next decade.|source=Philip Treacy, ''[[Irish Independent]]'', February 2011<ref name=\"kampen\"/>}}\n\nIn 1991, Treacy opened his first showroom in London, and won his first of five British Accessory Designer of the Year awards.<ref name=\"egan\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.independent.ie/woman/celeb-news/an-audience-with-prince-philip-26215107.html|title=An audience with Prince Philip | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | first=Barry | last=Egan | date=20 November 2005 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>  In 1993, Treacy held his first fashion show during [[London Fashion Week]] in ''[[Harvey Nichols]]'', with [[Naomi Campbell]], [[Yasmin le Bon]], [[Kate Moss]], [[Christy Turlington]] and [[Stella Tennant]] modelling in return for keeping Treacy's hats, which were all black.<ref name=\"egan\"/><ref name=\"scmp\"/>  In 1994, he opened up his boutique at 69 Elizabeth Street, in Belgravia, London, right beside Isabella Blow's residence at number 67.<ref name=\"flowerhats\"/><ref name=\"scmp\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londontown.com/LondonInformation/Shopping/Philip_Tracey/5b5f/|title=69 Elizabeth Street|publisher=LondonTown Guide|quote=Treacy opened this elegant shop in Elizabeth Street in 1994, next door to Blow's old house at 67 Elizabeth Street \u2013 where Treacy's business first began in the basement}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Treacy's first solo show in 1993 saw him debut on the fashion and celebrity radar when no fewer than five of the most famous supermodels of the era \u2013 Naomi Campbell, Yasmin Le Bon, Kate Moss, Stella Tennant, and Christy Turlington \u2013 appeared on his catwalk. Playing down his star appeal, Treacy is humble about his overnight success story. \"London was in a lull then,\" he said. \"The media went crazy when all those girls did my show, but it completely changed perceptions of the hat.|source=Philip Treacy, ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'', 2007<ref name=\"smh\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/fashion/most-popular-man-in-fashion-20030526-gdgtnu.html | title=Most popular man in fashion | newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | date=26 May 2003 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Philip Treacy London Boutique.jpg|thumb|Philip Treacy's boutique, 69 Elizabeth Street, Belgravia, London.]]\n\nTreacy has designed hats for [[Alexander McQueen]] (another discovery of Isabella Blow),{{efn|For McQueen's first Givenchy exhibition in 1997, Blow had the horns cut from a ram in her flock of rare\u2013breed sheep, which Treacy then sprayed with gold, and which Naomi Campbell then wore on the runway.<ref name=\"smh\"/>}} including his 1999 ''white collection'' for [[Givenchy]] [[Haute Couture]] in Paris, for [[Karl Lagerfeld]] at [[Chanel]], and for [[Valentino Garavani|Valentino]], [[Ralph Lauren]], [[Donna Karan]], [[Versace]] and [[Rifat \u00d6zbek]].  In January 2000, he became the first milliner for eighty years to be invited to exhibit at the Paris shows.{{efn|name=\"orch\"}}<ref name=\"guar\"/><ref name=\"orchid2\"/> In November 2015, ''Vogue'' magazine ran a feature of Treacy's 20 \"most awe\u2013inspiring chapeaux\" from the runways.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.vogue.com/article/philip-treacy-book-best-hats | title=20 of Philip Treacy\u2019s Most Jaw\u2013Dropping Couture Chapeaux | magazine=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue Magazine]] \n |date=13 November 2015 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Kristin | last=Anderson}}</ref>\n\n===Wider fashion===\n\nOutside of ''[[haute couture]]'', Treacy has designed hats for films, including [[Harry Potter films|Harry Potter]] (most notably the [[Beauxbatons]] hat, for [[The Goblet of Fire]] in 2005).<ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/attractions/harry-potter-s-wardrobe-is-brimful-of-secrets-a3587376.html | title=Harry Potter\u2019s wardrobe is brimful of secrets | newspaper=The Standard | date=13 July 2017 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Jennifer | last=Ruby}}</ref> [[Sarah Jessica Parker]] has worn his hats at [[Sex and the City (film)|''Sex and the City'']] premi\u00e8res (2008, 2011), and [[Met Gala]]s (2013, 2015).{{efn|Sarah Jessica Parker's 2015 Met Gala Treacy hat was nominated by ''Vogue'' in May 2018, as one of the ''16 Craziest Celebrity Moments in Met Gala History''.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.vogue.com/article/best-met-gala-celebrity-moments-of-all-time|title=The Craziest Celebrity Moments in Met Gala History|date=2 May 2018 | magazine=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] | quote=You gotta give it to SJP: She never phones it in. The Philip Treacy headpiece she wore for the 2015 Met Gala, \u201cChina: Through the Looking Glass,\u201d will always be remembered as the hat that launched a thousand memes | accessdate=15 April 2020 }}</ref>}} Treacy designed [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s gold headpiece for her 2012 [[Super Bowl]] half\u2013time show.<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG9200192/Exclusive-Philip-Treacy-on-designing-Madonnas-Super-Bowl-hat.html|title=Exclusive: Philip Treacy on designing Madonna's Super Bowl hat | date=12 April 2012 | first=Phong | last=Luu | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | quote=Treacy made Madonna's jewelled Egyptian-ish fanned headpiece for her Super Bowl performance. He shows off the mock-up he made of it, and, even as a dummy run, it's impressive. | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> [[Lady Gaga]] described Treacy as \"the greatest milliner of all time\", while hosting his 2012 London Week fashion show.<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2012/sep/16/lady-gaga-philip-treacy-london-fashion-week | title=Lady Gaga pays tribute to milliner Philip Treacy at London fashion week | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | first=Jess | last=Cartner-Morley | date=16 September 2012 | quote=How extraordinary was Philip Treacy's London fashion week catwalk show? Put it this way: when Lady Gaga appeared wearing a floor-length neon pink veil and towering Alexander McQueen Armadillo shoes, she did not immediately attract much attention. It was that kind of night | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> Notable designs for Lady Gaga include a ''telephone-shaped headpiece with a removable handset'' hat, worn for her appearance on [[Friday Night with Jonathan Ross]] in 2010 (now in permanent display at [[Madame Tussauds]]),<ref>{{cite newspaper | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | quote=In the London Madame Tussauds, a waxwork figure of the singer wearing a show\u2013stopping Philip Treacy telephone hat which she wore on Friday Night with Jonathan Ross in March 2010 was unveiled, teamed with a Giorgio Armani Priv\u00e9 outfit with pagoda\u2013style shoulders and vertiginous heels | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/dec/09/lady-gaga-outfits-madame-tussauds | date=9 December 2010 | first=Alexandra | last=Topping | title=Lady Gaga appears in eight different outfits at eight Madame Tussauds | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> and a ''lightning-bolt'' hat she wore for the 2010 [[Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.independent.ie/style/fashion/fashion-fix/lady-gaga-shares-a-laugh-with-genius-philip-treacy-30706941.html | title=Lady Gaga shares a laugh with 'genius' Philip Treacy | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | first=Elaine | last=McCahill | date=31 October 2014 | quote=Gaga was wearing Treacy's unique hats as far back as 2010 when she wore an eye\u2013catching outfit to the Grammy Awards | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite website|url=http://hepburnette.com/blog/138_5-Crazy-Lady-Gaga-Philip-Treacy-Hats | title=5 Crazy Lady Gaga Philip Treacy Hats | website=Hepburnette.com | date=2014 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs well as Isabella Blow, Sarah Jessica Parker, and Lady Gaga, other notable muses for Treacy's hats are socialite [[Daphne Guinness]],<ref>{{cite website | url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/gallery/philip-treacy-hat-designer-book/all | title=Philip Treacy\u2019s Trippiest, Most Dazzling Hats | date=25 October 2015 | website=Architectural Digest | quote=\"Daphne is a rare bird. She\u2019s a fashion contradiction. No designer owns her. Whatever Daphne wears, she owns.\" Treacy says of Guinness | first=Colleen | last=Egan | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> model [[Naomi Campbell]],<ref name=\"examiner\"/><ref name=\"power\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.independent.ie/style/fashion/top-hat-philip-treacys-two-decades-of-creating-masterpieces-31609729.html | title=Top Hat... Philip Treacy's two decades of creating masterpieces | date=18 October 2015 | first=Bairbre | last=Power | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> and singer, and model, [[Grace Jones]],<ref name=\"grace\"/> who used Treacy as art director and designer for her 2009 ''Hurricane'' tour.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.essence.com/news/hats-off-to-grace-jones-favorite-head-topper/|title=Hats Off To Grace Jones' Favorite Head Topper|magazine=[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]| first=Patrik | last=Henry Bass | date=10 November 2011 | quote=The style icon tapped the milliner as art director and designer for her 2009 sold\u2013out \u201cHurricane\u201d tour. Long before that collaboration, Grace was sporting the milliner\u2019s works of art in videos and special appearances. | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn a July 2011 interview with ''[[The Guardian]]'', Treacy distilled what he felt a hat should do (a Treacy quote which is often reproduced):<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.independent.ie/style/fashion/top-hat-philip-treacys-two-decades-of-creating-masterpieces-31609729.html | title=Top Hat... Philip Treacy's two decades of creating masterpieces | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | date=18 October 2015 | quote=Philip Treacy's mission as a hat designer is to be creative and, as he says himself, he likes \"to make hats that make the heart beat faster\". | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Bairbre | last=Power}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Princess Beatrice's hat.jpg|thumb|150px|Princess Beatrice's [[fascinator]] \"pretzel hat\" by Philip Treacy in April 2011]]\n\n{{quote|''The Guardian'': Does a person carry off a hat or a hat carry off a person?<br>''Philip Treacy'': A person carries off the hat. Hats are about emotion. It is all about how it makes you feel. I like hats that make the heart beat faster. | source=Philip Treacy, ''[[The Guardian]]'', July 2011.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2011/jul/10/philip-treacy-milliner-interview | title=Philip Treacy: 'I like hats that make the heart beat faster' | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | date=10 July 2011 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Kate | last=Kellaway}}</ref>}}\n\nTreacy had previously written a piece for ''The Guardian'' in May 2001 on what defines the \"perfect hat\".<ref>{{cite newspaper |  url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2001/may/27/life1.lifemagazine3|title=The perfect hat | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | first=Philip |last=Treacy | date=22 May 2001 | quote=Everyone thinks you need confidence to wear a beautiful hat, but this perfect hat will instead give you the courage and the energy to carry it off. | accessdate=15 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Royal occasions===\n\nTreacy's hats are also associated with English royalty, with thirty six worn at the [[Wedding of Prince William, Duke of Cambridge, and Catherine Middleton|29 April 2011 Royal wedding]] of [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]] and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|Catherine Middleton]],<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=http://www.independent.ie/world-news/royal-wedding/philip-treacy-king-of-royal-wedding-hats-2633003.html | title=Philip Treacy: King of Royal wedding hats | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | date=29 April 2011 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> including the controversial [[fascinator]] style hat worn by [[Princess Beatrice of York]].  This so\u2013called \"pretzel hat\" was auctioned for charity by Princess Beatrice on eBay for $130,000 (\u00a380,100) on the 22 May 2011.<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/gossip/2011/05/princess-beatrices-royal-wedding-hat-sells-for-a-whopping-130000-on-ebay.html | title=Princess Beatrice\u2019s royal wedding hat sells for more than $130,000 on EBay | newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=22 May 2011 | quote=The princess plans to give the money (final bid: 81,100.01 pounds, which is around $131,134) from the 10-day auction to UNICEF UK and Children in Crisis via her Little Bee Initiative campaign. | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Emily | last=Christianson}}</ref>  Treacy felt the criticism regarding the \"pretzel hat\" was extreme (the hat had its own Facebook page with over 140,000 connections), and in July 2011 said: \"In the future, we'll look back and think she looked wild\".<ref name=\"guardian\"/>  In a July 2018 Radio 4 [[Desert Island Discs]] interview, Treacy said: \"There was a moment where I thought I would find myself with my head on a spike outside the Tower of London\", from the controversy of the \"pretzel hat\".<ref>{{cite website |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-44755082 | title=Royal hat-maker Philip Treacy 'feared head on spike' | website=[[BBC News]] | date=8 July 2018 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>  The hat resides at the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].<ref>{{cite website | url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/171324|title=PHILIP TREACY HAT (c. 2011): Gift of Melinda B. Hildebrand, 2012| website=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] | quote=Accession Number: 2012.519 (search item 171324) | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nTreacy designed over twenty hats that were worn at the 19 May 2018 [[Wedding of Prince Harry and Meghan Markle]], including by [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]], by [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]], and by [[Oprah Winfrey]].<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.independent.ie/style/fashion/fashion-news/irish-designer-philip-treacy-created-20-hats-for-the-british-royal-wedding-including-oprahs-36923734.html | title=Irish designer Philip Treacy created 20 hats for the British royal wedding - including Oprah's | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | date=19 May 2018 | quote=Treacy designed hats for [[Oprah Winfrey]], Priyanka Chopra, Camilla, the Duchess of Cornwall, and Kate Middleton for Meghan and Harry's big day | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Karen | last=Birney}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/celebrity/latest/g20106557/meghan-markle-prince-harry-royal-wedding-hats/?slide=1 | title=All the Hats at Meghan Markle and Prince Harry's Wedding | magazine=[[Harper's Bazaar]] | date=19 May 2018 | quote=There was a lot of Philip Treacy. | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Tamara | last=Abraham}}</ref>  [[Megan Markle]] chose a Treacy hat for her first official royal event in December 2017.<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.independent.ie/style/fashion/meghan-markle-chose-irish-designer-philip-treacy-hat-for-first-royal-outing-36438983.html | title=Meghan Markle chose Irish designer Philip Treacy hat for first 'royal outing' | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | date=27 December 2017 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Bairbre |last=Power}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/meghan-s-first-official-duty-tops-off-hat-maker-philip-treacy-s-rise-wtwpq6g77 | title=Meghan's first official duty tops off hat-maker Philip Treacy\u2019s rise | first=Jennifer | last=O'Brien | newspaper=[[The Times]] | date=24 May 2018 | quote=Hats off to him. Philip Treacy, the Galway-born milliner, has cemented his position as the primary choice of hatmaker for the royal family. | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Treacy credited the [[Elizabeth II|Queen]] with \"single-handedly saving the British hat industry\".<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/07/07/queenspatronage-has-single-handedly-saved-british-hat-industry/ | title=Queen's patronage has single-handedly saved the British hat industry, Philip Treacy says | newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | date=8 July 2018 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first= Hannah | last=Furness}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n\n[[File:Duchess of Cornwall 2012.JPG|thumb|150px|[[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]] wearing a Treacy hat in June 2012]]\n\nTreacy won the title of British Accessory Designer of the Year at the [[British Fashion Awards]] five times during the 1990s (1991, 1992, 1993, 1996 and 1997).<ref>{{cite website |title=Philip Treacy 'Hatforms' at IMMA Thursday|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2001/0405/treacyp.html|accessdate=11 December 2010|website=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]]|date=5 April 2001 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>  In January 2000, Treacy was invited by the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration fran\u00e7aise de la couture|Chambre Syndicale de la Haute Couture]] to participate in Paris fashion shows, the first milliner to be invited in 80 years.{{efn|name=\"orch\"|Treacy exhibited his ''Orchid Collection'' at the Paris 2000 haute couture shows.<ref name=\"orchid\">{{cite newspaper |url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG3363781/Philip-Treacy-Madcap-milliner-receives-OBE.html | title=Madcap milliner receives OBE| newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | first=Hillary |last=Alexander | date=19 November 2007 | quote=In 2000, he made millinery history by staging his 'Orchid' collection of haute couture hats in Paris | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>}}<ref name=\"guar\">{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2002/apr/16/fashion|title=Who wants to be a milliner|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|first=Jess | last=Cartner-Morley|date=16 April 2002|quote=He has created hats to accompany the catwalk collections of Alexander McQueen and Valentino, has been named British Accessory Designer of the Year five times, and was the first milliner in 80 years to be invited by French fashion's governing body, the Chambre Syndicale, to take part in the Parisian haute couture shows | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"orchid2\">{{cite magazine | url=https://www.vogue.it/en/fashion/news/2010/03/09/philip-treacy/?refresh_ce= |title=Philip Treacy | magazine=[[Vogue Italia]] | date=9 March 2010 | quote=In 2000, he was the first milliner in 70 years to be invited by the Chambre Syndicale to show his collection during the Haute Couture fashion week in Paris | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2004, Treacy was named the International Designer of the Year, at the [[China Fashion Week|China Fashion Awards]] in Shanghai.<ref name=\"scmp\"/>  In April 2006, he was awarded a Doctorate of Fine Arts, by the [[National University of Ireland]] at [[University College Dublin]] (\"UCD\").<ref name=colm/><ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/irish-hat-designer-philip-treacy-turns-royal-heads-with-obe-award-48391.html|title=Irish hat designer Philip Treacy turns royal heads with OBE award|newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]]|date=20 November 2007| accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe was awarded an honorary [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] (Order of the British Empire) for services to the British fashion industry by [[Prince Charles]] and [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]] at a special ceremony in [[Clarence House]] in November 2007.{{efn|Because Treacy is Irish, and not sworn to allegiance to the Crown, the ceremony was not held with the Queen in Buckingham Palace.  Normally, in such cases, a Government Minister would perform the ceremony, however, Prince Charles intervened to host the ceremony in Clarence House.}}<ref name=\"personal\">{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.independent.ie/style/fashion/prince-honours-king-of-the-hats-26333118.html | title=Prince honours king of the hats | newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | quote=Irishman Philip Treacy (40) received an honorary OBE at a special ceremony hosted by Prince Charles and his wife, Camilla Parker Bowles, at their Clarence House home. The fashion designer was appointed an honorary Officer of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire (OBE). The honour was conferred on Philip by Queen Elizabeth in recognition of his services to the British Fashion industry | date=20 November 2007 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Bairbre |last=Power}}</ref>  Treacy designed the headdress worn by the Duchess of Cornwall for [[Wedding of Charles, Prince of Wales, and Camilla Parker Bowles|the couple's wedding]].<ref name=\"personal\"/>\n\nIn July 2010, Treacy was one of six contemporary and internationally renowned Irish fashion designers honoured by a set of [[Postage stamps of Ireland|Irish postage stamps]] issued by [[An Post]]. The other designers were [[Paul Costelloe]], [[Louise Kennedy]], [[John Rocha]], [[Lainey Keogh]] and [[Orla Kiely]].<ref>{{cite newspaper | url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/fashion/stamp-of-approval-1.620308 | newspaper=[[Irish Times]] | date=10 July 2010 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Deirdre | last=McQuillan | title=Stamp Of Approval}}</ref><ref>{{cite website | title=Magnificent Irish fashionista stamps | url=http://www.worldstampnews.com/2010/07/magnificent-irish-fashionista-stamps/ | accessdate=23 January 2014 | website=World Stamp News | date=18 July 2010|url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203001930/http://www.worldstampnews.com/2010/07/magnificent-irish-fashionista-stamps/|archivedate=3 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nTreacy's hats have been exhibited, and are housed in the collections of design museums including the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]],<ref name=\"orchid2\"/><ref>{{cite website |url=https://collections.vam.ac.uk/search/?listing_type=&offset=0&limit=15&narrow=&extrasearch=&q=Philip+Treacy&commit=Search&quality=0&objectnamesearch=&placesearch=&after=&before=&namesearch=&materialsearch=&mnsearch=&locationsearch=|title=Victoria & Albert: Philip Treacy | website=Victoria and Albert Museum | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]],<ref name=\"orchid2\"/><ref>{{cite website | url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search#!?q=Philip%20Treacy|title=Search The Met Collection: Philip Treacy | website=MetMuseum.com | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> and the ''Galleria del Costume'' of the [[Palazzo Pitti]] in Florence.<ref>{{cite website |url=http://www.firenzemadeintuscany.com/en/arts/articles/hats-between-art-and-extravaganza-in-florence/|title=Exhibition in Florence: The Hat Between Art and Extravaganza|date=28 November 2013|quote=Despite prevailing specimens of known names of the fashion house such as Christian Dior, Givenchy, Chanel, Yves Saint Laurent, Prada, Gianfranco Ferre and international famous milliners of the present and the past like Philip Treacy, [[Stephen Jones (milliner)|Stephen Jones]], [[Caroline Reboux]], [[Claude Saint-Cyr]], and [Madame] Paulette [..]|website=FIRENZE | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> ''Vogue'' magazine has described Treacy, on a number of occasions, as being the \"greatest milliner in the world\".<ref name=\"vog2\">{{cite magazine | url=https://www.vogue.com/article/best-summer-hats| title=7 Chic Hats We've Fallen Head Over Heels For This Summer | magazine=Vogue|first=Lynn | last=Yaeger|date=24 June 2015|quote=As Philip Treacy, one of our greatest living milliners, once said, \"Wearing a hat is fun! People have a good time when they're wearing a hat\". | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"vog1\">{{cite magazine | url=https://www.vogue.com/article/thriller-night-at-philip-treacy-the-king-of-pops-wardrobe-meets-its-millinery-match | title=Thriller Night: At Philip Treacy, the King of Pop's Wardrobe Meets Its Millinery Match | magazine=Vogue | first=Lynn | last=Yaeger |date=17 September 2012 | quote=On one thing, at least, the ecstatic throng can agree\u2014it is a London show like none other, and Gaga is right: Treacy is perhaps the greatest milliner in the world | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTreacy is gay and in May 2017 he married his long\u2013term partner of over 21 years, Stefan Bartlett, in a ceremony in Las Vegas.<ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.independent.ie/style/celebrity/irish-designer-philip-treacy-weds-long-term-love-in-las-vegas-and-celebrates-with-cher-35688627.html|title=Irish designer Philip Treacy weds long\u2013term love in Las Vegas - and celebrates with Cher|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]]|date=7 May 2017 | accessdate=15 April 2020 | first=Patricia | last=Murphy}}</ref>\n\nTreacy has noted the support his parents{{efn|Treacy's father was a baker and his mother was a housewife,<ref name=\"cul\">{{cite website|url=http://www.culch.ie/2009/06/03/philip-treacy-the-culchie-interview/|title=Philip Treacy Interview|website=Culch.ie|date=3 June 2009|first=Darragh|last= Doyle|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> however, his father had a weak heart which prevented him from working as a full-time baker, and he eventually died when Philip was age 11 from a heart attack; Treacy's mother died in 1993, when Philip was 25.<ref name=\"egan\"/>}} gave him in pursuing his love of millinery, noting that his father would say: \"whatever makes him happy\".<ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/fashion/irish-milliner-philip-treacy-feared-head-on-spike-over-beatrice-hat-1.3557971|title=Irish milliner Philip Treacy 'feared head on spike' over Beatrice hat|newspaper=[[Irish Times]] | date=8 July 2018 | quote=One of the strongest memories I have is being in somebody's house and my father's friend saying don't you think that's a little odd, don't you think it's a bit strange this child is doing this?'  And I remember distinctly my father saying: 'Whatever makes him happy'. It moves me still. | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/raise-your-hat-to-philip-26248191.html|title=Raise your hat to Philip|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] | first=Mary | last=O'Sullivan | date=15 April 2001 | accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>  Treacy called his friendship with his mentor, Isabella Blow, as: \"an affair without sex\".<ref name=\"bryony\"/> Treacy also highlights the importance of fashion model [[Grace Jones]] as a collaborator and friend.<ref name=\"grace\">{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/fashion/irish-milliner-philip-treacy-feared-head-on-spike-over-beatrice-hat-1.3557971|title=Irish milliner Philip Treacy|date=8 July 2018|newspaper=[[Irish Times]] | quote=Treacy also spoke candidly to Young about how he has overcome some of the losses in his life with the help of close friend and eccentric collaborator Grace Jones. \"If you told somebody you were getting advice from Grace Jones they would probably tell you you need your head examined,\" said Treacy. \"But she actually gives really good advice\".|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nTreacy is the second youngest of a large family and has one sister,<ref name=\"ia\"/> and seven brothers.<ref name=\"personal\"/><ref name=\"cul\"/>  He is particularly close to his sister, Marion Tubbing,<ref name=\"personal\"/> the eldest sibling, whom he credits with supplying him with editions of ''[[Harper's and Queen]]'' and ''Vogue'' while living in Galway (Tubbing was working in London at the time),<ref name=\"ia\">{{cite magazine | url=https://irishamerica.com/2007/02/the-master-hatter/ | title=The Master Hatter | magazine=[[Irish America (magazine)|Irish America]] | date=March 2007 | quote=Being the second youngest of seven boys, and with one sister who was the eldest child, Philip recollects, \"I thought my sister, Marion, was the most glamorous girl in the world. She was a huge inspiration to me. She was my introduction to fashion and magazines. She worked as a nurse in London and used to come home on holidays with all these great magazines like Harper's and Queen and Vogue, which I'd never seen.\"|first=Marilyn |last=Cole Lownes|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> and for whom, along with his partner Stefan Bartlett, Treacy dedicated his 2015 biography: ''Philip Treacy: Hat Designer''.<ref name=\"power\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Designs by Philip Treacy}}\n{{Portal|Ireland|Fashion}}\n* [[John Boyd (milliner)|John Boyd]], milliner\n* [[Stephen Jones (milliner)|Stephen Jones]], milliner\n* [[Claude Saint-Cyr]], milliner\n* [[Caroline Reboux]], milliner\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Blow\n  | first = Isabella\n  | title = Philip Treacy (Memoire) \n  | publisher = Assouline\n  | isbn = 978-2843233937\n  | year = 2011\n   }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Davies\n  | first = Kevin\n  | title = Philip Treacy\n  | publisher = Phaidon Press\n  | isbn = 978-0714865270\n  | year = 2013\n   }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Hume\n  | first = Marion\n  | title = Philip Treacy: Hat Designer\n  | publisher = Rizzoli International Publications\n  | isbn = 978-0847846504\n  | year = 2015\n   }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Reed\n  | first = Paula\n  | title = Philip Treacy\n  | publisher = Charta\n  | isbn = 978-8881583553\n  | year = 2001\n   }}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Treacy\n  | first = Philip\n  | title = Philip Treacy: \"When Philip Met Isabella\"\n  | publisher =  Assouline\n  | isbn = 978-2843233722\n  | year = 2003\n   }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://www.philiptreacy.co.uk/en}}\n*[http://www.fashionencyclopedia.com/To-Vi/Treacy-Philip.html Philip Treacy] at Fashion Encyclopedia\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/philip-treacy Philip Treacy] at [[The 