Cook Stats, Bio and Game Logs | NBA.com]</ref>\n* [[Norm Cook]], [[NBA]] player<ref>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/c/cookno01.html Norm Cook NBA & ABA Stats | Basketball-Reference.com]</ref>\n* [[Terry Kinney]], actor<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0455767/?ref_=sr_1 Terry Kinney - IMDb]</ref>\n* [[Edward Madigan]], Former United States Secretary of Agriculture\n* [[William Keepers Maxwell]], Jr., editor, novelist, short story writer\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Illinois}}\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Logan County, Illinois]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.co.logan.il.us/ Official website]\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Logan County, Illinois\n|North     = [[Tazewell County, Illinois|Tazewell County]]\n|Northeast = [[McLean County, Illinois|McLean County]]\n|East      = [[De Witt County, Illinois|De Witt County]]\n|Southeast = [[Macon County, Illinois|Macon County]]\n|South     = [[Sangamon County, Illinois|Sangamon County]]\n|Southwest = \n|West      = [[Menard County, Illinois|Menard County]]\n|Northwest = [[Mason County, Illinois|Mason County]]\n}}\n{{Logan County, Illinois}}\n{{Illinois}}\n{{coord|40.13|-89.36|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-IL_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Illinois counties]]\n[[Category:1839 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1839]]\n[[Category:Logan County, Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Whoisjohngalt", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logan_County,_Illinois"}
{"title_page": "It's Only Rock 'n Roll", "text_new": "{{Other uses|It's Only Rock and Roll (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = It's Only Rock 'n Roll\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[the Rolling Stones]]\n| cover      = IORNRCover.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = 18 October 1974{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n| recorded   = 25 November \u2013 21 December 1972, 13\u201324 November 1973, 14\u201328 January, 10\u201315 April, 20\u201325 May 1974\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Rock and roll]]\n* [[blues rock]]\n* [[funk rock]]<ref name=\"Rivadavia\">{{cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/rolling-stones-its-only-rock-n-roll/|title=How the Rolling Stones Returned to the Fundamentals on 'It's Only Rock 'n' Roll'|first=Eduardo|last=Rivadavia|website=Ultimate Classic Rock}}</ref>}}\n| length     = 48:26\n| label      = [[Rolling Stones Records|Rolling Stones]]\n| producer   = [[Jagger/Richards]]<br />(credited as The Glimmer Twins)\n| prev_title = [[Goats Head Soup]]\n| prev_year  = 1973\n| next_title = [[Black and Blue]]\n| next_year  = 1976\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = It's Only Rock 'n Roll\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[It's Only Rock 'n Roll (But I Like It)]]\n | single1date = 26 July 1974\n | single2     = [[Ain't Too Proud to Beg]]\n | single2date = 25 October 1974\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''It's Only Rock 'n Roll''''' is the 12th British and 14th American studio album by [[the Rolling Stones]], released on 18 October 1974. It was the last Rolling Stones album for guitarist [[Mick Taylor]] and the songwriting and recording of the album's title track had a connection to Taylor's eventual replacement, [[Ronnie Wood]]. The album also marked the 10th anniversary since the release of the band's debut album, [[The Rolling Stones (album)|''The Rolling Stones'']]. ''It's Only Rock 'n Roll'' combines the core [[British blues|blues]] and [[rock 'n' roll]]-oriented sound with elements of [[funk]] and [[reggae]].<ref name=\"Rivadavia\">{{cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/rolling-stones-its-only-rock-n-roll/|title=How the Rolling Stones Returned to the Fundamentals on 'It's Only Rock 'n' Roll'|first=Eduardo|last=Rivadavia|website=Ultimate Classic Rock}}</ref> ''It's Only Rock 'n Roll'' reached number one in the United States and number two in the UK.\n\nThough it wasn't as successful as their prior albums, ''It's Only Rock 'n Roll'' was an important transitional album for the Rolling Stones.  Long-time producer [[Jimmy Miller]] was out, and the album was self-produced by guitarist [[Keith Richards]] and singer [[Mick Jagger]] under the pseudonym \"[[The Glimmer Twins]]\".  Guitarist [[Mick Taylor]] missed the initial recording sessions with health problems, and ended up quitting the Rolling Stones a few months after the album's release.  The rest of the instrumentation included bassist [[Bill Wyman]] and drummer [[Charlie Watts]], as well as frequent collaborators [[Ian Stewart (musician)|Ian Stewart]], [[Nicky Hopkins]], and [[Billy Preston]], and featured the first appearance of percussionist [[Ray Cooper]], who would continue to work with the Rolling Stones into the 1980s.\n\nThe [[It's Only Rock 'n Roll (But I Like It)|title track]] bears special note as it was recorded separately from the rest of the album.  The basic rhythm track had been laid down by members of the [[Faces (band)|Faces]], including rhythm guitarist [[Ronnie Wood]] and drummer [[Kenney Jones]], during a jam session with Mick Jagger, [[David Bowie]], and bassist [[Willie Weeks]].  Jagger liked the song so much, he brought the basic track to Richards, who added some guitar overdubs, and after some polishing, was put on the album as-is.  After Taylor left the Rolling Stones at the end of 1974, the band would approach Wood to become a full-time member.\n\n==History==\nWork began on ''It's Only Rock 'n Roll'' following the Rolling Stones' autumn [[The Rolling Stones 1973 European Tour|1973 European tour]]. Production began in November at [[Munich]], [[Germany]]'s [[Musicland Studios]]. According to guitarist [[Keith Richards]], \"We were really hot (off the road) and ready just to play some new material.\"<ref name=\"RS 175\">{{cite web|last=Turner|first=Steve|title=Making The Stones' New Album|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/making-the-stones-new-album-19741205|work=Rolling Stone Magazine No. 175|accessdate=26 November 2012|date=5 December 1974}}</ref> The recording sessions were attended by Belgian painter [[Guy Peellaert]], who [[Mick Jagger]] invited to do the album cover after seeing his work in the book ''Rock Dreams'', which featured illustrations of various rock musicians such as the Stones. Peellaert eventually painted the band as \"rock deities,\" descending a temple staircase, surrounded by young girls and women worshiping them in [[Clothing in ancient Greece|Grecian clothing]]. The artist refused to sign a deal of exclusivity, and in 1974 provided the album art for [[David Bowie]]'s ''[[Diamond Dogs]]''.<ref>[https://www.athenaart.com/its-only-rock-n-roll.html IT'S ONLY ROCK N ROLL] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022141152/https://www.athenaart.com/its-only-rock-n-roll.html |date=22 October 2016 }}, Athena Art</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Mammoth Book of the Rolling Stones: An anthology of the best writing about the greatest rock \u2018n\u2019 roll band in the world\n|first=Sean|last=Egan|page=182|publisher=Hachette|year=2013|ISBN=1-78033-647-0}}</ref>\n\n===Recording===\nThe album was at first developed as a half-live, half-studio production with one side of the album featuring live performances from the Stones' European tour while the other side was to be composed of newly recorded cover versions of the band's favourite [[R&B]] songs. Covers recorded included a take of [[Dobie Gray]]'s \"[[Drift Away]]\", [[Jimmy Reed]]'s \"Shame Shame Shame,\u201d and [[The Temptations]]' \"[[Ain't Too Proud to Beg]].\" Soon the band began working off riffs by Richards and new ideas by [[Mick Jagger]] and the original concept was scrapped in favour of an album with all-new material. The cover of \"Ain't Too Proud to Beg\" was the only recording to make the cut, while the \"Drift Away\" cover is a popular [[bootleg recording|bootleg]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stadler |first1=Gustavus |title=Cover Art |url=http://avidly.lareviewofbooks.org/2013/06/25/cover-art/ |website=Avidly |accessdate=23 April 2019 |date=25 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n''It's Only Rock 'n Roll'' marked the Stones' first effort in the producer's chair since ''[[Their Satanic Majesties Request]]'', and the first for Jagger and Richards under their pseudonym \"[[The Glimmer Twins]].\" On the choice to produce, Richards said at the time:\n\n<blockquote>\"I think we'd come to a point with [[Jimmy Miller|Jimmy (Miller)]] where the contribution level had dropped because it'd got to be a habit, a way of life, for Jimmy to do one Stones album a year. He'd got over the initial sort of excitement which you can feel on ''[[Beggars Banquet]]'' and ''[[Let It Bleed]]''. Also, Mick and I felt that we wanted to try and do it ourselves because we really felt we knew much more about techniques and recording and had our own ideas of how we wanted things to go. ''Goats Head Soup'' hadn't turned out as we wanted to \u2013 not blaming Jimmy or anything like that... But it was obvious that it was time for a change in that particular part of the process of making records.\"<ref name=\"RS 175\" /></blockquote>\n\nStarting with this release, all future Rolling Stones albums would either be produced by themselves or in collaboration with an outside producer.\n\nMost of the album's backing tracks were recorded first at Musicland; solo vocals were recorded later by Jagger, about whom Richards would say, \"he often comes up with his best stuff alone in the studio with just an engineer.\"<ref name=\"RS 175\" />\n\nThe song \"Luxury\" showed the band's growing interest in [[reggae]] music, while \"[[Till the Next Goodbye]]\" and \"If You Really Want to Be My Friend\" continued their immersion in [[ballad]]s. Seven of the album's 10 songs crack the four-minute mark, a feature that would come to be disparaged during the rising [[punk rock]] scene of the late 1970s.\n\n[[Ronnie Wood]], a long-time acquaintance of the band, began to get closer to the Rolling Stones during these sessions after he invited Mick Taylor to play on his debut album, ''[[I've Got My Own Album to Do]]''. Taylor spent some time recording and hanging out at Wood's house [[The Wick]]. By chance, Richards was asked one night by Wood's wife at the time, Krissy, to join them at the guitarist's home.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} While there, Richards recorded some tracks with Wood and quickly developed a close friendship, with Richards going as far as moving into Wood's guest room.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} Jagger soon entered the mix and it was here that the album's lead single and title track, \"[[It's Only Rock 'n Roll (But I Like It)]]\", was first recorded. Wood worked closely on the track with Jagger, who subsequently took the song and title for their album. The released version of this song features Wood on 12-string acoustic guitar.\n\n''It's Only Rock 'n Roll'' was Mick Taylor's last album with the Rolling Stones, and he played on just seven of the 10 tracks (he did not play on tracks 2, 3 or 6).{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nSimilar to receiving no writing credits on the Stones' previous album, ''Goats Head Soup'', Taylor reportedly had made songwriting contributions to \"Till the Next Goodbye\" and \"[[Time Waits for No One (song)|Time Waits for No One]],\" but on the album jacket, all original songs were credited to Jagger/Richards. Taylor said in 1997:\n\n<blockquote>\"I did have a falling out with Mick Jagger over some songs I felt I should have been credited with co-writing on ''It's Only Rock 'n Roll''. We were quite close friends and co-operated quite closely on getting that album made. By that time Mick and Keith weren't really working together as a team so I'd spend a lot of time in the studio.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Bungey|first=John|title=Hello Goodbye|url=http://www.micktaylorwemissyou.com/mojo.html|work=Issue 48|publisher=Mojo Magazine|accessdate=26 November 2012|date=November 1997}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nTaylor's statement contradicts Jagger's earlier comment concerning the album. Jagger stated in a 1995 ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' interview about \"Time Waits for No One\" that Taylor \"maybe threw in a couple of chords.\"{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nAlongside the usual outside contributors, namely [[Billy Preston]], [[Nicky Hopkins]] and unofficial member [[Ian Stewart (musician)|Ian Stewart]], [[Elton John]] sideman [[Ray Cooper]] acted as percussionist for the album. Several songs were finished songs and overdubs and mixing were performed at Jagger's home, [[Stargroves]], in the early summer of 1974.\n\n==Release and reception==\n{{Album reviews\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r16838|pure_url=yes}} link]</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies|Christgau's Record Guide]]''\n|rev2score = B<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=rolling+stone|title=Robert Christgau: CG: rolling stone|website=www.robertchristgau.com}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[D\u017euboks]]''\n|rev3score = (unfavourable)<ref name=\"dzuboks\">{{cite journal|last=|first=|title=It's Only Rock 'n Roll|journal=D\u017euboks|publisher=De\u010dje novine|location=Gornji Milanovac|issue=5 (second series)|page=23|language=Serbian}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[The Great Rock Discography]]''\n|rev4Score = 6/10<ref name=\"OnlyR'n'R/Acclaimed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/A324.htm|title=The Rolling Stones ''It's Only Rock 'n' Roll''|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141127214917/http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/A324.htm|archive-date=27 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|rev5 = [[MusicHound]]\n|rev5score = 3/5<ref>{{cite book|last1=Graff|first1=Gary|last2=Durchholz|first2=Daniel (eds)|title=MusicHound Rock: The Essential Album Guide|publisher=Visible Ink Press|location=Farmington Hills, MI|year=1999|isbn=1-57859-061-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781578590612/page/952 952]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781578590612/page/952}}</ref>\n|rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n|rev6Score = 6/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cduniverse.com/productinfo.asp?pid=7911448&style=music |title=The Rolling Stones \u2013 It's Only Rock 'n' Roll CD|publisher=[[CD Universe]]/[[Muze]]|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref>\n|rev7 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n|rev7score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110412195111/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/the-rolling-stones/albumguide \"The Rolling Stones: Album Guide\"]. [[Rolling Stone|rollingstone.com]]. Archived version retrieved 15 November 2014.</ref>\n|rev8 = [[Tom Hull (critic)|Tom Hull]]\n|rev8Score = B<ref>{{cite web|last=Hull|first=Tom|authorlink=Tom Hull (critic)|date=n.d.|url=http://tomhull.com/ocston/nm/get_gl.php?n=The+Rolling+Stones|title=Grade List: The Rolling Stones|website=tomhull.com|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n|rev9 = ''[[Virgin Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n|rev9Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"OnlyR'n'R/Acclaimed\" />\n}}\nIn July 1974, the lead single, \"It's Only Rock \u2019n Roll (But I Like It),\" was released. Despite the familiar sound, it surprised many by failing to reach the top 10 in the United States (although it did reach the top 10 in the UK). With its sing-along chorus, it has become a staple at Rolling Stones concerts. The B-side \"Through the Lonely Nights\" dates back to the previous year's ''[[Goats Head Soup]]'' sessions. A cover of \"Ain\u2019t Too Proud to Beg,\" originally a 1966 hit by [[The Temptations]], was released as the second single in the United States only, where it also became a top 20 hit. Its parent album appeared in October with brisk initial sales, reaching number two in the UK (breaking a string of number-one albums that stretched back to 1969's ''[[Let It Bleed]]'') and number one in the United States, where it eventually went platinum.\n\nReviews were largely positive, with [[Jon Landau]] calling ''It's Only Rock \u2019n Roll'' \"one of the most intriguing and mysterious, as well as the darkest, of all Rolling Stones records.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Landau|first=John|title=The Rolling Stones / It's Only Rock 'n Roll|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/its-only-rock-n-roll-19741219|work=Rolling Stone Magazine No. 172|accessdate=26 November 2012|date=16 October 1974}}</ref> However rock critic [[Lester Bangs]] disparaged the album in ''[[The Village Voice]]'', much like ''Goats Head Soup'', saying, \"The Stones have become oblique in their old age, which is just another word for perverse except that perverse is the corniest concept extant as they realized at inception... ''Soup'' was friendly and safe. I want the edge and this album doesn't reassure me that I'll get it, what a curious situation to be stuck in, but maybe that's the beauty of the Stones, hah, hah, kid? This album is false. Numb. But it cuts like a dull blade. Are they doing the cutting, or are we?\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Bangs|first=Lester|title=It's Only the Rolling Stones|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jEeovH2wN9kC&pg=PA156|work=The Village Voice|accessdate=26 November 2012|date=31 October 1974}}</ref>\n\nAuthor James Hector added that ''It's Only Rock \u2019n Roll'' was a definitive turning point for the band. \"The album marked the band\u2019s decisive entry into a comfortable living as rock's elder statesmen. From this point on, their youth culture importance vanished, and there would be few musical surprises in the future.\" Hector concluded with \"On ''It's Only Rock \u2019n Roll'', the band had become what they imagined their mass audience desired them to be. They were wrong.\"<ref>{{cite book | last = Hector | first = James | authorlink =  | coauthors = | title = The Complete Guide to the Music of The Rolling Stones| publisher =Omnibus Press | year = 1995 | location = London, England | pages = 95 | doi = | id = | isbn = 0-7119-4303-6}}</ref>\n\nInstead of immediately touring to promote the album, the band decided to head back into the Munich studios to record the next album, to Mick Taylor's disappointment and subsequent resignation from the band.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} A tour didn't happen until the following summer in the United States, the \u2018[[Rolling Stones Tour of the Americas '75|Tour of the Americas '75]]\u2019, with future member Ronnie Wood taking Taylor's place on guitar.\n\nThe title track became a permanent staple of the band's live setlist, but apart from some performances of \"Ain\u2019t Too Proud to Beg\" and \"If You Can\u2019t Rock Me\" on the [[Licks Tour]], none of the other tracks have been performed since 1977. As of 2006, \"Till The Next Goodbye,\" \"Time Waits For No-One,\" \"If You Really Want To Be My Friend\" and \"Short and Curlies\" had never been played live.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocksoff.org/debuts.htm|title=ROCKS OFF SETLISTS|website=www.rocksoff.org}}</ref>\n\nIn order to promote the album, music videos were filmed for several of the songs. The most commonly seen video from the album was the one for \"It\u2019s Only Rock\u2019n\u2019Roll (But I Like It),\" featuring the band (in sailor suits) playing in a tent, which gradually fills with soap bubbles (Taylor is featured in the video but did not actually play on the recorded cut). Videos were also filmed for \"Ain\u2019t Too Proud to Beg\" and \"Till The Next Goodbye.\"\n\nIn 1994, ''It's Only Rock \u2019n Roll'' was remastered and reissued by [[Virgin Records]], in 2009 by [[Universal Music]], and once more in 2011 by [[Universal Music Enterprises]] in a Japanese-only SHM-[[Super Audio CD|SACD]] version. The 1994 remaster was initially released in a Collector's Edition CD, which replicated in miniature elements of the original vinyl album packaging.\n\nTwo different versions of \"Luxury\" exist. A shorter version (4:30) is included on the early CD version from 1986, while the 5:01 version was originally released on vinyl in Europe, and on the 1994 and 2009 CD remasters. The difference is the shorter version starts the fadeout 30 seconds earlier, and thereby missing the short guitar solo at the end.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Tracklist\n| all_writing = [[Jagger/Richards|Mick Jagger and Keith Richards]], except where noted\n| headline = Side one\n| title1   = [[If You Can't Rock Me]]\n| length1  = 3:46\n| title2   = [[Ain't Too Proud to Beg]]\n| note2    = writers: [[Norman Whitfield]], [[Eddie Holland]]\n| length2  = 3:30\n| title3   = [[It's Only Rock 'n Roll (But I Like It)]]\n| writer3    = \n| length3  = 5:07\n| title4   = [[Till the Next Goodbye]]\n| length4  = 4:37\n| title5   = [[Time Waits for No One (song)|Time Waits for No One]]\n| length5  = 6:37\n}}\n{{Tracklist\n| headline = Side two\n| title1   = Luxury\n| length1  = 5:00\n| title2   = [[Dance Little Sister (The Rolling Stones song)|Dance Little Sister]]\n| length2  = 4:11\n| title3   = If You Really Want to Be My Friend\n| length3  = 6:16\n| title4   = Short and Curlies\n| length4  = 2:43\n| title5  = [[Fingerprint File]]\n| length5 = 6:33\n}}\n\n===Other songs===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Length\n!Notes\n|-\n|\"Through the Lonely Nights\"\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 4:07\n|rowspan=\"1\"| \"It's Only Rock 'N Roll\" B-side\n|}\n\n==Personnel==\n'''The Rolling Stones'''\n*[[Mick Jagger]] \u2013 lead vocals {{small|(all tracks)}}, backing vocals {{small|(1\u20136, 9)}}, acoustic guitar {{small|(4)}}, electric guitar {{small|(10)}}\n*[[Keith Richards]] \u2013 electric guitar {{small|(all but 4)}}, backing vocals {{small|(1\u20136, 8, 9)}}, acoustic guitar {{small|(4, 8)}}, bass guitar {{small|(1)}}\n*[[Mick Taylor]] \u2013 electric guitar {{small|(1, 4, 5, 7\u20139)}}, acoustic guitar {{small|(4, 5)}}, bass guitar {{small|(10)}}\n*[[Bill Wyman]] \u2013 bass guitar {{small|(2, 4\u20139)}}, [[synthesizer]] {{small|(5, 10)}}\n*[[Charlie Watts]] \u2013 drums {{small|(all but 3)}}\n\n\n'''Additional personnel'''\n*[[Nicky Hopkins]] \u2013 piano {{small|(4\u20136, 8, 10)}}\n*[[Billy Preston]] \u2013 piano {{small|(1, 2, 10)}}, [[clavinet]] {{small|(2, 10)}}, organ {{small|(8)}}\n*[[Ian Stewart (musician)|Ian Stewart]] \u2013 piano {{small|(3, 7, 9)}}\n*[[Ray Cooper]] \u2013 percussion {{small|(1, 2, 5, 6)}}\n*[[Blue Magic (band)|Blue Magic]] \u2013 backing vocals {{small|(8)}}\n*Charlie Jolly \u2013 [[tabla]] {{small|(10)}}\n*Ed Leach \u2013 [[cowbell (instrument)|cowbell]] {{small|(2)}}\n\n'''Basic track on \"It's Only Rock 'n Roll (But I Like It)\"'''\n*[[Kenney Jones]] \u2013 drums\n*[[Willie Weeks]] \u2013 bass guitar\n*[[David Bowie]] \u2013 backing vocals\n*[[Ronnie Wood]] \u2013 twelve\u2013string acoustic guitar, backing vocals\n\n'''Production'''\n*[[Andy Johns]] \u2013 [[Audio engineering|recording engineer]]\n*[[Keith Harwood]] \u2013 recording engineer, mixing\n*George Chkiants \u2013 overdub engineer\n*[[Glyn Johns]] \u2013 mixing (on \"Fingerprint File\")\n*[[Guy Peellaert]] \u2013 cover art design and painting\n*[[Bob Clearmountain]] \u2013 1994 remastering\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20em;\"|Chart (1974)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|{{albumchart|Austria|3|artist=The Rolling Stones|album=It's Only Rock 'n Roll|accessdate=11 June 2016}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|Canada|5|chartid=3896a|artist=The Rolling Stones|album=It's Only Rock 'n Roll|accessdate=11 June 2016}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|Netherlands|5|artist=The Rolling Stones|album=It's Only Rock 'n Roll|accessdate=11 June 2016}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|Norway|3|artist=The Rolling Stones|album=It's Only Rock 'n Roll|accessdate=11 June 2016}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|Germany4|12|id=9033|artist=The Rolling Stones|album=It's Only Rock 'n Roll|accessdate=11 June 2016}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|UK|2|artist=Rolling Stones|album=It's Only Rock 'n Roll|refname=ukchart|accessdate=11 June 2016}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|Billboard200|1|artist=The Rolling Stones|album=It's Only Rock 'n Roll|refname=uschart|accessdate=11 June 2016}}\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Single\n!Chart\n!Position\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|1974\n|rowspan=\"5\"|\"It's Only Rock and Roll\"\n|Dutch Top 100 (MegaCharts)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=The+Rolling+Stones&titel=It%27s+Only+Rock+%27N%27+Roll&cat=s|title=The Rolling Stones- It's Only Rock and Roll|work=dutchcharts.nl|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|13\n|-\n|German Singles ([[GfK Entertainment Charts|Official German Charts]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/album-details-9033|title=Offizielle Deutsche Charts|publisher=[[GfK Entertainment Charts]]|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|12\n|-\n|Norwegian Singles (VG-lista)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://norwegiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=The+Rolling+Stones&titel=It%27s+Only+Rock+%27N%27+Roll&cat=s|title=The Rolling Stones- It's Only Rock and Roll|work=norwegiancharts.com|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|8\n|-\n|UK Singles (OCC)<ref name=\"ukchart\" />\n|align=\"center\"|10\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref name=\"uschart\" />\n|align=\"center\"|16\n|-\n|\"Ain't Too Proud to Beg\"\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref name=\"uschart\" />\n|align=\"center\"|17\n|-\n|}\n\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=album|artist=The Rolling Stones|title=It's Only Rock and Roll|award=Gold|certyear=1975|accessdate=11 June 2016}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=album|artist=The Rolling Stones|title=It's Only Rock and Roll|award=Platinum|certyear=2000|accessdate=11 June 2016}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080408104153/http://www.rollingstones.com/discog/index.php?v=a&a=1&id=10 ''It's Only Rock 'n Roll'' on RollingStones.com]\n\n{{The Rolling Stones}}\n{{The Rolling Stones albums}}\n\n[[Category:1974 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by The Glimmer Twins]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Rolling Stones Records albums]]\n[[Category:The Rolling Stones albums]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|It's Only Rock and Roll (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = It's Only Rock 'n Roll\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[the Rolling Stones]]\n| cover      = IORNRCover.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = 18 October 1974{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n| recorded   = 25 November \u2013 21 December 1972, 13\u201324 November 1973, 14\u201328 January, 10\u201315 April, 20\u201325 May 1974\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Rock and roll]]\n* [[blues rock]]\n* [[funk rock]]<ref name=\"Rivadavia\">{{cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/rolling-stones-its-only-rock-n-roll/|title=How the Rolling Stones Returned to the Fundamentals on 'It's Only Rock 'n' Roll'|first=Eduardo|last=Rivadavia|website=Ultimate Classic Rock}}</ref>}}\n| length     = 48:26\n| label      = [[Rolling Stones Records|Rolling Stones]]\n| producer   = [[Jagger/Richards]]<br />(credited as The Glimmer Twins)\n| prev_title = [[Goats Head Soup]]\n| prev_year  = 1973\n| next_title = [[Black and Blue]]\n| next_year  = 1976\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = It's Only Rock 'n Roll\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[It's Only Rock 'n Roll (But I Like It)]]\n | single1date = 26 July 1974\n | single2     = [[Ain't Too Proud to Beg]]\n | single2date = 25 October 1974\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''It's Only Rock 'n Roll''''' is the 12th British and 14th American studio album by [[the Rolling Stones]], released on 18 October 1974. It was the last Rolling Stones album for guitarist [[Mick Taylor]] and the songwriting and recording of the album's title track had a connection to Taylor's eventual replacement, [[Ronnie Wood]]. The album also marked the 10th anniversary since the release of the band's debut album, [[The Rolling Stones (album)|''The Rolling Stones'']]. ''It's Only Rock 'n Roll'' combines the core [[British blues|blues]] and [[rock 'n' roll]]-oriented sound with elements of [[funk]] and [[reggae]].<ref name=\"Rivadavia\">{{cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/rolling-stones-its-only-rock-n-roll/|title=How the Rolling Stones Returned to the Fundamentals on 'It's Only Rock 'n' Roll'|first=Eduardo|last=Rivadavia|website=Ultimate Classic Rock}}</ref> ''It's Only Rock 'n Roll'' reached number one in the United States and number two in the UK.\n\nThough it wasn't as successful as their prior albums, ''It's Only Rock 'n Roll'' was an important transitional album for the Rolling Stones.  Long-time producer [[Jimmy Miller]] was out, and the album was self-produced by guitarist [[Keith Richards]] and singer [[Mick Jagger]] under the pseudonym \"[[The Glimmer Twins]]\".  Guitarist [[Mick Taylor]] missed the initial recording sessions with health problems, and ended up quitting the Rolling Stones a few months after the album's release.  The rest of the instrumentation included bassist [[Bill Wyman]] and drummer [[Charlie Watts]], as well as frequent collaborators [[Ian Stewart (musician)|Ian Stewart]], [[Nicky Hopkins]], and [[Billy Preston]], and featured the first appearance of percussionist [[Ray Cooper]], who would continue to work with the Rolling Stones into the 1980s.\n\nThe [[It's Only Rock 'n Roll (But I Like It)|title track]] bears special note as it was recorded separately from the rest of the album.  The basic rhythm track had been laid down by members of the [[Faces (band)|Faces]], including rhythm guitarist [[Ronnie Wood]] and drummer [[Kenney Jones]] during a jam session with Mick Jagger, [[David Bowie]], and bassist [[Willie Weeks]].  Jagger liked the song so much, he brought the basic track to Richards, who added some guitar overdubs, and after some polishing, was put on the album as-is.  After Taylor left the Rolling Stones at the end of 1974, the band would approach Wood to become a full-time member.\n\n==History==\nWork began on ''It's Only Rock 'n Roll'' following the Rolling Stones' autumn [[The Rolling Stones 1973 European Tour|1973 European tour]]. Production began in November at [[Munich]], [[Germany]]'s [[Musicland Studios]]. According to guitarist [[Keith Richards]], \"We were really hot (off the road) and ready just to play some new material.\"<ref name=\"RS 175\">{{cite web|last=Turner|first=Steve|title=Making The Stones' New Album|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/making-the-stones-new-album-19741205|work=Rolling Stone Magazine No. 175|accessdate=26 November 2012|date=5 December 1974}}</ref> The recording sessions were attended by Belgian painter [[Guy Peellaert]], who [[Mick Jagger]] invited to do the album cover after seeing his work in the book ''Rock Dreams'', which featured illustrations of various rock musicians such as the Stones. Peellaert eventually painted the band as \"rock deities,\" descending a temple staircase, surrounded by young girls and women worshiping them in [[Clothing in ancient Greece|Grecian clothing]]. The artist refused to sign a deal of exclusivity, and in 1974 provided the album art for [[David Bowie]]'s ''[[Diamond Dogs]]''.<ref>[https://www.athenaart.com/its-only-rock-n-roll.html IT'S ONLY ROCK N ROLL] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022141152/https://www.athenaart.com/its-only-rock-n-roll.html |date=22 October 2016 }}, Athena Art</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Mammoth Book of the Rolling Stones: An anthology of the best writing about the greatest rock \u2018n\u2019 roll band in the world\n|first=Sean|last=Egan|page=182|publisher=Hachette|year=2013|ISBN=1-78033-647-0}}</ref>\n\n===Recording===\nThe album was at first developed as a half-live, half-studio production with one side of the album featuring live performances from the Stones' European tour while the other side was to be composed of newly recorded cover versions of the band's favourite [[R&B]] songs. Covers recorded included a take of [[Dobie Gray]]'s \"[[Drift Away]]\", [[Jimmy Reed]]'s \"Shame Shame Shame,\u201d and [[The Temptations]]' \"[[Ain't Too Proud to Beg]].\" Soon the band began working off riffs by Richards and new ideas by [[Mick Jagger]] and the original concept was scrapped in favour of an album with all-new material. The cover of \"Ain't Too Proud to Beg\" was the only recording to make the cut, while the \"Drift Away\" cover is a popular [[bootleg recording|bootleg]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stadler |first1=Gustavus |title=Cover Art |url=http://avidly.lareviewofbooks.org/2013/06/25/cover-art/ |website=Avidly |accessdate=23 April 2019 |date=25 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n''It's Only Rock 'n Roll'' marked the Stones' first effort in the producer's chair since ''[[Their Satanic Majesties Request]]'', and the first for Jagger and Richards under their pseudonym \"[[The Glimmer Twins]].\" On the choice to produce, Richards said at the time:\n\n<blockquote>\"I think we'd come to a point with [[Jimmy Miller|Jimmy (Miller)]] where the contribution level had dropped because it'd got to be a habit, a way of life, for Jimmy to do one Stones album a year. He'd got over the initial sort of excitement which you can feel on ''[[Beggars Banquet]]'' and ''[[Let It Bleed]]''. Also, Mick and I felt that we wanted to try and do it ourselves because we really felt we knew much more about techniques and recording and had our own ideas of how we wanted things to go. ''Goats Head Soup'' hadn't turned out as we wanted to \u2013 not blaming Jimmy or anything like that... But it was obvious that it was time for a change in that particular part of the process of making records.\"<ref name=\"RS 175\" /></blockquote>\n\nStarting with this release, all future Rolling Stones albums would either be produced by themselves or in collaboration with an outside producer.\n\nMost of the album's backing tracks were recorded first at Musicland; solo vocals were recorded later by Jagger, about whom Richards would say, \"he often comes up with his best stuff alone in the studio with just an engineer.\"<ref name=\"RS 175\" />\n\nThe song \"Luxury\" showed the band's growing interest in [[reggae]] music, while \"[[Till the Next Goodbye]]\" and \"If You Really Want to Be My Friend\" continued their immersion in [[ballad]]s. Seven of the album's 10 songs crack the four-minute mark, a feature that would come to be disparaged during the rising [[punk rock]] scene of the late 1970s.\n\n[[Ronnie Wood]], a long-time acquaintance of the band, began to get closer to the Rolling Stones during these sessions after he invited Mick Taylor to play on his debut album, ''[[I've Got My Own Album to Do]]''. Taylor spent some time recording and hanging out at Wood's house [[The Wick]]. By chance, Richards was asked one night by Wood's wife at the time, Krissy, to join them at the guitarist's home.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} While there, Richards recorded some tracks with Wood and quickly developed a close friendship, with Richards going as far as moving into Wood's guest room.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} Jagger soon entered the mix and it was here that the album's lead single and title track, \"[[It's Only Rock 'n Roll (But I Like It)]]\", was first recorded. Wood worked closely on the track with Jagger, who subsequently took the song and title for their album. The released version of this song features Wood on 12-string acoustic guitar.\n\n''It's Only Rock 'n Roll'' was Mick Taylor's last album with the Rolling Stones, and he played on just seven of the 10 tracks (he did not play on tracks 2, 3 or 6).{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nSimilar to receiving no writing credits on the Stones' previous album, ''Goats Head Soup'', Taylor reportedly had made songwriting contributions to \"Till the Next Goodbye\" and \"[[Time Waits for No One (song)|Time Waits for No One]],\" but on the album jacket, all original songs were credited to Jagger/Richards. Taylor said in 1997:\n\n<blockquote>\"I did have a falling out with Mick Jagger over some songs I felt I should have been credited with co-writing on ''It's Only Rock 'n Roll''. We were quite close friends and co-operated quite closely on getting that album made. By that time Mick and Keith weren't really working together as a team so I'd spend a lot of time in the studio.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Bungey|first=John|title=Hello Goodbye|url=http://www.micktaylorwemissyou.com/mojo.html|work=Issue 48|publisher=Mojo Magazine|accessdate=26 November 2012|date=November 1997}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nTaylor's statement contradicts Jagger's earlier comment concerning the album. Jagger stated in a 1995 ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' interview about \"Time Waits for No One\" that Taylor \"maybe threw in a couple of chords.\"{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nAlongside the usual outside contributors, namely [[Billy Preston]], [[Nicky Hopkins]] and unofficial member [[Ian Stewart (musician)|Ian Stewart]], [[Elton John]] sideman [[Ray Cooper]] acted as percussionist for the album. Several songs were finished songs and overdubs and mixing were performed at Jagger's home, [[Stargroves]], in the early summer of 1974.\n\n==Release and reception==\n{{Album reviews\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r16838|pure_url=yes}} link]</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies|Christgau's Record Guide]]''\n|rev2score = B<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?name=rolling+stone|title=Robert Christgau: CG: rolling stone|website=www.robertchristgau.com}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[D\u017euboks]]''\n|rev3score = (unfavourable)<ref name=\"dzuboks\">{{cite journal|last=|first=|title=It's Only Rock 'n Roll|journal=D\u017euboks|publisher=De\u010dje novine|location=Gornji Milanovac|issue=5 (second series)|page=23|language=Serbian}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[The Great Rock Discography]]''\n|rev4Score = 6/10<ref name=\"OnlyR'n'R/Acclaimed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/A324.htm|title=The Rolling Stones ''It's Only Rock 'n' Roll''|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141127214917/http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/A324.htm|archive-date=27 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|rev5 = [[MusicHound]]\n|rev5score = 3/5<ref>{{cite book|last1=Graff|first1=Gary|last2=Durchholz|first2=Daniel (eds)|title=MusicHound Rock: The Essential Album Guide|publisher=Visible Ink Press|location=Farmington Hills, MI|year=1999|isbn=1-57859-061-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781578590612/page/952 952]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9781578590612/page/952}}</ref>\n|rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n|rev6Score = 6/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cduniverse.com/productinfo.asp?pid=7911448&style=music |title=The Rolling Stones \u2013 It's Only Rock 'n' Roll CD|publisher=[[CD Universe]]/[[Muze]]|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref>\n|rev7 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n|rev7score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110412195111/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/the-rolling-stones/albumguide \"The Rolling Stones: Album Guide\"]. [[Rolling Stone|rollingstone.com]]. Archived version retrieved 15 November 2014.</ref>\n|rev8 = [[Tom Hull (critic)|Tom Hull]]\n|rev8Score = B<ref>{{cite web|last=Hull|first=Tom|authorlink=Tom Hull (critic)|date=n.d.|url=http://tomhull.com/ocston/nm/get_gl.php?n=The+Rolling+Stones|title=Grade List: The Rolling Stones|website=tomhull.com|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n|rev9 = ''[[Virgin Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n|rev9Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"OnlyR'n'R/Acclaimed\" />\n}}\nIn July 1974, the lead single, \"It's Only Rock \u2019n Roll (But I Like It),\" was released. Despite the familiar sound, it surprised many by failing to reach the top 10 in the United States (although it did reach the top 10 in the UK). With its sing-along chorus, it has become a staple at Rolling Stones concerts. The B-side \"Through the Lonely Nights\" dates back to the previous year's ''[[Goats Head Soup]]'' sessions. A cover of \"Ain\u2019t Too Proud to Beg,\" originally a 1966 hit by [[The Temptations]], was released as the second single in the United States only, where it also became a top 20 hit. Its parent album appeared in October with brisk initial sales, reaching number two in the UK (breaking a string of number-one albums that stretched back to 1969's ''[[Let It Bleed]]'') and number one in the United States, where it eventually went platinum.\n\nReviews were largely positive, with [[Jon Landau]] calling ''It's Only Rock \u2019n Roll'' \"one of the most intriguing and mysterious, as well as the darkest, of all Rolling Stones records.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Landau|first=John|title=The Rolling Stones / It's Only Rock 'n Roll|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/its-only-rock-n-roll-19741219|work=Rolling Stone Magazine No. 172|accessdate=26 November 2012|date=16 October 1974}}</ref> However rock critic [[Lester Bangs]] disparaged the album in ''[[The Village Voice]]'', much like ''Goats Head Soup'', saying, \"The Stones have become oblique in their old age, which is just another word for perverse except that perverse is the corniest concept extant as they realized at inception... ''Soup'' was friendly and safe. I want the edge and this album doesn't reassure me that I'll get it, what a curious situation to be stuck in, but maybe that's the beauty of the Stones, hah, hah, kid? This album is false. Numb. But it cuts like a dull blade. Are they doing the cutting, or are we?\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Bangs|first=Lester|title=It's Only the Rolling Stones|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jEeovH2wN9kC&pg=PA156|work=The Village Voice|accessdate=26 November 2012|date=31 October 1974}}</ref>\n\nAuthor James Hector added that ''It's Only Rock \u2019n Roll'' was a definitive turning point for the band. \"The album marked the band\u2019s decisive entry into a comfortable living as rock's elder statesmen. From this point on, their youth culture importance vanished, and there would be few musical surprises in the future.\" Hector concluded with \"On ''It's Only Rock \u2019n Roll'', the band had become what they imagined their mass audience desired them to be. They were wrong.\"<ref>{{cite book | last = Hector | first = James | authorlink =  | coauthors = | title = The Complete Guide to the Music of The Rolling Stones| publisher =Omnibus Press | year = 1995 | location = London, England | pages = 95 | doi = | id = | isbn = 0-7119-4303-6}}</ref>\n\nInstead of immediately touring to promote the album, the band decided to head back into the Munich studios to record the next album, to Mick Taylor's disappointment and subsequent resignation from the band.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} A tour didn't happen until the following summer in the United States, the \u2018[[Rolling Stones Tour of the Americas '75|Tour of the Americas '75]]\u2019, with future member Ronnie Wood taking Taylor's place on guitar.\n\nThe title track became a permanent staple of the band's live setlist, but apart from some performances of \"Ain\u2019t Too Proud to Beg\" and \"If You Can\u2019t Rock Me\" on the [[Licks Tour]], none of the other tracks have been performed since 1977. As of 2006, \"Till The Next Goodbye,\" \"Time Waits For No-One,\" \"If You Really Want To Be My Friend\" and \"Short and Curlies\" had never been played live.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocksoff.org/debuts.htm|title=ROCKS OFF SETLISTS|website=www.rocksoff.org}}</ref>\n\nIn order to promote the album, music videos were filmed for several of the songs. The most commonly seen video from the album was the one for \"It\u2019s Only Rock\u2019n\u2019Roll (But I Like It),\" featuring the band (in sailor suits) playing in a tent, which gradually fills with soap bubbles (Taylor is featured in the video but did not actually play on the recorded cut). Videos were also filmed for \"Ain\u2019t Too Proud to Beg\" and \"Till The Next Goodbye.\"\n\nIn 1994, ''It's Only Rock \u2019n Roll'' was remastered and reissued by [[Virgin Records]], in 2009 by [[Universal Music]], and once more in 2011 by [[Universal Music Enterprises]] in a Japanese-only SHM-[[Super Audio CD|SACD]] version. The 1994 remaster was initially released in a Collector's Edition CD, which replicated in miniature elements of the original vinyl album packaging.\n\nTwo different versions of \"Luxury\" exist. A shorter version (4:30) is included on the early CD version from 1986, while the 5:01 version was originally released on vinyl in Europe, and on the 1994 and 2009 CD remasters. The difference is the shorter version starts the fadeout 30 seconds earlier, and thereby missing the short guitar solo at the end.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Tracklist\n| all_writing = [[Jagger/Richards|Mick Jagger and Keith Richards]], except where noted\n| headline = Side one\n| title1   = [[If You Can't Rock Me]]\n| length1  = 3:46\n| title2   = [[Ain't Too Proud to Beg]]\n| note2    = writers: [[Norman Whitfield]], [[Eddie Holland]]\n| length2  = 3:30\n| title3   = [[It's Only Rock 'n Roll (But I Like It)]]\n| writer3    = \n| length3  = 5:07\n| title4   = [[Till the Next Goodbye]]\n| length4  = 4:37\n| title5   = [[Time Waits for No One (song)|Time Waits for No One]]\n| length5  = 6:37\n}}\n{{Tracklist\n| headline = Side two\n| title1   = Luxury\n| length1  = 5:00\n| title2   = [[Dance Little Sister (The Rolling Stones song)|Dance Little Sister]]\n| length2  = 4:11\n| title3   = If You Really Want to Be My Friend\n| length3  = 6:16\n| title4   = Short and Curlies\n| length4  = 2:43\n| title5  = [[Fingerprint File]]\n| length5 = 6:33\n}}\n\n===Other songs===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Length\n!Notes\n|-\n|\"Through the Lonely Nights\"\n|rowspan=\"1\"| 4:07\n|rowspan=\"1\"| \"It's Only Rock 'N Roll\" B-side\n|}\n\n==Personnel==\n'''The Rolling Stones'''\n*[[Mick Jagger]] \u2013 lead vocals {{small|(all tracks)}}, backing vocals {{small|(1\u20136, 9)}}, acoustic guitar {{small|(4)}}, electric guitar {{small|(10)}}\n*[[Keith Richards]] \u2013 electric guitar {{small|(all but 4)}}, backing vocals {{small|(1\u20136, 8, 9)}}, acoustic guitar {{small|(4, 8)}}, bass guitar {{small|(1)}}\n*[[Mick Taylor]] \u2013 electric guitar {{small|(1, 4, 5, 7\u20139)}}, acoustic guitar {{small|(4, 5)}}, bass guitar {{small|(10)}}\n*[[Bill Wyman]] \u2013 bass guitar {{small|(2, 4\u20139)}}, [[synthesizer]] {{small|(5, 10)}}\n*[[Charlie Watts]] \u2013 drums {{small|(all but 3)}}\n\n\n'''Additional personnel'''\n*[[Nicky Hopkins]] \u2013 piano {{small|(4\u20136, 8, 10)}}\n*[[Billy Preston]] \u2013 piano {{small|(1, 2, 10)}}, [[clavinet]] {{small|(2, 10)}}, organ {{small|(8)}}\n*[[Ian Stewart (musician)|Ian Stewart]] \u2013 piano {{small|(3, 7, 9)}}\n*[[Ray Cooper]] \u2013 percussion {{small|(1, 2, 5, 6)}}\n*[[Blue Magic (band)|Blue Magic]] \u2013 backing vocals {{small|(8)}}\n*Charlie Jolly \u2013 [[tabla]] {{small|(10)}}\n*Ed Leach \u2013 [[cowbell (instrument)|cowbell]] {{small|(2)}}\n\n'''Basic track on \"It's Only Rock 'n Roll (But I Like It)\"'''\n*[[Kenney Jones]] \u2013 drums\n*[[Willie Weeks]] \u2013 bass guitar\n*[[David Bowie]] \u2013 backing vocals\n*[[Ronnie Wood]] \u2013 twelve\u2013string acoustic guitar, backing vocals\n\n'''Production'''\n*[[Andy Johns]] \u2013 [[Audio engineering|recording engineer]]\n*[[Keith Harwood]] \u2013 recording engineer, mixing\n*George Chkiants \u2013 overdub engineer\n*[[Glyn Johns]] \u2013 mixing (on \"Fingerprint File\")\n*[[Guy Peellaert]] \u2013 cover art design and painting\n*[[Bob Clearmountain]] \u2013 1994 remastering\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20em;\"|Chart (1974)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|{{albumchart|Austria|3|artist=The Rolling Stones|album=It's Only Rock 'n Roll|accessdate=11 June 2016}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|Canada|5|chartid=3896a|artist=The Rolling Stones|album=It's Only Rock 'n Roll|accessdate=11 June 2016}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|Netherlands|5|artist=The Rolling Stones|album=It's Only Rock 'n Roll|accessdate=11 June 2016}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|Norway|3|artist=The Rolling Stones|album=It's Only Rock 'n Roll|accessdate=11 June 2016}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|Germany4|12|id=9033|artist=The Rolling Stones|album=It's Only Rock 'n Roll|accessdate=11 June 2016}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|UK|2|artist=Rolling Stones|album=It's Only Rock 'n Roll|refname=ukchart|accessdate=11 June 2016}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|Billboard200|1|artist=The Rolling Stones|album=It's Only Rock 'n Roll|refname=uschart|accessdate=11 June 2016}}\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Single\n!Chart\n!Position\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\"|1974\n|rowspan=\"5\"|\"It's Only Rock and Roll\"\n|Dutch Top 100 (MegaCharts)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=The+Rolling+Stones&titel=It%27s+Only+Rock+%27N%27+Roll&cat=s|title=The Rolling Stones- It's Only Rock and Roll|work=dutchcharts.nl|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|13\n|-\n|German S